[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Welcome!"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "3"]
[GameId "2102815302589911"]

{" The most profound thing about the English Opening is that it often isn't. " Let me explain. White opens the game with:} 1. c4 {And Black has a wide choice of set-ups at his disposal. These often transpose to other openings, leaving the English territory. For example, Black can use King's Indian, Queen's Gambit Declined, or Slav set-ups... basically, any set-up that is part of their repertoire against d4. This characteristic of maximum flexibility is something that has been the defining feature of the English Opening for me: while Black can choose their preferred set-up, White is free to employ a wide range of move orders with the idea of navigating the opening in a direction of his preference. It is possible to play the English schematically: c4, g3, Bg2 and then either Nf3 or Nc3 and so on. But I've always thought that the power of the English lies in the knowledge of precise and often tricky! move orders and their use to lure the opponent in a variation that we want to play. To make it a bit easier, in this repertoire, White always starts with c4 and Nc3 except against Black's} c5 {the Symmetrical English when} 2. Nf3 {should be played because White wants to continue with d4 on the next move. Whenever I play the English Opening, I feel like I am trying to trick my opponent into a line I want to play. At the same time, I want to avoid his intended set-up or prepared line. The following repertoire is of that sort. Against each option that Black has at his disposal, I've attempted to come up with a move order that aims to take the game in a direction where White would be the better-prepared player. This also means that often new avenues have to be explored. And you will see rare and unexpected ideas and moves being analyzed. Given its inherent flexibility, the English Opening requires precision at the early stage and extreme care when it comes to the possible transpositions and move orders.This repertoire aims to give you a roadmap for the labyrinth of these transpositions and move orders, with the hope that every time you reach the end of the opening maze, you emerge with a position you're happy to play.Good luck!} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
