[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Symmetrical English 1…c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A35"]
[PlyCount "29"]
[GameId "2102815302663640"]

1. c4 c5 {The Symmetrical English.} 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Symmetrical English when White plays an early [d4].} 5. e3 $5 {[%cal Ge3d4]} ({It has been established for quite some time that Black obtains good play after the theoretical and standard} 5. Nc3 e6 {, so this move is a fresh attempt to take the game into less explored territory. There aren't many games played in the lines that follow, which makes them an excellent territory to spring a surprise on the unsuspecting opponent. Black has a wide choice now.}) 5... g6 {Black plans the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop.} ({In this position, the move} 5... e5 {is rare at master level, as after} 6. Nb5 {White threatens [Nd6]. Still, with precise moves after} Bb4+ 7. N1c3 d6 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 Bg4 $1 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 d5 {Black frees his play. But there are still problems to solve after} 12. O-O dxc4 13. Qxc4 O-O 14. Rd1 {followed by [Qb3], [Bd2]-[e1]. In this type of position, White: 🔹has some initiative on the queenside where he can also consider advancing the pawns; and,🔹his bishop can potentially be a stronger piece than either of Black's knights.}) 6. Nc3 {Natural development for White.} Bg7 7. Qb3 $1 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gb3d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] A very important move! White must stop ...[d5].} ({The other way to do so after} 7. Nc2 {is also possible, leading to a complex middlegame after} O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O {, when White wants to play [e4] and establish a Maróczy bind in the center.}) 7... O-O ({Pushing ...d5 would be a pawn sacrifice as after} 7... d5 8. cxd5 Nxd4 9. exd4 O-O 10. Bc4 {, White safely defends the pawn on [d5] and Black needs to find compensation for the pawn.}) 8. Be2 {[%cal Be1g1,Gf1d1,Gd1d8,Gh1d1] White wants to castle, place a rook on [d1] in order to discourage ...[d5] and then move the queen from [b3] to allow the development of the dark-squared bishop with [b3] and [Bb2].} b6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc8b7,Rc6d4,Rd7d5,Gb7d5] Black plans ...[Bb7], ...[Nxd4] and eventually ...[d5].} ({The more standard plan with} 8... d6 {doesn't solve Black's problems after} 9. O-O Nd7 10. Qd1 {with [b3] and [Bb2] next: White keeps the space advantage as Black didn't manage to play ...[d5].}) 9. O-O Bb7 10. Rd1 {[%cal Gd1d8,Gd4c6] White continues with the plan. Now the idea is to take on [c6] when Black cannot recapture with a pawn and keep the pawn symmetry.} Nxd4 {[%cal Rd7d5] Black also continues with the plan to liberate his play with ...[d5].} 11. exd4 {[%csl Bc4,Bd4][%cal Rd7d5] White cannot stop ...[d5].} ({After} 11. Rxd4 {Black is slightly better:} e6 12. Rd1 Qe7 {with ...[d5] next.}) 11... d5 12. c5 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gb3b7] Thanks to the pin on the [b6]-pawn, White can push [c5] and obtain a pawn majority on the queenside.} Bc6 13. cxb6 ({A good alternative is} 13. Qa3 {with the idea [b4]} bxc5 14. Qxc5 {when White's play again is on the queenside.}) 13... Qxb6 14. Bf4 {[%csl Bb8,Be5][%cal Gf4b8] The bishop is very well-placed on the [h2]-[b8] diagonal. It controls the [e5]-square so Black cannot push [e5] and the [b8]-square, ensuring Black doesn't get to use the semi-open b-file. This also lures Black to take on [b3] and double White's pawns.} Qxb3 15. axb3 {[%csl Ya7][%cal Ga1a8,Ga1a5,Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Gd1a1] The doubled pawns gave White the a-file. 💡The initiative White has on the queenside cannot easily be extinguished: 🔹we have the possibility to advance with [b4]-[b5] ; 🔹ideas like [Ra5] and doubling on the a-file should be considered.} *

