1. c4 c5 {The symmetrical English.} 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Symmetrical English when White plays an early [d4].} 5. e3 $5 ({It has been established for quite some time that Black obtains good play after the theoretical and standard} 5. Nc3 e6 {, so this move is a fresh attempt to take the game into less explored territory. There aren't many games played in the lines that follow, which makes them an excellent territory to spring a surprise on the unsuspecting opponent. Black has a wide choice now.}) 5... e6 {This position can also arise via the move order 4...e6 5.e3 Nc6 6.Be2} 6. Be2 {White postpones the development of the knight on [b1] in order not to allow the pin after [Nc3] [Bb4].} Bb4+ {[%csl Re1,Gb1][%cal Rb4e1]} ({After} 6... d5 7. Nxc6 bxc6 8. Qc2 {we have a transposition to the lines after 5...d5 6.Nxc6 bxc6 7.Be2 , mentioned as a clickable in the comment to Black's 7th move.}) ({Other moves are also possible, for example} 6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 {White intends [b3] and [Bb2] with a comfortable position that can further be improved by [Qd2], [Rfd1] and [Rac1];} ({Nxd4 exd4 gives White a space advantage in the center; Bc5} 8. Nc3 {O-O O-O with [b3] and [Bb2] to come is similar to the clickable mentioned above, while if Black wants to free his play with} d5 {then after} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. b3 {is a standard position where White has to play against Black's [c6]-[d5] pawns.})) 7. Bd2 {Naturally, White won't pin the knight voluntarily with [Nc3].} Bxd2+ {[%csl Re1] The most forcing.} ({In case of} 7... Bc5 8. Bc3 {White intends [Nxc6] and [b4], to grab space on the queenside...}) ({... while} 7... Be7 8. Bc3 Ne4 9. O-O Nxc3 10. Nxc3 {wins the bishop pair for Black, but it fails to free the position as White maintains the space advantage and central control after [Qc2] or d2, [Rfd1], [Rac1].}) 8. Nxd2 ({Taking with the queen is a good alternative. For example} 8. Qxd2 Ne4 9. Qd3 Qa5+ 10. Kf1 Nc5 11. Qc3 Qxc3 12. Nxc3 {when White has a space advantage in the endgame.}) 8... Nxd4 ({Or} 8... O-O 9. O-O d5 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. b4 {, activating the queenside majority.}) 9. exd4 Qb6 {[%csl Yb2,Yd4][%cal Rb6b2,Rb6d4]} 10. Nb3 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd1d3,Gb3d2] White defends both pawns and keeps the space advantage thanks to the pawn pair on [c4] and [d4]. 💡White's plan is to: 🔹castle; and, 🔹then find a way to advance with the queenside pawns. You may explore three ideas: play [Qd3] to cover the [d4]-pawn; [Nd2]; and, organize [b4] the pawn on [b2] is taboo as [Qxb2], [Rfb1] would trap the black queen. 10...Qb4+ is met by 11.Qd2 Qxd2+ 12.Nxd2} *

