1. c4 c5 {The symmetrical English.} 2. Nf3 {White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nc6 {Here we will take a look at the lines where Black doesn't play ...[Nf6] early on.} 3. d4 {White continues with the plan.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 e5 {[%csl Yd5] An attempt to be active in the center, but weakening the [d5]-square.} ({The move} 4... e6 5. e4 Nf6 6. Nc3 {transposes to the chapter The Flexible Nf6 and more specifically to the lines '2... [e6] with [c5]' after the moves: 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4}) {Another transposition is 4...Nf6 5.e3 which is analyzed via the move order: 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.e3} 5. Nc2 ({The alternative is} 5. Nb5 {, but from [c2] the knight can come to [e3] to further increase the control of the [d5]-square. Note that taking on [c6] is far from ideal, as both recaptures on [c6] give Black good play – ...[bxc6] strengthens the center, while ....[dxc6] solves the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop.}) 5... Nf6 ({White's play is the same in case of} 5... f5 6. Nc3 Nf6 7. g3 {followed by [Bg2], [O-O] and then an occupation of the [d5]-square by [Ne3]-[d5], combined with a strengthening of the position with [b3], [Ba3] or in case Black plays ...[Bc5] White will offer the exchange of bishops with [Be3].}) 6. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5,Gd1d5] White continues development and controls the [d5]-square.} Bc5 {The bishop is more active on [c5].} ({In case of} 6... d6 7. g3 {followed by [Bg2], [O-O], [b3] and then [Ne3]-[d5], [Ba3] with pleasant pressure on Black's position, the [d6]-pawn and the [d5]-square in particular.}) 7. g3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gf1g2,Gg2d5] White's development is simple as he concentrates on control of the light squares in the centre, especially the [d5]-square.} ({This gives easy and straight-forward play, which is simpler than the alternative} 7. Be3 Qb6 {.}) 7... d6 ({In case of} 7... O-O 8. Bg2 d6 9. b3 {we will likely have a transposition to the line after 7...[d6]}) (7... Ng4 8. e3 {renders the knight on [g4] useless.}) 8. Bg2 Be6 {[%cal Re6c4]} 9. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4] White defends the pawn on [c4] and plays a move that falls into his plan.} O-O 10. O-O {[%csl Yd5,Bd6][%cal Gc1e3,Ge3g5,Gg5f6,Ga1c1,Gf1d1,Gd1d2] White almost finished development. 💡What's our plan? 🔹next comes [Be3] or [Bg5xf6], eliminating a defender of the weak [d5]-square; and then, 🔹Qd2, [Rfd1] with very pleasant play on the d-file, where there are easy targets: Black's backward pawn on [d6] and the weak [d5]-square.} *

