1. c4 e5 {The reversed Sicilian.} 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} Bb4 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Rb4c3,Rf6e4] This is the most common move for Black and the main line.} ({The move} 4... g6 {allows} 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bd2 {with [O-O-O] and [f4] to come.}) {White obtains a similar position to the one from the variation 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4 Bg7 6.Nxc6 dxc6 7.Qxd8 Kxd8 8.Bg5 Ke8 9.O-O-O when the plan is to advance with the kingside majority.} 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White defends the [e4]-pawn, fending off the threat of ...[Bxc3] and ...[Nxe4].} ({A curious alternative worth exploring is} 5. Bd3 $5 {.}) 5... d6 6. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White will castle and then will continue depending on Black's responses.} O-O 7. O-O {[%csl Bd5,Bf5][%cal Gd3d4,Gf2f4,Gf3e1,Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3d5,Bf3d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Ge3f5] Generally speaking, White has two main and one minor idea in the position: the main ideas are the pawn breaks [d4] and [f4], while the minor idea is the transfer of the knight to the [d5]-square by [Ne1]-[c2]-[e3] or [Nd2]-[f1]-[e3]. The ensuing variations evolve around the implementation of these ideas. Black has several options now.} h6 {[%cal Gf6h7,Rf7f5] With this move Black intends a quick ...[f5] after ...[Nh7].} 8. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] Black is faster with ...[f5] than White can be with either [f4] or [d4], so White goes after the bishop pair.} Bxc3 9. bxc3 Nh7 {[%cal Rf7f5]} 10. Be3 {[%cal Gc4c5] White completes the development. The bishop on [e3] will support the [c5]-push, which would rid White of the doubled c-pawns.} f5 {[%cal Rf5f4] Black executes the plan.} ({In case of} 10... b6 {to stop [c5] as in the line after the immediate f5} 11. Re1 {freeing the [f1]-square for the knight – White doesn't forget the minor idea, to transfer the knight to [e3] and then possibly to [d5]} f5 12. exf5 Bxf5 13. d4 e4 14. Nd2 Nf6 15. Bf4 $1 {with further [Nf1]-[e3] and [Bg3], when White has a very solid position with the bishop pair as a long-term advantage.}) 11. exf5 {The threat was ...[f4], so White must take on [f5].} Bxf5 12. c5 $1 {[%csl Yb7,Yg8][%cal Gc5d6,Gd1b3,Gb3g8,Gb3b7] An important move that allows White to get rid of the doubled pawns. An additional threat is the check [Qb3], hitting the pawn on [b7].} Kh8 {Black's king gets out of the sensitive diagonal.} ({The move} 12... d5 {is met by} 13. d4 e4 14. Ne5 $1 {and after the exchange of knights} Nxe5 15. dxe5 {White will continue to the attack the center with [c4].}) 13. cxd6 {White now doesn't have an inferior pawn structure, as both sides have 3 pawn islands.} cxd6 14. c4 ({It's also possible to push the other pawn,} 14. d4 e4 15. Nd2 Nf6 16. c4 d5 17. Rc1 {with a complex middlegame.}) 14... Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} 15. h3 {[%csl Bg4][%cal Gh3g4,Ga1c1,Gd3d4,Ra8c8] Covering the [g4]-square and defending against ...[Ng4]. As soon as the players have placed their rooks on the c-file, White will complete development and have the bishop pair in a complex middlegame position: 💡The plan would be: 🔹to push [d4]; and, 🔹after ...[e4], [Nd2] to play (if allowed) d5, 🔹with [Nb3]-[d4] to come. See the whole variation here.} *

