[ECO "A21"]
[PlyCount "27"]
[GameId "2102815302778333"]

1. c4 e5 {The reversed Sicilian.} 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4c3,Gg8e7,Gg8f6,Rf7f5] This move became popular thanks to Anand's efforts from 2016 and has remained popular ever since. Black wants to take on [c3] and double White's c-pawns but also keeps flexibility by postponing the development of the knight on [g8] - it can go to [f6], but also to [e7], when it's easier to follow up with ...[f5].} 3. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gb3c3]} ({The main move with a well-developed theory is} 3. Nd5 {. With the queen move, White attacks the bishop on [b4] while at the same time preventing the doubling of the c-pawns.}) 3... Nc6 {[%cal Gc6b4,Rc6d4] The most natural reply, defending the bishop and threatening [Nd4] when the bishop cannot be taken in view of the fork [Nc2].} ({Taking on c3 just gives White the bishop pair. For example} 3... Bxc3 4. Qxc3 d6 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nf3 {followed by [Be2] and [O-O].}) ({There would be a similar play after} 3... a5 4. a3 Bxc3 5. Qxc3 d6 6. b3 {followed by [e3], [d3], [Bb2], [Nf3] and [Be2]. In both cases, White obtains a safe and compact position with the pair of bishops when the general plan is to advance on the queenside with [b4].}) 4. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White covers the [d4]-square.} Nf6 5. Nge2 {[%csl Bd5,Be4,Bf5][%cal Ge2c3,Gc3d5,Ge2g3,Gg3e4,Gg3f5] The knight is flexible on [e2]. It is ready to replace the other one on [c3] in case Black takes it; otherwise, it will go to [g3] from where it controls the [f5] and [e4] squares.} O-O 6. a3 Bxc3 ({This is better than retreating. In case of} 6... Be7 7. Ng3 d6 8. Qc2 {with [Be2], [O-O] and [b4] to come, White has play on the queenside.}) ({Similar is} 6... Bc5 7. Ng3 d6 8. Qc2 {when White plays along the same lines.}) 7. Nxc3 Ne7 {[%cal Gc7c6,Rd7d5] This somewhat unnatural plan is Black's best. Black prepares ...[c6] and ...[d5].} ({After a neutral move like} 7... Re8 8. d3 d6 9. Be2 {White castles and then will combine play in the center with [d4] prepared by [Rd1], for example and play on the queenside with [b4]-[b5] etc. Another idea for White is to play [e4] and then either expand in the center with [d4] or on the kingside with [f4].}) 8. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White completes the development of the kingside.} c6 {[%cal Rd7d5]} 9. O-O Re8 {[%cal Rd7d5] This is very precise. The point of the move is that it's a useful one for Black, waiting to see what White will do.} ({In case of the immediate} 9... d5 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. d4 e4 12. Bd2 {White continues with [Rfc1], [a4]-[a5] with smooth play on the queenside.}) 10. d4 ({White could insist on a closed type of position with something like} 10. Qc2 d5 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. d4 e4 13. Bd2 {with [Rfc1], but compared to the clickable in the note to Black's 9th move, the queen is worse on [c2] here than it is on [b3] there.}) 10... exd4 11. exd4 d5 12. Bg5 {[%csl Be2,Bg5][%cal Ga1d1,Gg5d8] White develops freely. He has an active position with the pair of bishops.} Nf5 {[%cal Rf5d4]} 13. Rad1 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gg5d8,Gc4d5,Gc3d5,Gb3d5] The threat is to take on [d5] since the knight on [f6] is pinned. After} h6 14. Bf4 {[%csl Bf4,Be2][%cal Gc3d5,Gb3b7,Gb3d5,Gd1d8] 💡We can set the stage for a dynamic middlegame, thanks to: 🔹White's pair of bishops; 🔹the active placement of the queen on [b3]; 🔹combined with the pressure on the queenside and in the center.} *

