1. c4 e6 {A Queen's Gambit Declined's set-up.} 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6.}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Be7 ({The move} 4... c6 {would transpose to the chapter on the Slav Defense.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The standard development for White in this variation.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {[%cal Rd5d4] The main move for Black, threatening ...[d4].} 7. cxd5 {White avoids the threat of ...[d4] by taking on [d5]. Now White keeps taking on [d5] until a pawn lands on [d5], when he follows up with [d4], aiming for positions with an IQP.} exd5 8. d4 {[%csl Bd5] White's standard reaction, fixing the pawn on [d5].} ({An interesting alternative is to delay the d4 move and play} 8. Rc1 Nc6 9. Na4 {, attacking the pawn on [c5]. After} b6 10. d4 {White has certain pressure on [d5], which sooner or later will lead: 🔹either to a position with an IQP after Black takes on [d4] or White on [c5] and Black recaptures with a piece; 🔹or to a position with a hanging pawn in case of [dxc5] [bxc5].}) 8... Nc6 9. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White prepares short castle.} Ne4 {This is Black's most active reply.} ({Against other moves, the play will be standard for positions with an IQP, for example} 9... Bg4 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. O-O {, or 9...cxd4 10.Nxd4 Bc5 11.Nxc6 bxc6 12.O-O . In case of 9...b6 10.O-O Be6 11.Bb5 Rc8 12.Ne2! White is comfortably placed to put pressure on Black's center after [Nf4].}) 10. O-O {White completes development.} Bf6 {[%csl Yc3,Yd4][%cal Rf6b2,Rc5d4] This is Black's idea, the bishop on [f6] together with the knights on [c6] and [e4] put pressure on White's targets on [d4] and [c3].} 11. Na4 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ga4c5,Ga4b2,Gb2d4] A multi-purpose move, White avoids the attack on the knight on [c3] and the pin on the long diagonal by defending the bishop on [b2], attacks the [c5]-pawn and increases control over the [d4]-square.} Bg4 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Rg4f3,Yf3d4,Rc5d4,Rf6d4,Rc6d4] The battle is about control of the [d4]-square. Black attacks the knight on [f3], which defends the pawn on [d4].} ({In case of} 11... cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bd7 13. Rc1 {there is still a lot of tension between the pieces, but White stabilized the control of the blockading [d4]-square.}) 12. Rc1 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gc1c5,Ga4c5] Attacking the [c5]-pawn.} cxd4 {Black can no longer sustain the tension and is forced to exchange on d4 . Taking on f3 loses a pawn after 12...Bxf3? 13.gxf3! with Nxc5 next.} 13. Nxd4 {[%csl Bd4] White won the battle for control of the [d4]-square. Nevertheless, there is counterplay for Black, as we shall see below.} Bxe2 14. Nxe2 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gd1d4,Ge2d4,Rf6b2,Ga4b2,Rd8a5] Still controlling the [d4]-square. 💡Now let's discuss the position: 🔹Our knight on the rim blocks the queenside, but Black has some activity. 🔹The isolated queen pawn will be a major theme for the rest of the game. See the whole variation here.} *

