1. c4 c6 {A Slav system. It might be called a 'Caro-Kann Defensive System' as well.} 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} e6 {The Semi-Slav option.} ({Of all the options mentioned, the move} 4... Bf5 $6 {is the worst because after} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {puts Black under immediate pressure, the pawns on [b7] and [d5] are under attack. Black's best is} Bc8 {, but after} 7. Ne5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. f4 {, White has a pleasant advantage as he can continue to play on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4] etc. or on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.}) ({Another sub-optimal move is} 4... dxc4 $6 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O {with [e4] and [d4] to come, when White obtains excellent play in the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {Now that the black knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: one is to push ...[e5] and the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} Re8 {[%cal Re6e5] The most common move at the master level.} ({The immediate} 8... e5 9. cxd5 cxd5 $6 10. Nb5 Bb8 11. Rc1 {with [Nc7] is excellent for White. Taking on [d5] with the knight is better and would lead to similar positions to the ones analyzed in the variation 4...Nbd7 5.Qc2 e5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.a3 Bd6 8.Be2 where White has already fianchettoed the dark-squared bishop.}) 9. O-O {White castles since Black doesn't control the [b5]-square, so the advance ...[e5] can be met by [cxd5], forcing Black to recapture with a knight.} b6 {With the white king already on g1, Black doesn't fear an attack with g4 like in the line: 8...b6 9.Rg1! , so it's possible to switch to the plan with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop.} 10. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gb2a3] A new move and a novel plan. White uses the a-pawn to cause problems by advancing it as far as possible in true Leela Chess Zero-style.} a5 {Stopping White's plan.} ({In case of} 10... Bb7 11. a5 bxa5 12. d4 {, White has good compensation for the pawn since both Black's pawns on the a-file are weak and subject to attacks.}) ({After} 10... c5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb5 Bb8 13. a5 {, White has initiative on the queenside and at some point will play [d4], to fix Black's [d5]-pawn.}) 11. Nd4 {[%csl Yc6,Be5][%cal Gd4c6,Gf2f4,Gf4e5] This is another original idea. White wins a tempo by attacking the pawn on [c6] so that he can advance with the f-pawn to stop Black's ...[e5] advance.} Bb7 12. f4 {[%csl Be5,Bb5][%cal Ga1d1,Gd2d4,Gd4f5,Bd4f3,Bf3e5,Gc4d5,Gc3b5,Gf1f8] White's control of the [e5]-square discourages Black's ...[e5] advance, as that would open the f-file after [fxe5] and weaken the [f5]-square, which White can use after [Nf5]. 💡White's ideas are : 🔹Rad1, [Nf3]-[e5] followed by [d4], or in some cases even [g4]-[g5]; 🔹the capture [cxd5] would either gain access to the [b5]-square after ...[cxd5], or the [f5]-square after ...[exd5], so it should be timed accurately.} *

