1. c4 c6 {Black favors a Slav / Caro-Kann system.} 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} Bg4 {[%cal Re7e6,Rg4d1] This move works nicely with a white pawn on [d4] without a knight on [c3]. In this case, White can pose more concrete problems thanks to the lead in development.} 5. cxd5 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gd1b3,Gb3b7,Gb3d5] White releases the tension, opens the [f1]-[a6] diagonal for the bishop the move [Bb5] is an important idea for White and intends to play [Qb3], immediately taking advantage of the weakness of the pawn on [b7].} ({If White plays} 5. Qb3 {, then after} Qb6 {Black will recapture with a knight on [d5] when White takes at a later stage.}) 5... Bxf3 $1 {Black must take on [f3] in this particular moment to prevent White's idea of [Qb3].} ({In case of} 5... cxd5 $6 6. Qb3 $1 Bc8 7. Ne5 {, we have the same position and a transposition to the position after 4...Bf5?! 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 Bc8 , where White has a stable advantage.}) ({Taking with the knight is inferior as} 5... Nxd5 $6 6. d4 {allows White to take over the center after a subsequent preparation of [e4].}) 6. Qxf3 cxd5 7. Bb5+ {[%csl Re8] A positional approach.} ({The aggressive} 7. g4 $5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. Bd3 {with [g5] and [h4] to come is also possible.}) 7... Nc6 8. Bxc6+ {[%csl Re8] White immediately saddles Black with a backward pawn on the c-file.} bxc6 9. b3 {[%csl Bc5,Yc6][%cal Gc1b2,Ga1c1,Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gc1c5] White's play is simple. After [Bb2] freeing the [c1]-square for a rook White will aim to place a rook on the c-file and continue with [Na4], targeting the backward pawn on [c6] and the weak square in front of it.} e5 ({This is more active than} 9... e6 {, which wouldn't alter White's plan to go for} 10. Bb2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 {followed by [Rac1] and a possible doubling of the rooks on the c-file.}) 10. Bb2 {White continues with the plan.} Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rac1 {[%csl Bc5,Yc6][%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gc1c2,Gc2c6,Gf3e2,Gf1c1] Simple chess, again. It's worth noting that Black's pawn center is largely inoffensive because the exchange of a pair of light pieces has decreased the dynamic potential in the position, thus not allowing Black to create threats on the kingside after, for example, a possible ...[e4]. 💡Here are some guidelines: 🔹we would like the c-rook to shift on the [c2]-square with the idea of doubling our “towers” on the c-file; 🔹the queen can retreat to [e2] to prepare [e4] (if allowed) and to control the [f1]-[a6] diagonal, to target the [a7]- and the [c6]-pawns. In the continuation of this line, Black plays [e4] himself and attempts queen activity on the kingside. The variation ends in this position: See the whole variation here.} *

