[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "The Dutch 1…f5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A10"]
[PlyCount "26"]
[GameId "2102815302995430"]

1. c4 f5 {White faces the Dutch Defense.} 2. Nc3 Nf6 ({After} 2... e5 3. d4 {, we have a transposition to the line analyzed in the chapter The Reversed Sicilian 1...e5 after 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 f5 3.d4 , mentioned as a clickable in the comments to Black's 2nd move.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf3e5] White stops the immediate ...[e5]. In the Dutch, Black needs to choose which iteration of the opening to play: 🔹the Leningrad Dutch which has the dark-squared bishop fianchettoed on [g7]; 🔹the Stonewall which places the pawns on light squares on [e6], [d5] and [c6]; or, 🔹the Classical, which develops the dark-squared bishop on [e7] or [b4] and aims for the [e5] push. In this position, Black already has to make the choice.} e6 {This move indicates that Black will either play the Stonewall with ...[d5] next, or the Classical with ...[Be7] or ...[Bb4].} 4. d3 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge2e3,Ge3e4] White anticipates ...[Bb4] so that it can be met by [Bd2], while preparing a possible [e4] in the center.} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4c3,Rd7d6,Re6e5] This move is played in the Classical line of the Dutch.} ({Here, it's a must if Black wants to play it, because the alternative} 4... Be7 $6 {allows} 5. e4 $1 {and White has taken over the center.}) ({Other moves like} 4... b6 $6 5. e4 $1 {and 4...g6?! 5.e4 are similarly impossible.}) 5. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2c3] White avoids a possible doubling of the pawns after ...[Bxc3].} O-O {[%cal Rd7d6,Re6e5,Rf5f4,Gd8e8,Re8g6,Rg6h5] Black wants to continue with [d6] and [e5] and then hopefully create threats on the kingside with the help of the queen maneuver [Qe8]-[g6] h5 and [f4].} 6. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1] White develops in reversed Scheveningen fashion with [Be2] and [O-O].} ({The alternative is to fianchetto the bishop after} 6. g3 {, but in those lines, it's more difficult to prevent Black's kingside play based on ...[f4].}) 6... Nc6 {[%cal Rd7d6,Re6e5] Black develops and will continue with ...[d6] and ...[e5].} 7. Be2 d6 8. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] Now that after ...[d6] the bishop cannot retreat White forces its exchange.} Bxc3 ({Retreating only helps White's planned queenside expansion with} 8... Ba5 $6 9. b4 Bb6 10. Na4 {.}) 9. Bxc3 {[%cal Gc3h8] The dark-squared bishop is unopposed and very strong on the long [a1]-[h8] diagonal. Black will close that diagonal with the next move, but White has ways to fight for its opening.} e5 10. O-O {[%csl Be5][%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Gd3d4,Gd4e5,Gf3e5] White completed development. The main plan is to advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5] and possibly in the center with [d4], but before that White needs to keep under wraps Black's plan to create activity on the kingside.} Qe8 {[%csl Yg2][%cal Ge8g6,Rf5f4,Rc8h3,Rg6g2] Black plans ...[Qg6], ...[f4] and possibly ...[Bh3].} 11. Nd2 $1 {[%csl Be5,Bf5][%cal Gf2f4,Gf4e5,Gc3e5,Gc8f5,Gf5f4] This is an important move for White. It avoids [Qh5] just in case, but more importantly, it prepares the advance of the f-pawn to [f4]. The pawn on [f4] has a double function: 🔹it blocks Black's [f5]-pawn, thus rendering the bishop on [c8] passive by looking at its own pawn on [f5] and preventing any activity after [f4]; 🔹and it also attacks the [e5]-pawn and gives the [c3]-bishop a purpose by attacking it.} Bd7 ({Pushing} 11... f4 $6 {is premature, as} 12. exf4 exf4 13. Bf3 {opens both long diagonals for White's bishops. With [Re1], [Qa4] or [d4]-[d5] next White controls the whole board.}) ({White's idea is clearly seen after} 11... Qg6 12. f4 $1 {and Black's kingside play comes to a standstill. Further attacks after} Ng4 13. Rf3 {are futile as White continues with [Nf1] and [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and when that pawn moves from [e5], either by pushing ...[e4] or taking on [f4], White will open the long diagonal with [d5] with the tremendous bishop on [c3] giving him control over the position.}) 12. Qb3 {[%csl Be5,Yb7][%cal Gb3b7,Ga1e1,Gf2f4,Gf4e5,Gc3h8]} ({White shouldn't rush with} 12. d4 e4 13. d5 $6 Ne5 {as the knight on [e5] effectively blocks the bishop on [c3]. Therefore, White concentrates on the [f4] advance, aimed at putting pressure on the [e5]-pawn with the ultimate goal of removing it from that square and opening the long diagonal for the unopposed dark-squared bishop.}) 12... b6 13. Rae1 {[%csl Be2,Bc3][%cal Gf1f4,Gf1f8,Ge1e8] 💡What ideas come to mind? 🔹White is ready to push [f4] next. 🔹With a pawn on [f4], the advance of [d4] with the idea of} d5 {is also possible, because the [f4]-pawn controls the [e5]-square, thus not allowing Black to close the long diagonal by Ne5. White has the pair of bishops and clear play in the center, while Black's main plan of kingside activity has effectively been stopped.} *

