{To prepare against 1...b6, you have to study The English Defense's chapter. And to train the three other lines, go to the chapter on these Rare Tries.} 1. c4 {⭐ 1... [b6] – The English Defense 1...b6 The English Defense against the English Opening is not a very bad idea. 2.Nc3 Bb7 3.e4 We will play in a Botvinnik-style setup with [d3] and [g3] e6 4.Nge2 Nf6 5.d3 c5 6.g3 ⭐ 1...[d5] with 2...Qxd5} (1. c4 d5 {the Anglo-Scandinavian Defense} 2. cxd5 Qxd5 3. Nc3 Qa5 4. d4 e5 5. dxe5 Qxe5 6. Nf3 Qd6 7. Qc2) ({⭐ 1...[d5] with 2...Nf6} 1. c4 d5 {the Anglo-Scandinavian Defense} 2. cxd5 Nf6 3. d4 c6 4. dxc6 Nxc6 5. Nf3 e5 6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Ng4 8. Ke1) ({⭐ 1...Nc6} 1. c4 Nc6 {the Anglo-Lithuanian variation} 2. Nc3 e6 3. e3 d5 4. Nf3 d4 5. exd4 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3) *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction: The Symmetrical English 1…c5"]
[Black "Introduction: The Symmetrical English 1…c5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A32"]
[PlyCount "9"]
[GameId "2102815303032296"]

{5.e3 !? The main idea of this move is to delay the development of the knight on [b1] in order to avoid the [Bb4]-pin and to let Black show his plans. In many lines, White seeks positions where he plays against an IQP and these positions are ideal outcomes from the opening as they offer a safe position with good long-term prospects. These positions are often encountered in the other chapters of this course and are ones I've actively sought to obtain, serving as the basis of our repertoire.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Against the Symmetrical English, White has two possible plans: 🔹one is to develop with [Nc3], [g3] followed by [Bg2]; 🔹and the other is to play in the center with [d4]. I chose the latter option i.e. after both 2...Nf6 or 2...Nc6 , we play 3.d4 . There are two reasons for this: ( First, in the lines with 2.g3 , the play is less forcing. It gives Blacks greater flexibility to plot their plans. Black can copy White with the fianchetto, with a plethora of options for deciding when to stop the symmetry. Or he can play in the center with ...[Nf6] followed by ...[d5], with ...[Nc6] and ...[e5], or with ...[e6] after which Black disputes the center with ...[d5]. Second, in the more direct lines with [d4], I managed to find a rare idea based on the move e3 that allows White to obtain more original play. )} Nf6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 e6 5. e3 $5 {[%csl Gb1]} ({This is the 'small' idea that is like a breath of fresh air in these positions. It works against most of Black's set-ups, making it universal and easy to remember. It has long been established that} 5. Nc3 Bb4 {is very good for Black, as is 5...Nc6 . Both these moves are very deeply explored and instead of trying to find a small subtlety down the theoretical lines, I thought that it's much more practical to spring a surprise early on.}) *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) The Symmetrical English 1…c5"]
[Black "Symmetrical: 2...Nc6 with 4...Qb6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A30"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[GameId "2102815303044585"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nc6 {Here we will take a look at the lines where Black doesn't play ...[Nf6] early on.} 3. d4 {White continues with the plan.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Qb6 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Rc6d4,Rb6d4] Black wants to dislodge the centralized knight.} 5. e3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Ge3d4] A typical move for White in these lines, supporting the centralized knight instead of removing it from the center.} e6 ({In case of} 5... g6 6. Nc3 {threatening [Nd5]} Nf6 7. g3 $1 {followed by [Bg2], [O-O], [b3] and [Bb2], White has a comfortable space advantage with good center control. He will plan to centralize the rooks after [Qd2] and then a possible idea is the d-knight transfer to [e2], [f4] and finally [d5].}) 6. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gb1c3] White intends to castle and continue with [Nc3], [b3] and [Bb2]. This is White's ideal set-up, altered only in case Black goes for the central push with ...[d5]. By postponing the development of the knight on [b1], White avoids the possible [Bb4]-pin.} Nf6 ({In case of} 6... Bb4+ {White plays} 7. Bd2 {.}) 7. O-O Be7 8. b3 {[%csl Bb1][%cal Gc1b2,Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Rd7d5,Rd5c4] White postpones the development of the [b1]-knight because he anticipates Black's play in the center with ...[d5]. In that case, White wants to be able to develop the knight on [d2], so that he can recapture on [c4] with the knight.} O-O 9. Bb2 {White continues with development and waits for Black's ...[d5].} ({After} 9. Nc3 d5 $1 10. cxd5 Nxd4 $1 {Black successfully simplifies the position in the center.}) 9... d5 ({This is Black's only way to free his play. Otherwise, White will have a comfortable space advantage after} 9... d6 10. Nc3 {.}) 10. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2c4] The point of White's development. Now a capture on [c4] would be met by [Nxc4], winning a tempo by attacking the black queen.} Bd7 ({In case of} 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {Black needs to waste time with the queen, when White can consider a queenside expansion with [a3] and [b4], possibly in combination with [c5], or an exchange on [d5], which would lead to a position with an IQP in case of ...[exd5] or give White rich piece play in case of ...[Nxd5], [Nc4].}) 11. cxd5 {[%cal Gd2c4] Since Black won't capture the [c4]-pawn, White takes on [d5] to free the [c4]-square for the knight.} Nxd5 12. Nc4 {[%csl Bc4,Bd4][%cal Gc4b6] The queen now must go back all the way to [d8], since going to [c7] would allow further attacks with [Ndb5].} Qd8 13. Qd2 {[%csl Bd7][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gd1d8,Gc1c8] 💡The rooks are coming to [d1] and [c1]. White has a pleasant pressure in the center, while Black still has to solve the light-squared bishop's development question. Note that if that bishop comes out to [c6] for example after Black takes [Ncxd4], it is still susceptible to attacks after [Nce5] or [Nca5].} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
