[White "1) The Symmetrical English 1…c5"]
[Black "Symmetrical: 2...b6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A31"]
[PlyCount "27"]
[GameId "2102815303081451"]

1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb7h1] This move isn't very common, but it is used when Black wants to play the Hedgehog.} 3. d4 {White continues as usual.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Bb7 5. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White develops and intends [e4], to establish the Maróczy bind in the center with the pawns on [c4] and [e4].} Nf6 {[%csl Be4][%cal Rf6e4,Gb7e4]} 6. f3 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gf3e4,Ge2e4,Gc3e4] After this move Black cannot stop [e4] anymore.} d6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Ga7a6,Gf8e7,Ge8g8,Gb8c6,Gb8d7] Going for a Hedgehog formation with ...[e6], ...[a6] and then either ...[Nc6] or ...[Nbd7]. Black can try 6...[e6] 7.e4 [Nc6] but after 8.Bf4 [Bc5] 9.Nb3, White is targeting the dark squares in the center and intends [Qc2] and [O-O-O].} 7. e4 {[%csl Bb5,Bc4,Bd5,Be4][%cal Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc4b5] The Maróczy structure gives White a commanding space advantage. The pawns on [c4] and [e4] effectively prevent the liberating breaks ...[d5] and ...[b5].} e6 8. Be2 {[%cal Gc1e3,Ge1g1,Gd1d2] White's development is simple: [Be3], [O-O] and [Qd2], when his general plan will be to advance on the queenside.} ({White can also start with} 8. Be3 {.}) 8... Be7 9. Be3 {Both sides complete their development.} O-O 10. O-O a6 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga6b5] It's important for Black to control the [b5]-square.} 11. Qd2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1]} ({The immediate} 11. b4 $5 {is an interesting alternative, but finishing development and connecting the rooks is more thematic.}) 11... Nbd7 ({This is the standard Hedgehog development for Black. Black's position is harmonious, but it lacks space. The alternative is to play} 11... Nc6 {and exchange one pair of knights. After} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 13. b4 {, White immediately starts the advance on the queenside. He will put the rooks in the center on [d1] and [c1] and can also expand with [f4] after securing the [e4]-pawn, with options to break through on either wing: [b5] on the queenside and [e5] or [f5] on the kingside.}) 12. Rfd1 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c8,Gd1d8] White is placing the rooks on [d1] and [c1]. From those squares they will be effective against the possible ...[d5] and ...[b5] breaks and can also support a queenside advance after [a4], [Nb3], [a5], with an eventual [c5].} Qc7 13. Rac1 {[%cal Gb2b4] White finished development and will proceed with advance on the queenside with [b4].} Rac8 {Black can also put the other rook on [c8], but that won't affect White's plans as he will continue with [b4] anyway.} 14. b4 {[%cal Gd4b3,Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gc3a4,Gc4c5,Gg1h1,Ge3g1,Ge2f1] White advances on the queenside. 💡There are two main ideas that he will try to combine: 🔹Nb3 followed by [a4]-[a5] and [a3] defending the [b4]-pawn so after the [d5] break the pawn on [b4] won't be attacked by the bishop on [e7] with [Na4] and [c5], opening the files on the queenside; 🔹on the kingside, White can solidify his position with moves like [Kh1], [Bg1] and [Bf1].} *

