1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} e6 (3... e6 {Black invites White in the Benoni territory in case we decide to play} 4. d5 {.}) 4. e3 {The move is in line with the approach White takes in all the variations of the Symmetrical English.} d5 {[%csl Bb1][%cal Gb1d2,Gb2b3,Gc1a3] This is now a transposition to the Tarrasch Defence where White has played the move [e3] and postponed the development of the knight on [b1]. The latter factor is important for White as it lends more flexibility to White's position: the knight can be developed to [d2] and in some lines the idea to exchange the dark-squared bishops with [Ba3] is possible.} ({Note that the move} 4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 {leads to a transposition to the lines analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 e6 5.e3 .}) 5. cxd5 {With this capture, White creates an IQP on [d5].} exd5 ({Taking with the knight:} 5... Nxd5 {is met by} 6. e4 Nf6 7. e5 Nd5 8. Bc4 {followed by [O-O], [Re1] with free play where White aims to create threats on the kingside with [Bd3], [Nc3] d2-[e4] etc.}) 6. Bb5+ {[%cal Gb5e8,Ge1g1] Developing with tempo, White wants to castle next.} Nc6 {The most natural move, but the other two alternatives are also possible. For White though, in all three cases, the play is the same and it revolves around the IQP on [d5].} ({After} 6... Bd7 7. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 8. dxc5 Nxc5 9. O-O {White continues with Nc3, b3, Bb2, possibly Ne2-d4f4 with easy play on the dark squares thanks to the control of the d4-square.} ({Similar is Nbd7 dxc5 Bxc5} 9. O-O {O-O Nc3} a6 {Be2 followed by [b3] and [Bb2]. An interesting maneuver later on for White is [Rc1]-[c2]-[d2], to put pressure on the [d5]-pawn.})) 7. O-O {White castles and now Black needs to decide whether to take on [d4] or to allow White to take on [c5] on the next move.} Bd6 ({After} 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Bd7 9. Nc3 {we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 e6 5.e3 d5 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Bb5 Bd7 9.O-O}) 8. dxc5 {[%csl Yd5] White gains a tempo by forcing the bishop to move again and stabilizes the structure in the center, giving Black an IQP on [d5].} Bxc5 9. Qc2 {[%csl Yc5,Bc6][%cal Gc2c6,Gb5c6] A move that puts immediate pressure on Black's position by attacking the loose bishop on [c5] and the knight on [c6].} Qb6 {[%cal Gb6c5,Gb6c6,Rb6b5]} ({Black defends both light pieces and attacks the bishop on b5. The alternative is} 9... Qd6 {, but that blocks the retreat of the dark-squared bishop. After} 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Na4 {, White manages to exchange a pair of light pieces, Black's dark-squared bishop in particular with} Bb4 12. a3 Ba5 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. Bd2 {and Black must exchange the bishops because if the bishop moves from a5 White can play Bb4, which will win an exchange.}) 10. Bxc6+ ({White gains a tempo for development by exchanging on c6. It is also possible to play} 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Be2 {with Rd1, b3 and Bb2 next.}) 10... bxc6 11. Nc3 {[%csl Yb6,Yc5][%cal Gc3a4,Ga4b6,Ga4c5,Gc2c5] Now the threat is [Na4], to win the bishop on [c5].} Qc7 12. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] The bishop will be very active on the long diagonal.} O-O 13. Bb2 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb2f6,Gc3e2,Ga1c1,Gc1c6] White finished development and now will start play against the backward pawn on [c6]. The next moves will be [Ne2] to open the c-file and the long diagonal and [Rac1].} Bg4 14. Ne2 $1 {[%csl Yc6,Gf6][%cal Gb2f6,Ga1c1,Gc1c7] An important move that opens the c-file and the long diagonal. White threatens both the bishop on [c5] and the exchange [Bxf6], which will wreck Black's kingside structure. It's important that White doesn't mind the exchange ...[Bxf3], [gxf3] because the pawn on [f3] will be useful to cover the [e4]-square and the open g-file can be used after [Kh1] and [Rg1] – particularly dangerous in combination with the long-range bishop on [b2].} Bxf3 15. gxf3 {[%cal Gb2f6,Gc2c5]} Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6] Black stops [Bxf6].} 16. Kh1 {[%csl Yc6,Yg7][%cal Gf1g1,Gg1g7,Ge2d4,Gd4c6,Gd4f5,Ga1c1,Gc1c6,Gf5g7] White prepares [Rg1], to use the semi-open g-file. 💡White can continue with: 🔹Rac1 and Nd4, to put pressure on the [c6]-pawn; while, 🔹from [d4] the knight can come to [f5], attacking the [g7]-pawn. The position is quite pleasant for White, who can play on both wings.} *

