1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} d5 {[%cal Rd5c4] This is an attempt to eliminate White's [c4]-pawn and free Black's play. The problem is that after the exchange on [d5] White gains time for development by attacking the black piece on that square. Still, this is a decent equalizing try for Black.} 5. cxd5 {The pawn was attacked, so White captures on [d5].} Nxd5 ({Taking with the queen is also possible. After} 5... Qxd5 6. Nc3 Qa5 7. Nb3 Qc7 8. Nb5 Qc6 9. e4 $1 {White has a development advantage and the initiative. He wants to continue with [Be2] and [O-O] while the pawn on [e4] is taboo in view of:} ({𓈓9... Qxe4? Be2 threatening} 9. Nc7+ {Na6 O-O with a big advantage; or: 𓈓9... Nxe4? Be3 with [Rc1] next. This position usually arises from the variation: 1.d4 d5 2.c4 c5 3.cxd5 Qxd5 4.Nf3 cxd4 5.Nc3 Qa5 6.Nxd4 Nf6})) 6. e4 {[%csl Be4][%cal Ge4d5]} ({The most natural move, attacking the knight and gaining space in the center. An interesting alternative is} 6. Nf3 $5 {, which opens the d-file and threatens [e4], when [Qxd8] will deprive Black of his castling rights.}) 6... Nf6 {[%cal Rf6e4]} ({Black retreats and attacks the pawn on e4. In case of} 6... Nb4 {threatening Qxd4 followed by the fork} 7. Nc2 {Be3} e5 {Nb5 White has the initiative thanks to his extra tempo} 8. Be3 {in an otherwise symmetrical position.}) 7. Be3 $5 ({A very interesting pawn sacrifice. White has an alternative with the calmer} 7. Nc3 e5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. Nf5 {with some slight initiative in the endgame after} Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 g6 12. Ne3 {, thanks to the firm control of the [d5]-square and the more active bishop, not limited by the [e5]-pawn.}) 7... Nxe4 ({In case of} 7... e5 8. Nb5 {White has an initiative as Black lags back in development on the queenside.}) 8. Qc2 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gc2e4] White continues to develop with tempo. Black is forced to move the knight one more time, making it 5 times in 8 moves!} Nf6 9. Nc3 {[%csl Bc2,Bc3,Bd4,Be3][%cal Gf1b5,Ge1g1,Ge1c1,Gd4f5] White's development advantage is a sufficient compensation for the pawn. Further ideas involve [O-O-O] or [Rd1], [Bb5] developing with tempo to allow [O-O], [Nf5] and so on. A sample line is:} e5 {[%cal Re5d4]} ({Or} 9... e6 10. O-O-O Bd7 11. Ne4 {with active play.}) 10. Bb5+ {[%csl Re8][%cal Gb5e8] Speeding up the development with tempo.} Bd7 11. Nf5 {[%csl Bf5,Yf8][%cal Gf5g7] The knight is annoying on [f5], preventing the [f8]-bishop's development by attacking the [g7]-pawn.} g6 {[%csl Yh6,Yf6,Yg7][%cal Rg6f5] Understandably Black wants to get rid of the knight, but this weakens the dark squares.} 12. Nh6 {[%csl Ye8,Bh6][%cal Gh6f7,Ge1g1,Ga1d1,Gd1d8,Ge3h6] The knight won't allow Black to castle. Taking it will develop White's bishop on [h6], preventing the short castling as well. 💡White will also castle and place a rook on [d1], to increase the pressure along the d-file.} *

