1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} e5 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Re5d4] An active move that chases away the centralized knight. As we saw in this line: 2...Nc6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 the move e5 weakens the [d5]-square. But, in the present line, with a knight on [f6], Black plans to push ...[d5] and sacrifice a pawn in order not to allow White easy control of the light squares in the center.} 5. Nb5 {[%csl Yd5,Yd6][%cal Gb5d6,Gd1d6] A move that aims to take immediate advantage of Black's weakened squares on the d-file, [d5] and [d6].} d5 {Practically a forced sacrifice for Black.} 6. cxd5 Bc5 ({Black cannot regain the pawn as} 6... Nxd5 $4 7. Qxd5 $1 Qxd5 8. Nc7+ {wins a piece for White.}) 7. N5c3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gd1d5] The knight was not stable on [b5], so it retreats to [c3], safely guarding the [d5]-pawn. Now White will be a pawn up, since the pawn on [d5] cannot easily be regained, but Black gets free development for his pieces.} O-O 8. g3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gf1g2,Gg2d5,Gc1g5] Ideally, White would develop the bishop on [g2] thus defending the extra pawn on [d5] one more time, castle and leave the [c1]-[h6] diagonal open for the dark-squared bishop. Black shouldn't allow this.} Ng4 {[%csl Bf2][%cal Rg4f2,Rc5f2]} ({This is Black's best move. The move} 8... Qb6 {has a similar idea to provoke} 9. e3 {thus shutting the bishop on c1 but is less precise. After} Bg4 10. Be2 Bxe2 11. Qxe2 e4 12. a3 {followed by [Nd2], [b4] or [b3] in case Black plays [a5], [Bb2] and [O-O], White completes development and obtains a comfortable position as Black's activity has been stymied.}) ({The aggressive} 8... e4 $6 {is not very good because after} 9. Bg2 {the pawn is overly exposed, while further advance with} e3 {only helps White's development after} 10. Bxe3 Bxe3 11. fxe3 Qb6 12. Qd2 {when White will castle and remain two pawns up.}) 9. e3 {[%csl Be3,Gf2][%cal Rc5f2,Ge3f2] White must blunt the activity of the bishop on [c5].} f5 {[%cal Rf5f4] Only aggressive play can justify Black's pawn sacrifice.} 10. h3 {[%csl Yg4][%cal Gh3g4] Getting rid of the active knight.} Nf6 (10... Nxf2 $2 {the sacrifice on [f2] is insufficient} 11. Kxf2 f4 12. Ne4 fxe3+ 13. Kg2 {and the dominant knight on [e4] ensures against any problem.}) 11. Nd2 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5] The knight is en route to [b3] to harass the bishop on [c5].} Nbd7 12. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5] Black now needs to decide on which diagonal to keep the bishop.} Bb6 (12... Bd6 {, Black keeps the [b6]-square available for the knight on [d7]. This means that a further attack on the [d5]-pawn is possible when the bishop moves from [d6], so in this case White should develop the bishop on [g2], keeping the pawn safe. After} 13. Bg2 {the pawn is safe, so Black should play} e4 {and after} 14. O-O Ne5 15. Bd2 {intending to meet} Nd3 {with} 16. Nc1 {play is unclear, but White is still a pawn up and plans [Nd4] and [Qb3] with possible [Nd4]-[e6] ideas.}) 13. a4 {[%csl Yb6][%cal Ga4a5,Ga5b6] Intending to further harass the bishop with [a5].} a5 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Gc3b5] Black stops White's expansion but weakens the [b5]-square.} 14. Be2 {[%csl Bd3,Bf3][%cal Ge2d3,Ge2f3] With the [b6]-square taken by the bishop Black cannot play ...[Nb6] to attack the pawn on [d5], so White can develop the bishop to [e2], from where it guards both squares [d3] and [f3], thus taking the sting out of the plan ...[e4] and ...[Ne5].} Nc5 {Black must somehow develop the knight on [d7].} 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3g8] White continues the development.} Kh8 17. Bd2 {[%csl Bd5,Bb5,Bc4][%cal Ge1c1,Gc1b1,Ge2b5,Gb3c4,Gc3b5,Gd1d8] 💡White intends to: 🔹castle long and tuck away the king to [b1], where it will be completely safe thanks to White's heavy presence on the queenside and the blockade on the light-squares, especially the [b5]-square, which prevents any opening of the game there. 🔹The rook on [d1] will support the extra [d5]-pawn; and, 🔹White can use his control of the light squares by placing pieces on [b5] and [c4].} *

