1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Symmetrical English when White plays an early [d4].} 5. e3 $5 ({It has been established for quite some time that Black obtains good play after the theoretical and standard} 5. Nc3 e6 {, so this move is a fresh attempt to take the game into less explored territory. There aren't many games played in the lines that follow, which makes them an excellent territory to spring a surprise on the unsuspecting opponent. Black has a wide choice now. It's worth pointing out that the capture on [c6] is bad as after ...[bxc6] Black has reinforced the center and opened the b-file for the rook.}) 5... d5 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3d5] A direct attempt to take advantage of the absence of White's knight from [c3], which means less control of the [d5]-square.} 6. Nxc6 {By taking on [c6] White prevents the early simplifications in the center by ...[Nxd4] and ...[dxc4].} bxc6 {Now White can play in different ways. The pawn structure is typical of lines in the Queen's Indian or the Semi-Tarrasch with colors reversed meaning White gets Black's structure in those openings.} 7. Be2 {A flexible move that keeps the tension in the center.} ({White can treat the game even in reversed Grünfeld fashion with} 7. g3 $5 {followed by [Bg2] and [O-O].}) ({A reversed Semi-Tarrasch approach if possible, too, and is also more forcing after} 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Qxd7 10. O-O {followed by [b3], [Nc3], [Bb2] etc. Since White is a tempo up compared to the Semi-Tarrasch, he will be better prepared for the plan with the central break ...[d4], which is the most testing plan in these positions. Otherwise, White will seek to expand on the queenside to activate the pawn majority there with ideas like [Na4]-[c5], [a3], [b4], putting rooks on [c1] and [d1] and so on.}) 7... e5 {Black takes the center.} ({In case of} 7... e6 8. Qc2 {threatening [cxd5] and [Qc6]} Bd7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Nc3 {With [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] next, White completes development and has a harmonious position. He will seek play on the queenside for example by trying to exploit the [c5]-square with ideas like [Rac1], [cxd5], [Na4]-[c5] or in the center by pushing [e4].}) 8. O-O {White castles and will develop the queenside next.} Be7 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Rd8d5,Rc6d5]} ({If the bishop is developed on d6, then Black has less control over the d5-square, which would allow White to gain tempo for development after} 8... Bd6 9. cxd5 cxd5 10. Nc3 {, attacking the pawn on [d5] and threatening [Nb5] or [Bb5], thus practically forcing the bishop to retreat.}) 9. b3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gc1b2,Gb2e5] On the other side, the bishop on [e7] doesn't defend the pawn on [e5], so White immediately develops the bishop to [b2] in order to attack it.} O-O 10. Bb2 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gb2e5] Attacking the pawn and forcing Black to lose tempo.} Bd6 {[%cal Gd6e5]} 11. cxd5 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Gb1c3,Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Ga1c1,Gc1c5] White opens the c-file. One of White's ideas is to play [Rc1] and use the [c5]-square with the [Na4]-[c5] maneuver.} cxd5 12. Nc3 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gd1d5] Continuing the development with tempo as the pawn on [d5] is attacked.} Bb7 {[%cal Gb7d5]} ({The bishop can also be developed on e6, but play will be similar, for example} 12... Be6 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. Qd3 {with idea of [Rfd1] when White can continue with [Nb5] to exchange rooks on the c-file and gain control of it by putting the other rook on [c1].}) 13. Bf3 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gf3d5,Gc3d5,Gd1d5] A typical move for this structure. White puts pressure on the [d5]-pawn and wants to provoke ...[e4], when he will obtain control of the [d4]-square and an excellent open long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} Bc7 {Black should resist the temptation to push ...[e4].} 14. Rc1 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gd1d2,Gc3b5,Gb5c7,Gc1c7,Gf1d1,Gd1d5] White completes development. 💡Next, he can play: 🔹Nb5, attacking the bishop on [c7]; or, 🔹simply [Qd2], [Rfd1] with further pressure on [d5].} *

