1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Symmetrical English when White plays an early [d4].} 5. e3 ({It has been established for quite some time that Black obtains good play after the theoretical and standard} 5. Nc3 e6 {, so this move is a fresh attempt to take the game into less explored territory. There aren't many games played in the lines that follow, which makes them an excellent territory to spring a surprise on the unsuspecting opponent. Black has a wide choice now.}) 5... e5 {[%csl Yd5] This move is possible, but the obvious drawback is the weakening of the [d5]-square.} 6. Nb5 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Gb5d6] White threatens [Nd6].} Bb4+ {[%csl Re1][%cal Rb4e1]} 7. N1c3 {[%cal Gb5d6] Renewing the threat of [Nd6].} d6 8. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] White goes after the exposed bishop.} Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 {[%csl Yd5,Bd6][%cal Ge1g1,Gf1e2] If allowed to finish development with [Be2], [O-O] White will have an advantage thanks to the better structure (Black has a backward pawn on [d6] and a weak [d5]-square) and the pair of bishops, so Black must act urgently.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rg4d1] Black develops with tempo and wants to disrupt White's development.} 10. Be2 {White wants to avoid making a weakning move like [f3].} Bxe2 11. Qxe2 {[%csl Yd5,Bd6][%cal Ge1g1,Ge1d1,Gd1d8] The plan is to castle and place a rook on the d-file, targeting the backward [d6]-pawn and the weakened [d5]-square.} d5 {Black must act immediately before White established a bind on the d-file.} 12. O-O {White finishes development of the kingside. Now after} dxc4 13. Qxc4 O-O 14. Rd1 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gc4b3,Gb3b7,Ga1c1,Gc1c8,Gd1d8,Bc1d2,Bd2e1] The pawn structure is symmetrical, but White has some initiative. 💡The plan is to: 🔹continue with [Qb3] (targeting the pawn on [b7]) with further development of the bishop [Bd2]-[e1]. 🔹A future advance of the queenside pawns is also possible. 🔹In the long-term, the bishop may become active on the [c3]- or [b4]-square.} *

