1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} e6 ({Together with} 4... Nc6 {, this is one of Black's most popular choices. The move g6 would transpose to the lines after 4...Nc6 5.e3 g6 , but there is a rare independent line after 5.Nc3 d5 when White should play 6.Nf3! Be6 7.Ng5! which would give him the better structure and the bishop pair after the best response 7...d4 8.Nxe6 fxe6 9.Nb5 Nc6 10.g3 .}) 5. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1]} ({The natural} 5. Nc3 Bb4 {gives Black excellent play, so White postpones the development of the knight on [b1].}) 5... d5 {The most direct move. In fact, pushing ...[d5] is Black's only way to play to equalize, the only question is on which move he would do so.} ({In case of} 5... Nc6 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the line analyzed via 4...Nc6 5.e3 e6 6.Be2 . Another transposition leading to that move order is 5...Bb4 6.Bd2 Bxd2 7.Nxd2 Nc6 8.Be2 , reached after 4...Nc6 5.e3 e6 6.Be2 Bb4 7.Bd2 Bxd2 8.Nxd2 . Black can also start with 5...Be7 , but after 6.Nc3 d5 , we have a transposition to the lines after 5...d5 6.Nc3 Be7 . The final transposition is after 5...Bc5 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Be2 Nc6 8.O-O , when we transpose to the line mentioned as a clickable in the note to Black's 6th move after 4...Nc6 5.e3 e6 6.Be2 . A move that doesn't transpose anywhere is 5...a6 , when Black aims for a Hedgehog formation after 6.Be2 Qc7 7.O-O Be7 8.b3 O-O 9.Bb2 , but White obtains easy play here after [Nc3] and [Rc1] as Black is rather passive.}) 6. Nc3 {Now that [Bb4] is no longer advisable for Black in view of [Qa4] which comes with check now, thanks to the move [d5], White develops the knight to [c3].} dxc4 {With this move Black tries to avoid the IQP positions.} 7. Bxc4 a6 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga6b5,Rb7b5,Gc8b7] A useful move for Black, covering the [b5]-square and possibly preparing ...[b5] and ...[Bb7].} 8. e4 {[%cal Gc1g5] A natural move for White, opening the [c1]-[h6] diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} b5 {[%cal Gc8b7]} ({A passive move like} 8... Be7 {shows the dangers Black faces after} 9. O-O O-O 10. e5 Nd5 11. Qg4 {with dangerous threats on the kingside.}) ({An alternative is} 8... Bd6 9. Bb3 O-O 10. O-O Qc7 11. Kh1 {with the idea of [f4] with a complex middlegame.}) 9. Bb3 Nbd7 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gd7e5,Ge4e5] Black prevents a possible [e5] before developing the bishop on [b7].} ({After} 9... Bb7 10. e5 {, White has the initiative.}) 10. Be3 {White develops harmoniously.} Bb7 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Rb7e4,Rf6e4]} 11. O-O {[%csl Be6,Be4][%cal Gb3e6,Gd4e6] White completes development. The position resembles the Sicilian, with White missing the c-pawn and Black missing the d-pawn. The pawn on [e4] is poisoned, given the sacrifice on [e6].} Bb4 {[%cal Ge8g8,Rb4c3,Rf6e4,Rb7e4] Black needs to finish development and uses the fact that there is no pawn on [d6] as in the Sicilian. There are a couple of bad moves the opponent needs to avoid. For example:} (11... Be7 $2 12. Bxe6 $1 {and:}) (11... Nxe4 $2 12. Nxe4 Bxe4 13. Bxe6 $1 {.}) ({The move} 11... b4 {leads to a sharp middlegame after} 12. Na4 Bxe4 13. Re1 {where White has full compensation for the pawn after he plays [Bg5] next.}) ({It's possible to play} 11... Nc5 {, covering the [e6]-pawn. After} 12. f3 Be7 13. a3 Nxb3 14. Nxb3 {, White keeps some initiative thanks to the threat of [Na5] either after the exchange of queens on [d1] or after Black avoids the exchange and moves the queen from [d8].}) 12. a4 {[%cal Ga4b5,Gc3b5] Adding fuel to the fire. White wants to weaken the [b5]-pawn by taking [axb5].} ({It's possible to play in a more restrained manner with} 12. f3 {, securing the pawn on [e4].}) 12... Bxc3 {It's critical to check what happens if Black takes the pawn.} ({In case of} 12... O-O {, White has a choice: 𓈓13. f3 White kills off Black's counterplay against the pawn on [e4] and has a clear target on the queenside in the pawn on [b5]; while with: 𓈓13. axb5 axb5 Qe2 the likely exchange of the [e4]-pawn for the [b5]-pawn will give White an outside passed pawn on the b-file.}) 13. bxc3 bxa4 14. Rxa4 {[%csl Be6,Yb7][%cal Gd4e6,Gb3e6,Ga4b4,Gb4b7,Ga4h4] The rook is active on the fourth rank.} ({Taking with the bishop is also promising, for example after} 14. Bxa4 Bxe4 15. f3 Bd5 16. c4 $1 Bxc4 17. Nc6 {, White has plenty of compensation for the material.}) 14... Bxe4 15. Bxe6 {The simplest is to regain the pawn and remain with the pair of bishops.} ({An alternative is} 15. f3 Bd5 16. c4 Bb7 17. Rb4 {, when White has good compensation for the pawn.}) 15... O-O {Taking on e6 is fatal, after 15...fxe6? 16.Nxe6 Qe7 otherwise the pawn on g7 falls 17.Rxe4! Nxe4 18.Nc7 Kf7 19.Qh5 Kg8 20.Nxa8 , White has a decisive advantage.} 16. Ba2 {[%csl Ba2,Be3,Ya6][%cal Gc3c8,Gc3c4,Gc4c5,Gc5c6,Gc6c7] Material is equal, but White has the bishop pair. Objectively, the position is equal, but there is still plenty of life in the position. 💡White will seek to: 🔹use his bishops; 🔹advance his passed c-pawn; and, 🔹attack Black's a-pawn.} *

