1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White intends [d4]. Once played, the centralized knight on [d4] and the pawn on [c4] will give White a space advantage.} Nf6 {The other important choices are: 🔹2...Nc6 – the main one; 🔹2...g6 ; which after 3.d4 is analyzed via the move order 2...Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 g6 ; and also: 🔹2...b6 , while after: 🔹2...e6 3.e4 Nf6 4.Nc3 , we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after the moves 1.c4 Nf6 2.Nc3 e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3} 3. d4 {White continues as planned.} cxd4 ({This is the most common reply, though Black can keep the tension with} 3... e6 {. After d5 cxd5 cxd4 Nxd4 Nxd5 , we have a transposition to the line analyzed after 3...cxd4 4.Nxd4 d5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 .}) 4. Nxd4 {Now Black has a wide choice.} e6 ({Together with} 4... Nc6 {, this is one of Black's most popular choices. The move g6 would transpose to the lines after 4...Nc6 5.e3 g6 , but there is a rare independent line after 5.Nc3 d5 when White should play 6.Nf3! Be6 7.Ng5! which would give him the better structure and the bishop pair after the best response 7...d4 8.Nxe6 fxe6 9.Nb5 Nc6 10.g3 .}) 5. e3 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1]} ({The natural} 5. Nc3 Bb4 {gives Black excellent play, so White postpones the development of the knight on [b1].}) 5... d5 {The most direct move. In fact, pushing ...[d5] is Black's only way to play to equalize, the only question is on which move he would do so.} ({In case of} 5... Nc6 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines analyzed via 4...Nc6 5.e3 e6 6.Be2 . Another transposition leading to that move order is 5...Bb4 6.Bd2 Bxd2 7.Nxd2 Nc6 8.Be2 , reached after 4...Nc6 5.e3 e6 6.Be2 Bb4 7.Bd2 Bxd2 8.Nxd2 . Black can also start with 5...Be7 , but after 6.Nc3 d5 , we have a transposition to the lines after 5...d5 6.Nc3 Be7 . The final transposition is after 5...Bc5 6.Nc3 O-O 7.Be2 Nc6 8.O-O , when we transpose to the line mentioned as a clickable in the note to Black's 6th move after 4...Nc6 5.e3 e6 6.Be2 . A move that doesn't transpose anywhere is 5...a6 , when Black aims for a Hedgehog formation after 6.Be2 Qc7 7.O-O Be7 8.b3 O-O 9.Bb2 , but White obtains easy play here after [Nc3] and [Rc1] as Black is rather passive.}) 6. Nc3 {Now that [Bb4] is no longer advisable for Black in view of [Qa4] which comes with check now, thanks to the move [d5], White develops the knight to [c3].} Nc6 ({The move} 6... Be7 {gives White a small advantage after} 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Bb5+ Bd7 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. O-O {when White obtains a comfortable version of the IQP as some light pieces have already been exchanged.}) 7. cxd5 {With the black knight on [c6] the capture on [d5] ensures that White obtains the better pawn structure.} exd5 {[%csl Yd5]} ({The point of the previous note was that with a knight on c6 Black cannot avoid the IQP with} 7... Nxd5 {because then} 8. Nxc6 $1 bxc6 9. Bd2 {saddles Black with a backward pawn on [c6].}) 8. Bb5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb5e8,Gd4c6] White develops with tempo, pinning and attacking the knight on [c6].} Bd7 9. O-O {White finished the development of the kingside. Next is to do the same on the queenside.} Bd6 10. b3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8,Gb2d4] The standard development of the dark-squared bishop. It will be active on the long diagonal, lending extra support and defense of the blockading square [d4].} O-O 11. Bb2 {White finished development. Now a typical complex middlegame with an IQP arises.} Re8 12. Nce2 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge2d4,Gb2d4,Gd1d4,Gd4c6] A consolidating move. Exchanges favor White in these positions, with fewer pieces on the board Black's dynamic potential will also be less, making the weakness of the IQP bigger. With his last move, White wants to exchange one pair of knights. Thus, the other knight from [e2] can take up the blockading [d4]-square. This is a typical operation of getting rid of the superfluous piece both White's knights want to come to [d4], so White gets rid of one.} a6 {[%cal Ra6b5]} 13. Bd3 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4c6,Ge2d4] White plans [Nxc6] followed by [Nd4]. If Black avoids the exchange and plays} Ne5 {[%cal Re5d3]} 14. Bf5 {[%csl Gd4,Gf5][%cal Gf5d7,Gd4f5,Ge2d4] Black either exchanges the light-squared bishops, when the knight from [d4] finds an excellent square on [f5], or in case of} Rc8 15. Nf4 {[%csl Gf4,Yd5][%cal Gf4h5,Gf4d5] White improves the [e2]-knight. 💡What is the role of this piece? 🔹from [f4], it puts pressure on the isolani; and, 🔹also intends to jump to [h5], inviting favorable exchanges. White has a pleasant position, especially as Black doesn't have much activity thanks to White's excellently placed pieces.} *

