1. c4 e5 {White needs to make the first choice as early as move 2!} 2. Nc3 ({The alternative is the move} 2. g3 {. I decided against it as the lines with} c6 {became very popular for Black, and it wasn't easy to find a convincing avenue for White to pursue.}) ({Hence,} 2. Nc3 {.}) 2... Nf6 3. Nf3 ({Again,} 3. g3 c6 {works nicely for Black.}) 3... Nc6 {White needs to choose his preferred line in this position.} 4. e4 ({Traditionally, the main 'English' move has always been} 4. g3 {. Black has many good lines against it} Bb4 {, 4...Bc5 , 4...Nd4 and 4...d5 being the main ones. Recently, a relatively rare plan was developed in the last one after 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Bg2 Nf6!? of course, nothing wrong with the traditional move 6...Nb6 or Caruana's choice in his match with Carlsen 6...Bc5 All these options for Black are extremely well-explored and lead to different types of positions, thus making them too diverse conceptually. For these reasons, I gave up on the move 4.g3 .}) {My initial plan was to recommend 4.e3 , inspired by Ding Liren's win in the 4th game of the World Championship match in Astana against Nepomniachtchi. But then the following line was played against him in Wijk aan Zee in 2024: 4...Bb4 5.Qc2 Bxc3 6.bxc3 e4! instead of 6...[d6] as in the game in Astana 7.Ng5 Qe7 8.f3 d6 9.Nxe4 Nxe4 10.Qxe4 Qxe4 11.fxe4 f6 and this position looks like a fortress for Black! Van Foreest held the draw without problems. This idea made me abandon my plan to recommend 4.e3 . I wasn't thrilled by the 'little' moves 4.d3 or 4.a3 either, so that left the move 4.e4 .} 4... Bb4 {This is Black's main move.} ({The main alternative is} 4... Bc5 {. It was also used by Nepomniachtchi in Astana, making a relatively easy draw in game 10. Luckily, I managed to find some ways for White to keep the game going with play against Black's uncastled king.}) 5. d3 d6 6. Be2 {This was the move that gave life to our line with 4.e4.} ({When playing this line, usually White opted to hunt for the dark-squared bishop with} 6. a3 Bc5 7. b4 Bb6 8. Na4 {, but after} Bg4 {, Black's play seemed too easy as it is all about the weak [d4]-square. Then I remembered the game Svidler-Carlsen, where Carlsen played exactly the same pawn structure... but with Black in the Sicilian. So I thought that if that structure was good for Black, it must be good for White with an extra tempo! The idea of the f3-knight transfer to [b3] via [d2] to [b6] via [d7] in that game also features in the recommended lines. Since one of White's main ideas is to execute the move [f4], this gives good chances for an attack on the king, and this was an additional allure of this variation:}) *

