1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4c3,Gg8e7,Gg8f6,Rf7f5] This move became popular thanks to Anand's efforts from 2016 and has remained popular ever since. Black wants to take on [c3] and double White's c-pawns but also keeps flexibility by postponing the development of the knight on [g8] – it can go to [f6], but also to [e7], when it's easier to follow up with ...[f5].} 3. Qb3 {[%cal Gb3b4,Gb3c3]} ({The main move with a well-developed theory is} 3. Nd5 {. With the queen move, White attacks the bishop on [b4] while at the same time preventing the doubling of the c-pawns.}) 3... Bc5 {Taking on c3 just gives White the bishop pair.} ({For example} 3... Bxc3 4. Qxc3 d6 5. d3 Nf6 6. Nf3 {followed by [e3], [Be2] and [O-O].}) ({There would be a similar play after} 3... a5 4. a3 Bxc3 5. Qxc3 d6 6. b3 {followed by [e3], [d3], [Bb2], [Nf3] and [Be2]. In both cases, White obtains a safe and compact position with the pair of bishops when the general plan is to advance on the queenside with [b4].}) 4. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4c5] This is a very concrete variation, so it pays to remember it well. Thanks to this and the next move White ensures that he obtains the bishop pair.} Be7 5. Qg3 {[%csl Be5,Bg7][%cal Gg3e5,Gg3g7] This double attack on the pawns on [e5] and [g7] forces Black's next move.} Bf6 6. Nxf6+ {White obtained the bishop pair.} Qxf6 7. d4 {[%csl Bc7,Be5][%cal Gd4e5,Gg3c7] White uses the pin on the [h2]-[b8] diagonal to attack Black's center.} d6 {Taking on [d4] allows} (7... exd4 8. Qxc7 {when after [Nf3] and [Qf4], (White will have both the pair of bishops and the better structure.)}) 8. Bg5 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gg5f6,Rf6d4] White develops with tempo. The idea of the attack on the queen is to dislocate it from [f6], from where it exerts pressure on White's pawn on [d4].} Qe6 {[%cal Re6c4,Re5d4] Now there is a double attack on White's central pawns, but White keeps everything under control with} 9. Bd2 {[%csl Bg7][%cal Gg3g7,Gg7h8] White counterattacks by attacking the pawn on [g7].} Qg6 {Black must defend the pawn on [g7].} ({It's not possible to do the same from f6 because after} 9... Qf6 $2 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Bc3 Nc6 12. Nf3 {, White wins the pawn on [e5].}) 10. e3 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3] White stabilizes the position in the center. A possible endgame is in White's favor as the pair of bishops is a long-term advantage.} Ne7 11. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2c3,Gf2f3,Ge2d4] Flexible development of the knight: 🔹it supports the [d4]-pawn; 🔹it can go to [c3] targeting both [d5] and [b5]; and, 🔹it allows for [f3], if White is to expand in the center by [e4].} Qxg3 {The following is self-explanatory.} 12. hxg3 O-O 13. Nc3 {[%csl Bh7][%cal Ge1c1,Gf1d3,Gd3h7,Gh1h7,Gf2f3,Gg3g4] The endgame is very favorable for White. 💡We can combine play in the center and the kingside with [O-O-O], [Bd3], [f3], [g4] and so on.} *

