1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nc6 {Black develops and keeps the options with the f-pawn open.} 3. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gf3d4,Gf3e5] As in the majority of cases, White plays for [d4].} g6 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gf8g7,Rg7d4,Rc6d4,Re5d4] This is a somewhat tricky move order because now White cannot play the Botvinnik Setup recommended in the corresponding chapter – the knight is already on [f3].} 4. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] The knight on [f3] also has positive aspects – White can execute the central thrust [d4] before Black fianchettoes the bishop and takes control of the [d4]-square.} exd4 ({Keeping the tension with} 4... d6 {and hoping for a King's Indian set-up is met by} 5. dxe5 Nxe5 {or 5...dxe5 6.Qxd8 Kxd8 7.b3 intending [Bb2] and [O-O-O] with good play for White 6.Bf4 Bg7 7.c5! Nxf3 8.exf3 with initiative in the center.}) ({White reacts similarly to} 4... Bg7 {with} 5. dxe5 Nxe5 6. Nxe5 Bxe5 7. g3 {with easy play after [Bg2], [O-O] thanks to the control of the long diagonal and the central [d5]-square.}) 5. Nxd4 Bg7 {[%cal Rc6d4,Rg7d4]} ({Black cannot avoid the doubling of the c-pawns as} 5... Nge7 $2 6. Bg5 Bg7 7. Nd5 {wins for White!}) 6. Nxc6 {White doubles Black's c-pawns whichever way Black recaptures.} dxc6 ({In case of} 6... bxc6 7. g3 Ne7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Bg5 {White has easy development Qd2 and [Rad1] are coming, there is pressure on the [h1]-[a8] diagonal and the [c6]-pawn, better pawn structure and space advantage.}) 7. Qxd8+ {White gains tempi for development by exchanging queens.} Kxd8 8. Bg5+ {[%cal Gg5d8,Ge1c1] White develops with tempo. The bishop frees the path for the long castle.} Ke8 ({Playing} 8... f6 {doesn't change much, after} 9. O-O-O+ Ke8 10. Bd2 {White will continue with the same plan as in the main line, by preparing the advance of the kingside pawns.}) 9. O-O-O {[%csl Ye8][%cal Gd1d8,Gg5d8,Gd8e8] With the not-too-hidden threat of [Rd8] mate.} Be6 {[%cal Re6c4]} 10. e4 {[%csl Be4,Bf2,Bg2,Bh2][%cal Gf2f3,Gf1e2,Gg5e3,Gc1c2,Gf3f4] White has a pawn majority on the kingside while Black's extra pawn on the queenside is a doubled one, which means that Black can never create a passed pawn there. This practically means that White plays as if he's a pawn up. 💡The plan is to: 🔹consolidate first with [f3], [Be2], [Kc2], [Be3]; 🔹then eventually [f4], starting to advance slowly the kingside majority.} *

