1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nc6 {Black develops and keeps the options with the f-pawn open.} 3. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gf3d4,Gf3e5] As in the majority of cases, White plays for [d4].} f5 {This move is the most aggressive one. Black would like to develop along the lines of the Grand Prix Attack in the Sicilian Defense: ...[Nf6], ...[Bc5], ...[O-O], ...[d6] followed by an attack with ...[f4], ...[Qe8]-[h5] etc.} ({The move} 3... Bc5 {is too simplistic, the bishop is rendered passive after} 4. e3 d6 5. a3 a5 {otherwise White expands with [b4], [Bb2] and then decides whether to play [d3] or [d4]} 6. d4 Ba7 7. Be2 Nf6 8. O-O {followed by [b4] and the bishop on [a7] won't see much action.}) ({Similarly sub-optimal is} 3... d6 {, as after} 4. d4 {White obtains an advantage, for example:} Nf6 5. d5 Ne7 6. e4 {already threatening [c5]} b6 7. Bg5 {and Black is worse on both wings.}) 4. d4 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] The standard move for White, which changes the character of the position. Now instead of the Grand Prix Attack, Black will have to play an inferior reversed French structure.} e4 5. Nd2 ({The move} 5. Bg5 {would be desirable, as before playing [e3], White would like to exchange the dark-squared bishop. But Black has the unpleasant} Be7 6. Bxe7 Qxe7 7. Nd2 e3 $1 {with complications.}) 5... Nf6 ({If} 5... Nxd4 $6 6. Ndxe4 {and, after the retreat of the two knights, White has an excellent position.}) 6. Ndb1 $1 {[%cal Gc1g5,Ge2e3] An unexpected move with a sound positional idea: before playing [e3] White wants to get the dark-squared bishop outside of the pawn chain to [g5].} h6 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Gh6g5] Black wants to stop White's idea.} ({In case of} 6... Bb4 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. Nxc3 d6 9. Bg5 {, White won't mind the exchange [Bxf6]. Indeed, after [e3] he will have an ideal French scenario: a sound structure, better bishop and easy play on the queenside.}) ({Similar is} 6... d6 7. Bg5 Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. g3 {stopping [f4] ideas with ideas like [Nd2], [Be2], [b4] and play on the queenside or [Bxf6] followed by [Nd5] and [N1c3].}) 7. e3 {White couldn't play [Bg5], but at least forced Black to lose a tempo on ...[h6].} Bb4 {Black also wants to get rid of his dark-squared bishop before playing ...[d6].} ({After} 7... d6 8. b4 Be7 9. b5 {followed by [a4], [Be2] and [Nd2], White has already started playing on the queenside.}) 8. a3 {[%cal Rb4c3] Forcing Black to take on [c3] and winning the bishop pair. For the time being the bishop pair doesn't count for much, but the dark-squared bishop can become very potent on the long diagonal if White manages to open it by pushing [d5].} Bxc3+ 9. Nxc3 d6 10. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8,Ga3a4,Gc1a3,Ga3f8] The pawn moves to [b3] so that after ...[d5] White has the [c4]-pawn protected and has the option after ...[dxc4] to recapture [bxc4], not allowing Black to take control of the [d5]-square. Additionally, now the bishop can also come to [a3] after [a4] and become active on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal.} O-O 11. Be2 {White completes development of the kingside and awaits Black's actions in the center.} Ne7 12. a4 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8,Gc1a3,Ga3f8] This advance keeps both options open for the bishop: it can be developed on [b2] or on [a3].} d5 ({If Black prepares ...d5 by} 12... c6 {, then White plays} 13. d5 $1 {and opens the long diagonal for the bishop, which will be very strong on [b2].}) 13. Ba3 {[%cal Ga3f8] The bishop is now active on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal.} c6 14. cxd5 {White opens the c-file that he plans to use for his queenside play.} cxd5 15. Qd2 $1 {[%csl Ba3,Be2][%cal Ge1c1,Gd1c1,Gc1c8,Gc1b2,Gh2h3,Gg2g4,Ga1c1] 💡A surprising concept: 🔹White plans queenside castling! After [O-O-O] and [Kb2], the king will be perfectly safe on the queenside, while White can still use the c-file after [Rc1]. 🔹But it's also possible to play on the kingside by preparing [g4] and eventually attacking the black king. White still has the pair of bishops, both of which are well-placed, and given the possibility to play on both wings, White has a promising middlegame ahead.} *

