[GameId "2102815303441915"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} d6 {With this move Black signals that he will either play in KID-style with ...[Nd7], ...[g6], etc. or will play ...[f5], ...[Nf6], ...[Be7] with Dutch motifs.} (2... d6 {This is a tricky move order to meet as, for example, after} 3. g3 Nc6 {3...f5 is another extra option for Black White can no longer play the lines with [d4] that were possible after 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 f5 4.d4 .}) 3. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gd2d3] A developing move that White usually plays against most moves. The intention is to push [d4], but White can also play [d3], as in this line.} g6 {Black opts for King's Indian development when White can no longer play the Botvinnik Setup because the knight is already on [f3]. Therefore, White switches to a Sicilian set-up with [d3].} ({After} 3... f5 {, White's standard reaction to the advance of the f-pawn is} 4. d4 {and after} e4 5. Ng1 {keeping the [c1]-[h6] diagonal open for the dark-squared bishop} Nf6 {or 5...Be7 6.Bf4 6.Bg5! White achieves the aim of developing the bishop outside the pawn chain before playing [e3]. Then after [e3], [Nge2]-[f4], [h4] White obtains a solid position on the kingside and can continue with queenside play. The move 3...Nd7 is also met by 4.d3 with similar play as in the main line because after 4.d4 g6 White cannot force an endgame like in the line 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d4 d6 5.dxe5 and will be forced to play a King's Indian. To avoid that, White switches to a Sicilian development, Scheveningen style. A set-up where Black doesn't play ...g6 after 3...Nd7 4.d3 is 4...f5 5.e3 Ngf6 6.Be2 Be7 7.O-O O-O 8.b4 with a play on the queenside with [a4]-[a5], [b5] or [c5].}) 4. d3 Bg7 5. e3 {The lines with [g3] have a lot of theory and are well-explored. On the other hand, the Scheveningen set-up for White is rare and offers more chances for independent play.} Nf6 {Black develops in KID style.} ({In case of} 5... f5 6. Be2 Nf6 7. O-O O-O {, White has the important motif} 8. c5 $1 {which takes advantage of the fact that the exchange of White's c-pawn for Black's e-pawn after} dxc5 $6 9. Qb3+ Kh8 10. Nxe5 {is in White's favor. Otherwise, White takes [cxd6] and continues to play on the queenside with [b4]-[b5], [Qb3], [a4], [Ba3] and so on.}) 6. Be2 {White continues with the development and castles next.} O-O 7. O-O {[%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Gc1b2] White completed the development of the kingside and in usual Sicilian fashion will play on the queenside by advancing the b-pawn. This will also allow for the development of the dark-squared bishop on the long diagonal on [b2].} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4,Gb2b4] It's natural for Black to stop [b4].} 8. a3 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4] White prepares [b4] with [a3] and [Rb1].} c6 {[%cal Gf8e8,Ge8e5,Gd6d5,Gc6d5] With this move, Black wants to play in the center by pushing ...[d5].} ({In case of} 8... Nc6 9. Rb1 {, White continues with [b4]-[b5]. Black can try to simplify the position after} Re8 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 e4 12. dxe4 Nxe4 13. Nxe4 Rxe4 {. But White keeps the game going after} 14. b5 Nb8 15. Nd4 {with ideas like, [Bf3], [Bb2] and so on.}) 9. Bd2 {[%cal Gb2b4,Gd1a1] White prepares [b4] by developing and defending the rook on [a1].} Re8 {[%cal Rd6d5,Ge8e5] By defending the pawn on [e5] Black prepares ...[d5].} 10. Qc2 $1 {[%cal Gc2c8,Gc4d5] A prophylactic move that anticipates ...[d5] and the subsequent opening of the c-file after [cxd5], so White places the queen on the file that will be opened.} ({In case of} 10. b4 axb4 11. axb4 Rxa1 12. Qxa1 e4 $1 {Black uses the vulnerability of the queen on the long diagonal to simplify the position.}) 10... d5 {Black follows through with his plan.} ({After} 10... Na6 11. Ne4 {prepares [b4], while 10...Nbd7 11.b4 allows White to start queenside play.}) 11. cxd5 {White opens the c-file.} cxd5 12. d4 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] White fixes the center.} e4 {Taking on [d4] would give White play against the IQP.} 13. Ne5 {[%csl Bb6,Bc5,Bc7,Be5,Yg7][%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c8,Bc3b5,Bb5c7,Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gc2b3,Ga4b6] In this reversed French structure White is well-placed for queenside play. The rook from [f1] can come to [c1], [Nb5] will threaten [Nc7]. Other ideas are [Qb3], [Na4]-[b6]c5. Additionally, Black's fianchettoed bishop is passive and will need to be redeployed with [Bf8]-[d6].} Nbd7 {Black must exchange the centralized knight.} 14. Nxd7 {White gains tempo by exchanging to continue play on the queenside.} Bxd7 15. Rfc1 {[%csl Bc7,Bd6][%cal Gc1c8,Gc3b5,Gb5d6,Gb5c7,Bc3a4,Gc2b3,Ba4c5] 💡White has ample play on the queenside: 🔹 The knight has the option to go to [b5] with [Nb5] from where it controls the [d6]-square, thus preventing the activation of Black's dark-squared bishop with [Bf8]-[d6] and threatens [Nc7]. 🔹 Another option is [Na4]-[c5] or -b6 aided with [Qb3]. White's play on the queenside is much faster than anything Black can come up with on the other wing.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
