[White "2) The Reversed Sicilian 1…e5"]
[Black "Reversed Sicilian: 2...Nf6 with 3...e4"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A22"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[GameId "2102815303470588"]

1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} e4 {[%cal Re4f3] This attack is actually a pawn sacrifice that only recently became popular. Play is rather forced now.} 4. Ng5 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gg5e4,Gc3e4,Gd1c2,Gc2e4] Black cannot defend the pawn on [e4] as if necessary White can attack it a third time with [Qc2].} c6 {[%cal Rd7d5] Black intends to gain time for development by harassing White's knight in the center.} ({In case of gambit play after} 4... b5 $6 5. d3 $1 exd3 6. cxb5 h6 7. Nf3 dxe2 8. Bxe2 {, White has smooth development and pressure in the center, while the pawn on b5 prevents the natural development of Black's queenside.}) 5. Ngxe4 {White takes the pawn.} Nxe4 6. Nxe4 d5 {[%cal Rd5e4,Rd5c4]} 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Ng3 ({The attacked knight steps out of the way, since} 8. Nc3 d4 9. Ne4 Nc6 {gives Black initiative.}) 8... h5 {[%csl Yg3][%cal Rh5h4,Rh4g3] Black continues to go after the knight.} ({After} 8... Nc6 9. d4 h5 10. e3 {we have a transposition.}) 9. e3 {[%cal Gg3e2] White frees the [e2]-square for the knight.} ({Playing} 9. h4 $6 {only gives the [g4]-square to the bishop after} Bg4 {.}) 9... h4 {[%cal Rh4g3]} ({Black can also start with} 9... Nc6 10. d4 h4 11. Ne2 {, with a transposition.}) 10. Ne2 {No other square to go to.} Nc6 11. d4 {[%cal Ge2c3] The knight wants to complete the full circle and return to [c3].} Qf6 {[%cal Gf6g6,Rg6g2,Rg6b1] Black's intention is to use the queen on the [g6]-square, from where it controls the [b1]-[h7] diagonal for possible [Nb4] ideas and slows down White's development of the kingside: the bishop on [f1] needs to defend the pawn on [g2].} 12. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gf1d3] The knight completes the full circle by returning to [c3] with tempo. It also frees the bishop on [f1] to be developed on [d3].} Qg6 $1 {[%cal Rg6g2,Rg6b1] Black sacrifices a second pawn for lead in development. Defending the pawn on d5 allows 12...Be6?! 13.Bd3! when White develops the kingside and Black's compensation diminishes.} 13. f3 {[%cal Ge1f2,Gf2g2,Gf1d3]} ({Taking on d5 is possible, but after} 13. Nxd5 Bd6 {, White still hasn't addressed the main problem of his position. White's main problem is the development of the kingside. With [f3] White plans [Kf2] and [Bd3], solving the development of the kingside.}) 13... Bd6 14. Kf2 {[%csl Bg2][%cal Gf1d3,Gf2g2] White defends the pawn on [g2] and will play [Bd3] next.} Bg3+ {A trick to slow down the development of the rook on [h1] by forcing the king to [g1].} ({In case of} 14... Bf5 $6 15. Nxd5 {White already threatens [e4].}) 15. Kg1 {[%cal Gh2g3]} ({Of course, White cannot take on g3 since} 15. hxg3 $4 hxg3+ 16. Kg1 Rxh1+ 17. Kxh1 Qh6+ 18. Kg1 Qh2# {would be embarrassing. Now the bishop is hanging.}) 15... Bd6 ({If the bishop drops back all the way to b8 then after} 15... Bb8 $6 16. Bd3 Bf5 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 18. Qb3 {Black has problems with the defense of the pawns on [d5] and [b7].}) 16. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gf1d3] Forcing the bishop to [b8] at the expense of weakening the pressure on the center.} ({The point is to stop Black from castling long, i.e.} 16. Bd3 Bf5 17. Bxf5 Qxf5 {and Black can castle long next with fine compensation.}) 16... Bb8 17. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3g6] White slowly untangles his kingside.} Bf5 18. Bxf5 {The bishop was hanging, so White continues with tempo.} Qxf5 19. Bd2 {[%cal Gg1f2,Gd1b1,Gb1d3] White almost finished development. 💡Next is to: 🔹let the rook on [h1] come into play. This will be done by [Kf2]; 🔹play [Qb1]-[d3], so we take back some light-square control from the black queen. Black has certain compensation for the pawn, but White has a compact position and if Black doesn't find something concrete it will be easy to lose all compensation.} *

