1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} d6 {This move allows [d4].} 5. d4 {White takes over the center.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg4d1,Ge5d4,Gc6d4] With the pin on the knight on [f3] Black puts pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} ({In case of} 5... exd4 6. Nxd4 g6 7. Be2 Bg7 8. Bg5 h6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Qd2 Re8 11. f3 {followed by [Nc2], [Rd1] and [O-O] White has solid control of the center, in a much superior version than in similar KID positions. In some lines White may even consider a kingside attack with [O-O-O], [g4], [h4] etc.}) 6. d5 {[%cal Gd5c6] White had no other way to defend the pawn.} Nd4 7. Be2 {[%csl Gd4,Gg4][%cal Gf3d4,Ge2g4] White develops the kingside, breaks the pin and doesn't mind exchanges as he has a space advantage and a better dark-squared bishop, both of which guarantee easier play.} Nxe2 {Black can also take on f3 and try to keep the knight on d4 alive: 7...Bxf3 8.Bxf3 c5 9.dxc6 bxc6 10.Be3 c5 but after 11.a3 and [b4], White successfully plays on the queenside. He will castle and double on the b-file, while the transfer of the bishop from [f3] to [d3] will strengthen White's control of the light squares in the center.} 8. Qxe2 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] Going for KID development.} ({The alternative development with} 8... Be7 {is met by} 9. h3 Bd7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne1 {with ideas to play on the queenside with [Nd3] and [c5] or in the center by pushing [f4].}) 9. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4,Gg4d1] White wants to get rid of the pin on the [d1]-[h5] diagonal.} Bd7 {Black must at least try to keep the important light-squared bishop.} 10. Bg5 {[%csl Gf6][%cal Gg5d8]} ({White can play in different ways, for example, the immediate} 10. c5 {is also promising, but I've found that plans with long castling are annoying against the KID as they offer White possibilities to attack on the kingside. With the pin on the knight on [f6] White wants to provoke the weakening ...[h6].}) 10... Bg7 11. O-O-O {[%csl Gc1][%cal Gc1b1] White's king will be safe on the queenside. If necessary, it can move to [b1], or even [a1].} O-O 12. g4 {[%cal Gf3e1,Ge1d3,Gf2f3,Gh3h4,Gh4h5] This is White's idea. 💡It is possible to further improve the position with [Ne1]-[d3], [f3], [h4]-[h5] with an attack on the kingside. White has easy play in this position, while Black is passive without a clear plan.} *

