1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} d6 {This move allows [d4].} 5. d4 {White takes over the center.} exd4 {The main move for lower-level players, made by them about half the time.} 6. Nxd4 g6 {Black aims for a King's Indian set-up, but White obtains very good play after...} 7. Be2 Bg7 8. Bg5 {[%cal Gd1d2,Gd2h6,Gg5d8] Pinning the knight and intending [Qd2], which would prevent ...[h6] in case Black castles.} h6 {Black should try to get rid of the pin.} 9. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge3d4,Gd2h6] The bishop retreats to cover the knight on [d4], while at the same time, White still plans [Qd2].} O-O 10. Qd2 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Gd2h6] Developing with tempo by attacking the pawn on [h6].} Re8 {Black counterattacks in the center.} 11. f3 {Defending the central pawn. 💡White now plans: 🔹 either [Nc2], [Rd1] and [O-O], with solid control of the center; 🔹or [O-O-O], [g4] and [h4] with a kingside attack.} *

