1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} Bc5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4,Rc6d4,Ge5d4]} ({This move is the main alternative to} 4... Bb4 {. It leads to sharper play. Both moves aim to stop White's [d4].}) 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Gd2d4] Thanks to this trick based on the forking motif, White manages to push [d4]. Play obtains a forcing character now.} O-O {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gf8e8,Re8e1,Rf6e4] Black speeds up the development and aims to regain the pawn with play on the e-file.} ({Taking on f2 is bad, as after} 5... Bxf2+ $2 6. Kxf2 Nxe5 7. d4 {White obtains a fantastic center and the bishop pair.}) ({The pawn sacrifice after} 5... Qe7 {is best met by} 6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Be6 8. f3 $1 {with [Qe2] and [Be3] to follow.}) 6. Nf3 {[%csl Bc4,Bd3,Be4][%cal Gd2d3,Gd3e4] White retreats the hanging knight and wants to play [d3] to defend the [e4]-pawn.} Nxe4 {Otherwise White plays [d3] and remains a pawn up.} 7. Nxe4 {[%cal Ge4c5] White accepts the temporary sacrifice.} Re8 {[%cal Re8e1] Black will regain the piece thanks to the pin on the e-file. During that time, White will finish the development of the kingside and castle.} 8. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gf1e2,Ge1g1] White defends the knight and intends [Be2] and [O-O].} f5 {[%cal Rf5e4,Ge8e1] The only way to regain the piece.} 9. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White blocks the e-file and plans to castle.} fxe4 10. dxe4 {[%csl Yc5,Yg8][%cal Gd1d5,Gd5g8,Gd5c5] For the time being, the pawn on e4 is taboo given the check on d5: 10...Rxe4? 11.Qd5+ Re6 wins the bishop on [c5].} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7c5] Black defends the bishop.} ({A transposition after} 10... d6 11. O-O Qe7 {is possible.}) 11. O-O {[%csl Yg8][%cal Gd1d5,Gd5g8] White has a safe position now and Black has certain problems due to the somewhat open position of the black king.} d6 {Taking on e4 is dangerous: 11...Qxe4? 12.Bd3 Qg4 13.Bxh7! Kxh7 14.Ng5 wins the queen on [g4] and shows the dangers that Black faces.} 12. Kh1 {[%cal Gf3d2,Gf2f3] Removing the king from the [g1]-[a7] diagonal and intending [Nd2] and [f3] to defend the extra [e4]-pawn.} Qxe4 {Now Black can take the pawn. The reason is that after:} 13. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7]} Qg4 {[%cal Gc8g4] The trick [Bxh7] doesn't work as after ...[Kxh7], [Ng5] the queen on [g4] is not lost as it is defended by the bishop on [c8].} 14. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] Chasing the queen away from the defended square, opening a luft for the king, and controlling the [g4]-square.} Qh5 15. Ng5 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gd1h5,Gd3h7,Gg5h7] A double attack on the queen and the pawn on [h7]. A series of forced moves follows.} Qxd1 16. Bxh7+ {[%csl Rg8][%cal Gh7g8]} Kh8 17. Rxd1 {[%csl Yf2]} Bxf2 18. Bg6 {[%csl Yh8][%cal Gg6e8,Gb2b3,Bb2h8,Bc1b2,Gc1f4] 💡 What conclusions can be drawn from the position? 🔹Black's king is limited in its movement; 🔹White has good piece play in the endgame... 🔹... while the opposing camp still needs to finish development.} *

