1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} Bc5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4,Rc6d4,Ge5d4]} ({This move is the main alternative to} 4... Bb4 {. It leads to a sharper play. Both moves aim to stop White's [d4].}) 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Gd2d4] Thanks to this trick based on the forking motif, White manages to push [d4]. The play obtains a forcing character now.} Nxe5 {This is Black's main move.} ({Taking on f2 is bad, as after} 5... Bxf2+ $2 6. Kxf2 Nxe5 7. d4 {White obtains a fantastic center and the bishop pair.}) ({The pawn sacrifice after} 5... Qe7 {is best met by} 6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Be6 8. f3 $1 {with [Qe2] and [Be3] to follow.}) 6. d4 {[%csl Yc5,Ye5][%cal Gd4c5,Gd4e5] White regains the piece.} Bb4 7. dxe5 {[%cal Ge5f6]} Nxe4 8. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3e4,Gf3c3] White develops the queen on an active position. It attacks the knight on [e4] and defends the knight on [c3] at the same time.} Nxc3 ({The simplest move, though the sharp} 8... f5 {, luring the queen to [f5] so that ...[d5] can come with tempo, is also possible. After} 9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. a3 $1 Bc5 11. bxc3 d6 12. Bf4 O-O 13. O-O {, Black suffers because of the weakening caused by the movement of the f-pawn – it limits the activity of the bishop on [c8] and enfeebles the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. These factors give White the easier game.}) 9. bxc3 Ba5 {This is the alternative, leading to very sharp play.} 10. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Ge1c1] White develops and plans long castling. In view of the attack on the [c3]-pawn by the bishop on [a5], the idea [Qg3] makes less sense as White cannot really take on [g7]: in that case, the pawn on [c3] would hang with check.} O-O 11. O-O-O {[%cal Bf1d3,Gc1b2,Bd3h7,Gd1d3,Gh1d1,Gd1d7] The white king will be safe on the queenside, for example, after [Kb2] to stop ...[Qa3] ideas, while White's central preponderance gives him easy play and the initiative. White can combine play on the kingside with play along the d-file.} Rb8 {[%cal Rb7b5] Black prepares counterplay with ...[b5], but White can keep the b-file closed.} ({In case of} 11... Qe7 12. Kb2 Rb8 13. Qe3 {, we have a transposition.}) 12. Qe3 {[%csl Ya5,Yb8,Ya7][%cal Ge3a7,Ga7b8,Ga7a5] Threatening [Qxa7], with double attack on the rook on [b8] and the bishop on [a5].} Qe7 {[%cal Re7a3] Black threatens ...[Qa3].} 13. Kb2 {[%cal Gb2a3] White covers the [a3]-square.} b5 {Black wants to open the b-file, but White can keep it closed by moving the c-pawns forward.} 14. c5 {[%cal Rb8b2] Whenever the black b-pawn moves forward, White's adjacent pawn c- or a- will move ahead to avoid the exchange and keep the b-file closed.} b4 15. c4 b3 16. a3 {[%csl Bb3] Both sides followed their plans. White kept the b-file closed and his king safe, while Black now has a passed pawn on [b3]. However, this pawn will certainly be lost in an endgame, making piece exchanges in White's favor.} Bb7 {Black develops the light-squared bishop.} 17. Qd4 {[%csl Yd7,Yh7][%cal Gd1d7,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gf2f3,Bf1d3,Bd3h7,Gd1d3,Gh1d1] White immediately attacks the [d7]-pawn that the light-squared bishop no longer protects. 💡White has several ways to further improve the position: 🔹the advance of the h-pawn as far as possible; 🔹the move [f3] to block the long diagonal and limit the activity of the black light-squared bishop; 🔹double the rooks on the d-file; 🔹develop the bishop to [d3]. Black suffers from lack of space, but any attempt to free the game, for example by ...[f6], would likely lead to an endgame after [exf6] [Qxf6], [Qxf6]. And in this endgame, Black is in danger of losing the [b3]-pawn without any compensation.} *

