1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} Bc5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4,Rc6d4,Ge5d4]} ({This move is the main alternative to} 4... Bb4 {. It leads to sharper play. Both moves aim to stop White's d4.}) 5. Nxe5 {[%cal Gd2d4] Thanks to this trick based on the forking motif White manages to push [d4]. Play obtains a forcing character now.} Nxe5 ({This is Black's main move. Taking on f2 is bad, as after} 5... Bxf2+ $2 6. Kxf2 Nxe5 7. d4 {, White obtains a fantastic center and the bishop pair.}) ({The pawn sacrifice after} 5... Qe7 {is best met by} 6. Nxc6 dxc6 7. d3 Be6 8. f3 $1 {with [Qe2] and [Be3] to follow.}) 6. d4 {[%csl Yc5,Ye5][%cal Gd4c5,Gd4e5] White regains the piece.} Bb4 7. dxe5 {[%cal Ge5f6]} Nxe4 8. Qf3 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gf3e4,Gf3c3] White develops the queen on an active position. It attacks the knight on [e4] and defends the knight on [c3] at the same time.} Nxc3 {The simplest move.} ({However, the sharp} 8... f5 {, luring the queen to [f5] so that ...[d5] can come with tempo, is also possible. After} 9. Bd3 Nxc3 10. a3 $1 Bc5 11. bxc3 d6 12. Bf4 O-O 13. O-O {Black suffers because of the weakening caused by the f-pawn-push. Indeed, it: 🔹limits the activity of the bishop on c8🔹weakens the [a2]-[g8] diagonal These factors give White the easier game.}) 9. bxc3 Bc5 ({The safer choice for Black. The retreat to e7 is not very good as} 9... Be7 $6 10. Qg3 g6 11. Bh6 {pinpoints the problem of the black king: it cannot find a safe haven anywhere. See the game Carlsen-Giri for the details.}) 10. Qg3 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gg3g7] White immediately targets the pawn on [g7].} Kf8 {[%cal Gf8g7] The only move.} ({Castling is bad in view of} 10... O-O $2 11. Bh6 {.}) ({Whereas} 10... g6 $2 11. Bh6 {fatally weakens the dark squares on Black's kingside.}) 11. Bd3 {[%csl Gf8][%cal Ge1g1] White continues the development. White's main advantage is the difficulty Black has in connecting the rooks in view of the uncastled king.} d6 {Black needs to develop the queenside.} 12. Bf4 {[%cal Gg3b8,Ge1g1,Ga1d1,Gd1d8] White develops and puts pressure on the [h2]-[b8] diagonal.} dxe5 ({Black will have to take on e5, sooner or later. It's possible to try to advance the h-pawn, for example,} 12... h5 13. O-O h4 14. Qf3 h3 15. g3 {, but White is nicely ahead in development and will centralize the rooks with [Rad1], [Rfe1]. The bishop can drop back to [f1] to target the [h3]-pawn, while Black still hasn't solved the problem with the king.}) 13. Bxe5 {[%csl Yc7,Yg7][%cal Ge5g7,Ge5c7,Gg3g7] White wins a pawn now, but Black speeds up the development and prevents White's castling.} f6 14. Bxc7 Qe7+ 15. Kf1 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gh1h4,Gh4a4,Gf1g1,Gg1h2,Gh5h6]} ({This is better than} 15. Be2 Bf5 {since then, White cannot easily untangle from the pin on the e-file. Now White has two ideas on how to unravel the kingside and both involve the advance of the h-pawn. After [h4]-[h5] White can consider: 🔹Rh4 to activate the rook along the fourth rank,🔹or [Kg1]-[h2] to connect the rooks on the first rank. The [h5]-pawn will also be useful to further weaken Black's kingside by advancing to [h6] when appropriate.}) 15... Be6 16. h4 {[%cal Gh4h5] The advance of the h-pawn is very useful for White.} Rc8 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Rc8c7,Ge7c7]} 17. Bf4 {[%csl Yf8][%cal Gh4h5,Gh1h4,Bf1g1,Bg1h2,Ga1d1,Gh1e1,Ge1e8,Gd1d8,Bd3e4,Be4a8,Gh5h6] 💡White has the aforementioned ideas of: 🔹h5, [Rh4]; or, 🔹Kg1-[h2]. 🔹The [a1]-rook can also come to [e1] to allow [Be4]; while, 🔹the joint development of the rooks on [d1] and [e1] is also possible. The position is complex, but White is a pawn up and long-term has the safer king as the h-pawn advancing to [h6] can weaken Black's kingside shelter.} *

