rity.} 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White defends the [e4]-pawn, fending off the threat of ...[Bxc3] and ...[Nxe4].} ({A curious alternative worth exploring is} 5. Bd3 $5 {.}) 5... d6 6. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White will castle and then will continue depending on Black's responses.} O-O 7. O-O {[%csl Bd5,Bf5][%cal Gd3d4,Gf2f4,Gf3e1,Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3d5,Bf3d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Ge3f5] Generally speaking, White has two main and one minor idea in the position: the main ideas are the pawn breaks [d4] and [f4], while the minor idea is the transfer of the knight to the [d5]-square by [Ne1]-[c2]-[e3] or [Nd2]-[f1]-[e3]. The ensuing variations evolve around the implementation of these ideas. Black has several options now.} Bg4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gg4f3,Gc6d4,Gf3d4] Black attacks the [f3]-knight, thus fighting for control of the [d4]-square.} 8. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] Since the fight is for the [d4]-square, White goes after the dark-squared bishop, now that it makes little sense for Black to take on [c3] since after [bxc3] White would cover the [d4]-square, rendering Black's idea useless.} Bc5 9. b4 {[%cal Gb4c5] Still going after the bishop.} Bb6 ({In case of the immediate} 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Bd4 11. Bd2 {, White will continue with [g3], [Bg2], [Kh1], and eventually [f4], achieving one of the pawn breaks, with kingside play incoming.}) 10. Na4 {[%cal Ga4b6] White will obtain the bishop pair now.} Bxf3 {With this exchange Black obtains control of the [d4]-square.} ({After} 10... Nd4 11. Nxb6 Nxe2+ 12. Qxe2 axb6 13. h3 ({𓈓13... Bxf3 Qxf3 , White can combine three ideas: pushing [d4], pushing [f4] and doubling on the a-file and pushing [a4]-[a5]. 𓈓13... Be6} 13. d4 {gives White a space advantage.})) 11. Bxf3 Bd4 {[%csl Gd4][%cal Gd4a1]} 12. Rb1 a6 {[%cal Gd4a7]} 13. Bd2 {[%csl Bd4,Be5,Bd6,Bc7][%cal Gd1e1,Gf3d1,Ga4c3,Gg1h1,Gf2f4] White completes development. Black has good control of the dark squares in the center. But White has a very solid position and can play around that control. 💡The plan to execute [f4] is to: 🔹bring the knight back to [c3]; 🔹play [Qe1] and [Bd1]; 🔹followed by [Kh1] and [f4]. This will give White play on the kingside.} *

