1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} Bb4 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Rb4c3,Gf6e4] This is the most common move for Black and the main line.} ({The move} 4... g6 {allows} 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bd2 {with [O-O-O] and [f4] to come.}) {White obtains a similar position to the one from the variation 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4 Bg7 6.Nxc6 dxc6 7.Qxd8 Kxd8 8.Bg5 Ke8 9.O-O-O when the plan is to advance with the kingside majority.} 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White defends the [e4]-pawn, fending off the threat of ...[Bxc3] and ...[Nxe4].} ({A curious alternative worth exploring is} 5. Bd3 $5 {.}) 5... d6 6. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White will castle and then will continue depending on Black's responses.} O-O 7. O-O {[%csl Bd5,Bf5][%cal Gd3d4,Gf2f4,Gf3e1,Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3d5,Bf3d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Ge3f5] Generally speaking, White has two main and one minor idea in the position: the main ideas are the pawn breaks [d4] and [f4], while the minor idea is the transfer of the knight to the [d5]-square by [Ne1]-[c2]-[e3] or [Nd2]-[f1]-[e3]. The ensuing variations evolve around the implementation of these ideas. Black has several options now.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7g6,Gc7c6] With the knight maneuver to [g6] Black strengthens the kingside and also allows for ...[c6], to control the [d5]-square.} 8. Ne1 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Ge1c2,Gf2f4,Gc2b4,Gc2e3] With no more need to guard the [d4]-square White prepares two of the main ideas: the [f4] advance and the transfer of the knight via [c2] to [e3], which would attack the bishop on [b4] along the way.} Bxc3 ({If Black tries to preserve the bishop after} 8... Ng6 9. Nc2 Bc5 {, White achieves the [f4] advance after} 10. Kh1 {and [f4].}) 9. bxc3 Ng6 {[%cal Rg6f4,Ge5f4] Now that Black has good control of the [f4]-square, White concentrates on the advance in the center with [d4].} 10. Nc2 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc2e3,Ge3d5] White improves the position of the knight first. The immediate [d4] is not possible because the [e4]-pawn is hanging for now.} c6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc6d5] Black also covers the [d5]-square.} 11. f3 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gf3e4,Gd3d4,Gf1f2,Ge2f1,Gf1e1] White defends the [e4]-pawn and is now ready for [d4].} d5 {It's critical to check what happens if Black becomes active in the center. Otherwise, White will either play [d4] or prepare the push with [Rf2], [Bf1] or [Re1] and [Bf1].} 12. cxd5 {White gets rid of the doubled pawns first.} cxd5 13. c4 $1 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move that attacks Black's center. Now both options that Black has, advancing or exchanging, are good for White.} d4 ({After} 13... dxe4 14. dxe4 {, White has the clear-cut plan of planting a knight on [d5] via [b4].}) 14. f4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gf4f5] White didn't achieve [d4], but successfully reached [f4].} ({An alternative is the move} 14. Nb4 {, intending [Nd5].}) 14... Nxf4 ({After} 14... exf4 15. Bb2 {White will win the [d4]-pawn.}) 15. Bxf4 {The knight has to be captured.} exf4 16. Qd2 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Gd2f4,Ga1b1] White wants to capture on [f4] with the queen, as that would place it on a dominant central position. Be aware that in case of: 16...Be6 , if 17.Qxf4 , Black can sacrifice Bxc4 . Then, White, in order not to see his pieces on the second rank forked, should push the e-pawn 18.e5 Nd5 19.Qxd4 . If Black defends the f4-pawn with 16...g5 , then after 17.h4 h6 18.hxg5 hxg5 19.g3 , White is better prepared for the opening of the position on the kingside.} *

