1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White develops the knight and reinforces the control of the [d5]-square.} Nf6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd7d5,Gf6d5] The most commonly-played move, fighting for control of the [d5]-square.} ({A move like} 2... f5 {can be met by} 3. d4 {a typical reaction for White to Black's lateral advance is to strike in the center and then} e4 4. Nh3 Nf6 5. Bg5 {gives White a favorable version of the French.}) ({This 'f5-line' is to be compared with:} 2... Nc6 3. Nf3 f5 4. d4 e4 5. Nd2 {after the exchange of the dark-squared bishop followed by [e3], [Nf4], [h4] to stabilize the kingside.}) ({Taking on d4 is worse, as 3...exd4 4.Qxd4 Nf6 5.g3 Nc6 6.Qe3 followed by [Bg2] gives White a superior pawn structure Black weakened his position with ...[f5] and central control. The move} 2... c6 $6 {is met by} 3. d4 {.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf3e5] The usual developing move for White, attacking the pawn on [e5].} Nc6 {This is the most natural: developing and defending the pawn on [e5].} ({In case of} 3... d6 4. d3 g6 5. e3 Bg7 6. Be2 {, we have a transposition to the lines after 2...d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 Bg7 5.e3 Nf6 6.Be2 .}) 4. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5] The most direct way to stop ...d5. White establishes a firm grip in the center and plans to develop with d3, Be2 and O-O. White's play is reminiscent of the Anti-Sveshnikov line in the Sicilian, arising after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Nc3 e5 . Some of White's ideas in the English were borrowed from Magnus Carlsen's ideas for Black in the Anti-Sveshnikov, as can be seen in the model game Svidler-Carlsen.} Bb4 {[%csl Yc3,Ye4][%cal Rf6e4,Rb4c3] This is the most common move for Black and the main line.} ({The move} 4... g6 {allows} 5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4 Bg7 7. Nxc6 dxc6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Bd2 {with [O-O-O] and [f4] to come.}) {White obtains a similar position to the one from the variation 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d4 exd4 5.Nxd4 Bg7 6.Nxc6 dxc6 7.Qxd8 Kxd8 8.Bg5 Ke8 9.O-O-O when the plan is to advance with the kingside majority.} 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White defends the [e4]-pawn, fending off the threat of ...[Bxc3] and ...[Nxe4].} ({A curious alternative worth exploring is} 5. Bd3 $5 {.}) 5... d6 6. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White will castle and then will continue depending on Black's responses.} O-O 7. O-O {[%csl Bd5,Bf5][%cal Gd3d4,Gf2f4,Gf3e1,Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3d5,Bf3d2,Bd2f1,Bf1e3,Ge3f5] Generally speaking, White has two main and one minor idea in the position: the main ideas are the pawn breaks [d4] and [f4], while the minor idea is the transfer of the knight to the [d5]-square by [Ne1]-[c2]-[e3] or [Nd2]-[f1]-[e3]. The ensuing variations evolve around the implementation of these ideas. Black has several options now.} Bc5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4,Rc6d4] This is main move for Black, increasing the control of the [d4]-square. This indicates that White should switch to the other pawn break, namely the [f4]-push.} 8. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2b3,Gb3c5,Gg1h1] The motif from the model game Svidler-Carlsen. White intends [Nb3], to go after the dark-squared bishop, but also [Kh1] and [f4].} a5 {[%cal Gc5a7] Black provides an escape square for the bishop.} ({The alternative is} 8... Nd4 {, but White simply continues with the plan after} 9. Nb3 Nxb3 10. axb3 {with [Kh1] and [f4] next.}) 9. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5] White goes after the bishop and controls the [d4]-square again.} Bb6 {[%cal Ra5a4] Black wants to lure White's [c3]-knight to [a4] before escaping to [a7].} ({After} 9... Ba7 10. Kh1 {, White executes [f4] next, with active play on the kingside.}) 10. Na4 {[%cal Ga4b6]} ({White should oblige, as the immediate} 10. Kh1 {is met by} a4 $1 {.}) 10... Ba7 11. Kh1 {[%csl Yg1][%cal Ra7g1,Gf2f4] White removes the king from the [g1]-[a7] diagonal and prepares [f4].} Bd7 {[%csl Ya4,Bd4][%cal Rd7a4,Rc6d4] Black targets the knight on [a4] after ...[Nd4].} ({An alternative is to fight f4 with ...f5 with} 11... Nd7 12. f4 f5 {, though after} 13. exf5 Rxf5 14. Nc3 {, White brings the knight back to control the light squares [e4] and [d5] in the center. White's pieces are better placed for the opening of the position because the knight on [d7] blocks the bishop on [c8].}) 12. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] The knight retreats from the vulnerable position and assumes control of the [d5]-square. 💡White's plan is to: 🔹push [f4] next with active play on the kingside; 🔹if allowed continue with [f5]; and, 🔹 develop a direct attack on the black king by further advancing with [g4].} *

