[White "Introduction: QGD Systems 1…e6"]
[Black "Introduction: The QGD Systems"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "7"]
[GameId "2102815303704070"]

1. c4 e6 {[%cal Rd7d5] If White doesn't want to transpose to the QGD by pushing [d4] there are two possible options. Both of these keep the d-pawn on [d2]: 🔹the Réti lines with [g3]; 🔹or the lines with [e3]. The main question is the move order: how to play either? I decided in favor of the lines with [e3] with the move order starting with:} 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] This move was necessary because of possible transpositions to other lines, but also because with it White avoids the Queen's Indian set-ups with ..b6.} (2. Nf3 {is the usual way for White to start, but I decided against it because Black gets a wide choice after} Nf6 ({🔹Against the Réti option, g3 , Black has two main lines: to push ...[d5] or to play in QID style with ...[b6]. I was not thrilled to allow either. 🔹 e3 playing with [e3] and trying to go for the lines we reach in our repertoire allows the extra option of} 2... b6 {, which is quite sound. So why allow it? This is another reason for choosing 2.Nc3, avoiding this extra option for Black.}) ({🔹3. Nc3 is a major move. But instead of} 2... d5 {, which would transpose to our lines after} 3. e3 {, Black has two additional major variations, which are 3...Bb4 and 3...c5 ; and a minor one like 3...b6 .}) ({Morevover, in the 'Réti line' – g3 – after} 2... d5 {note that b6 is also a very important line with a lot of theory: 𓈓4. Bg2 , and here Black can either dxc4 or play 4...Be7 , both of which are extremely well-explored. If: 𓈓4. b3 Be7 Bg2 O-O O-O , and here Black again has a wide choice of plans: with ...[c5] and ...[b6], only with ...[b6], with ...[c6], with ...[a5], when at a later stage the knight on [b8] can be developed to [a6], [c6] or [d7]. Just too diverse!})) 2... d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] The usual QGD move.} ({Against} 2... Nf6 3. e4 $1 {cuts down Black's options and this is analyzed in the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4,Rd5d4] Stopping ...[d4].} Nf6 ({The only additional option that Black gets with this move order is the very rare} 3... d4 {, though after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 {, White has a good development.}) ({The move} 3... c5 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {would transpose to the lines analyzed with a later ...[c5]. Therefore, by avoiding the masses of extra theory and additional lines after Nf3 , White manages to considerably cut down Black's options via the move order 2.Nc3 d5 3.e3 .}) 4. Nf3 {We have reached the starting position of the lines with [e3].} *

