1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} Bb4 {[%cal Rb4c3] A move in line with the ideas in the Nimzo-Indian. The difference is that Black still hasn't played ...[Nf6], so White can take over the center immediately.} 3. e4 {[%cal Gc4b5,Gc4d5,Ge4d5,Ge4f5] White now has good control of the center.} c5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4] Black also fights for the center. This has been Kramnik's post-retirement choice.} ({After} 3... Ne7 4. Nf3 O-O 5. a3 Bxc3 6. dxc3 d6 7. c5 $1 {is a promising pawn sacrifice to open the position. White obtains great compensation after} dxc5 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bf4 {as Black has problems with the defense of the pawn on [c7] and the development of the queenside.}) 4. a3 {[%cal Ga3b4] Forcing Black to exchange the bishop.} Bxc3 ({Black runs big risks after} 4... Ba5 $6 5. b4 $1 cxb4 6. Nb5 {with tremendous initiative.}) 5. dxc3 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gd1d6] White opens the d-file where the [d6]-square is particularly sensitive.} Nc6 6. Bd3 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gf2f4,Gg1f3,Gc1e3,Gd1e2,Be1c1,Gd3c2,Gd1d8] White will return to the d-file after finishing development. The plan is to play [f4], [Nf3], [Be3] and then [Qe2], [O-O-O] and [Bc2].} d6 7. f4 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gc1e3] White follows the plan as Black can do little to stop it.} Qh4+ {[%csl Re1][%cal Rh4e1] Forcing [g3] doesn't affect White's plan.} 8. g3 Qe7 9. Qe2 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gc1e3,Ge1c1] White simply puts the pieces on the intended squares. After} b6 10. Nf3 Bb7 11. Be3 O-O-O 12. O-O-O {[%cal Gd3c2,Gg3g4,Gh2h4,Gg4g5,Gh4h5,Ge4e5] With [Bc2] next, White has a very comfortable position. 💡Please be aware that: 🔹the pawn on [d6] will always require attention; and, 🔹White can advance on the kingside with [g4], [h4] etc. Should also be monitored: 🔹the central breaks [e5] and [f5], as they may bring immediate tactical gains.} *

