1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} c5 {A rare move order, but it's worth exploring as it offers Black additional options apart from the transpositions.} 3. e4 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gd2d4] Just like in the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6, White intends [Nf3] and [d4].} Nc6 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White is ready for [d4].} ({Note that in case of} 4. Nge2 Nd4 $1 {White doesn't have the [Bd3] at his disposal.}) 4... e5 ({The move} 4... Nf6 {leads to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6 after White plays} 5. d4 {.} ({Similar are a6} 5. d4 {and 4...d6 5.d4 . By closing the center, Black hopes for a protracted struggle. But White is now two tempi up Black moves second, plus the lost time on ...[e6]-[e5] and can obtain some initiative by advancing on the queenside.}) ({Another option that doesn't transpose is} 5. Nd4 {Bd3} Ne7 {Nxd4 cxd4 Ne2} 6. Nc6 {Bc2 followed by [d3], [O-O] when White can activate the bishop via the [a4]-square and expand with [f4] and [Ng3] on the kingside.})) 5. d3 d6 6. a3 {[%cal Gb2b4] White threatens to take over the initiative on the queenside with [b4].} a5 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ga5b4,Gc5b4,Gc6b4] This stops [b4], but only temporarily.} ({In case of} 6... g6 7. b4 Nge7 8. Rb1 Bg7 9. bxc5 dxc5 10. g3 {White will fianchetto the light-squared bishop and castle short. That done, the knight will land on [d5] with a more pleasant position thanks to: 🔹the dominating knight; 🔹the more compact pawn structure; and, 🔹the semi-open b-file.}) ({The move} 6... Nf6 {makes little sense, because it lands Black in a symmetrical position with two tempi less. White simply continues with queenside play after} 7. Rb1 {.}) 7. Be2 ({Since Black spent one more move not developing, it's faster for White to finish development like this, compared to the fianchetto with} 7. g3 {, which is also a possible way.}) 7... g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Gg8e7,Rf7f5,Ge8g8] Ideally, Black would like to play ...[Bg7], ...[Nge7], ...0-0 and ...[f5], but White is much faster with play on the queenside.} 8. Bg5 {[%cal Gg5d8] A disruptive move, forcing ...[f6] if Black is to stay on course with the planned development.} f6 9. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2b4,Gb2b4] From [d2] the bishop will support the [b4] advance once the knight moves from [c3]. White has practically finished development, needing only to castle, while Black is far from doing the same. In a closed position, this is not fatal, but it does give White the initiative.} Bg7 10. Qa4 {[%cal Ga4e8,Ga4a8,Gb2b4] The queen pins both the knight on [c6] and the pawn on [a5], thus intending [b4].} Be6 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Gd8a8,Ga5b4,Ra8a4] This prevents [b4] by defending the rook on [a8].} 11. Nb5 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Gb5d6,Gb5c7] White starts to use the weaknesses Black allowed by pushing ...[a5].} Nge7 12. b4 {[%csl Bb5,Bd5][%cal Gb4c5,Ga1b1,Gb1b7,Ge1g1] White achieved the [b4] advance. 💡On that basis: 🔹the opening of the b-file after [bxc5] is allowed; 🔹White will castle; and, 🔹use the b-file to put more pressure on Black's position. 🔹At the same time, he will use the strong outposts on [b5] and [d5] as necessary.} *

