1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb7h1] Black immediately wants to solve the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop.} 5. b4 $1 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb4b5,Gc1b2,Gb2h8,Ya4e8] White takes space on the queenside: 🔹using the fact that the [a4]-[e8] diagonal is open; 🔹exploiting Black's 4...b6 move, which weakened the [c6]-square, making ...[Nc6] no longer possible. At the same time, the [b2]-square is made available for the dark-squared bishop.} Bb7 ({The point of White's last move was:} 5... Bxb4 $4 6. Qa4+ {wins the bishop on [b4].}) 6. Bb2 {[%cal Gb2h8] Developing the bishop on the long diagonal is a standard development for White in all these lines.} dxc4 {[%cal Rb7h1] Black opens the long diagonal.} ({In case of} 6... a6 7. cxd5 exd5 {otherwise White obtains a pawn advantage in the center} 8. Ne2 Bd6 9. Ng3 {followed by [Be2] and [O-O] leads to a compact concentration of white pieces on the kingside. White can use the [f5]-square for a knight jump. Or, in case Black plays ...[g6] to stop that threat, the idea of [Nd4] with [f4]-[f5] can pose serious challenges to the opponent's position. At the same time, White can also play on the queenside with the standard minority attack with [a4], [b5], etc.}) 7. Bxc4 {[%cal Gc4g8,Gb2h8] White's bishop are actively developed now.} Nbd7 ({After} 7... c5 8. bxc5 Bxc5 9. d4 {followed by [O-O], [Qe2], [Rac1], [Rfd1], [e4] White has very active position in the center.}) ({In case of} 7... a6 8. b5 {intending [a4]} axb5 9. Bxb5+ c6 10. Be2 {, the [c6] and [b6] pawns are somewhat loose and White can play against them by fixing them with [a4] and playing along the b- and c-files.}) 8. b5 {[%csl Ba7,Bc7][%cal Gb5a6,Gb5c6] Fixing Black's pawns, which will inevitably lead to exchanges on [b5] as Black lacks space on the queenside.} a6 {[%cal Ra6b5]} 9. a4 {[%csl Gb5][%cal Ga4b5] White wants to keep the pawn on [b5], which gains space on the queenside.} axb5 10. axb5 {[%csl Bb5]} Rxa1 11. Qxa1 {[%cal Ga1h8] Developing the queen along the way.} Be7 12. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3,Rb7f3] Covering the knight before castling, so that ...[Bxf3] won't break White's kingside structure.} O-O 13. O-O {[%csl Bc6,Yc7][%cal Gd2d3,Gf1c1,Gc1c7,Gf3d4,Gd4c6,Gd3d4,Ga1b1,Gb1c2] 💡What should we bear in mind in this position? 🔹White has the advanced [b5]-pawn that fixes the pawn on [c7]. 🔹In case of an exchange of Black's c-pawn for White's b-pawn, Black will remain with a weak [b6]-pawn that can be attacked. 🔹If the pawn structure on the queenside remains as it is, then White can improve the position of the pieces with [Rc1], [Qb1]-[c2], [d3] or [d4], [Nd4]-[c6] playing on the queenside and trying to use the pressure on the c-file and the weak [c6]-square.} *

