1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} dxc4 {Black plays in the style of the Queen's Gambit Accepted.} 5. Bxc4 a6 {[%cal Rb7b5,Gc8b7]} ({Black can start with} 5... c5 {, but after a subsequent ...[a6], [a4] play will transpose.}) ({The move} 5... Be7 {is possible, though it will likely transpose at a later stage when Black plays ...[a6] and ...[c5], for example} 6. O-O O-O 7. b3 {and White develops along the same lines with [Bb2], [Ne2]-[g3], etc.}) ({Another option is} 5... Bb4 $6 {, but that is just bad after} 6. Qa4+ Nc6 7. Nd4 {and Black has problems defending the knight on [c6] and the bishop on [b4].}) 6. a4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga4b5,Rb7b5] Stopping Black's expansion.} ({Another interesting way to play with White is in hedgehog style with} 6. O-O b5 7. Be2 Bb7 8. b3 Be7 9. Bb2 O-O 10. Rc1 c5 11. a4 $1 b4 12. Nb1 {with [d3], [Nbd2] next and White will seek to use the strong [c4]-square combining it with play on the c-file putting pressure on the [c5]-pawn by doubling the rooks, putting a knight on [e4] and play in the center with [e4] or [d4], depending on circumstances.}) 6... c5 7. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] White develops along the usual lines.} Nc6 8. Bb2 Be7 9. O-O {The calmer approach.} ({The aggressive one with} 9. g4 $5 {is also possible and it leads to sharp play. For example, if Black takes the pawn} Nxg4 {then} 10. Rg1 h5 11. Qe2 {with [O-O-O] next, gives White plenty of compensation.}) 9... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black's only reasonable way to develop the light-squared bishop.} 10. Ne2 {[%csl Bf3,Bg3][%cal Ge2g3,Gb2h8] This regrouping, sending the knight to [g3] to open the long diagonal for the bishop on [b2] and concentrate forces on the kingside, is the key idea for White in this variation.} Bb7 11. Ng3 {[%csl Bb2,Bc4,Bf3,Bg3] White has a harmonious development.} O-O 12. Qe2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge3e4,Gf3g5,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd3d4,Ge4e5] Connecting the rooks. White is now fully prepared for the middlegame ahead. 💡The main ideas for White are as follows: 🔹the advance in the center with [d3] and [e4] this will limit the bishop on [b7] and will introduce ideas like [Ne5] followed by [f4]; 🔹advance with [d4]; 🔹playing [Ng5] to free the path for the f-pawn; and, 🔹if [h6], we replace our adventurous knight on [h3]... 🔹followed by [f4]-[f5] and/or [e4] to come with an attack on the kingside.} *

