1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} c5 {[%cal Rd5d4,Gc5d4] An active move in the center that controls the [d4]-square. Now Black threatens ...[d4], so White needs to take on [d5].} 5. cxd5 Nxd5 {By taking with a knight, Black avoids the positions with an IQP.} ({After the other recapture} 5... exd5 6. Bb5+ Nc6 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 {, we will have a transposition to the chapter The Symmetrical English 1…c5, the line analyzed after:}) {1.c4 c5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 e6 5.e3 d5 6.Nc3 Nc6 7.cxd5 exd5 8.Bb5 .} 6. Bc4 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gc4d5] White develops and controls the [d5]-square. In some cases taking on [d5] can become an option.} Be7 7. O-O {Now both sides develop.} O-O 8. Qe2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1d8,Gd2d4] Since White will advance with [d4], the queen liberates the [d1]-square for the rook.} Nc6 9. Rd1 {[%cal Gd2d4] White is ready to push [d4].} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb7h1] Black's only way to develop the light-squared actively.} 10. d4 {[%csl Yd5,Yd8][%cal Gd4c5,Gd1d8,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] White advances in the center and already threatens [dxc5], which would expose Black's knight on [d5] and the queen on [d8].} Nxc3 {Black releases the tension in the center.} ({In case of} 10... cxd4 11. Nxd5 $1 {here the control of the [d5]-square comes in handy} exd5 12. Nxd4 {thanks to the attack on the knight on [c6] and the semi-open d-file White obtains a strong attack on the IQP on [d5].}) 11. bxc3 {[%csl Yd8][%cal Gd4c5,Gd1d8] White again threatens to win a pawn by taking on [c5], so Black must move the queen.} Qc7 12. e4 {[%csl Bd4,Be4][%cal Gd4d5,Ge4e5] White obtains a pawn center that can be used to advance it further: with [d5] – obtaining a passed pawn, or with [e5] – useful as a focal point for a kingside attack.} Bb7 13. Be3 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gc1c8,Gd1d8] White develops and now the queen's rook can come to [c1].} Rac8 {[%cal Gc7b8,Ga1c1,Gc1c7,Rf8d8,Rd8d1,Rc5d4] Anticipating [Rac1], Black frees the [b8]-square for the queen. Additionally, the rook is placed on the c-file that Black plans to open by ...[cxd4]. The most natural development for the black rooks is to place them on [c8] and [d8].} ({In case of} 13... Rfd8 {White can continue with the same} 14. d5 {, with similar play. If Black decides to open the c-file now, after 13...cxd4 14.cxd4 Rac8 15.d5 is still good. After 15...exd5 16.Bxd5 White's better central control still gives him some initiative, with ideas on the kingside like [Ng5] or [h4]-[h5]-[h6].}) 14. d5 {[%cal Gd5c6,Gd5e6] White nips Black's idea to open the c-file with ...[cxd4] in the bud.} ({In case of} 14. Rac1 cxd4 15. cxd4 Ba3 {, Black starts some activity on the queenside.}) ({An interesting alternative is the Lc0's idea of} 14. h4 $5 {with the aim to advance the h-pawn as far as possible.}) 14... exd5 15. exd5 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gd5c6]} ({It's also possible to take with the bishop,} 15. Bxd5 Rfe8 16. h4 $5 {with the intention of [h5]-[h6] or [Nh2]-[g4].}) 15... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] Attacking the bishop on [c4].} ({Going to e5 allows the pin with Bf4,} 15... Ne5 16. Bf4 Nxf3+ 17. Qxf3 Bd6 18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. a4 {when White has a strong passed pawn on [d5] and Black has a passive bishop on [b7].}) 16. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gc3c4,Gd3e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5] The bishop retreats and now White wants to support the [d5]-pawn with [c4] or [Be4].} Bxd5 {Getting rid of the the dangerous pawn.} 17. Bxh7+ {[%cal Gd1d5] Thanks to this discovered attack White regains the pawn and weakens the shelter around Black's king.} Kxh7 18. Rxd5 {[%csl Yc7,Ye7,Yh7][%cal Ge2d3,Gd3h7,Gd5d7,Gd7c7,Gd7e7,Gd3d7,Be3g5,Bf3g5,Be2h5] Black's king has been weakened. 💡White can play to take advantage of that weakness: 🔹the immediate threat is [Qd3]+ followed by [Rd7], with a double attack on the queen on [c7] and the bishop on [e7]; 🔹another threat is [Bg5], aiming for an exchange on [g5] when the knight can come to that square, creating threats like [Qh5].} *

