1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Bd6 {A flexible move that allows for different set-ups later on. The bishop is more active on [d6] than on [e7], but it's also more exposed to attacks with [Nb5].} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] Standard development for White, the bishop will be very good on the long diagonal.} O-O 6. Bb2 {In this position Black has a wide choice.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb7h1] Black wants to solve the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop by fianchettoing it to [b7].} 7. cxd5 {A timely exchange. The point is that if Black takes with a pawn, then the queenside structure has been weakened by the move [b6] Black would rather have the pawn on [b7], so that after [c6] the structure is compact, while in case of a recapture with a knight, White obtains two central pawns, d and e, against a sole e-pawn for Black.} exd5 ({After} 7... Nxd5 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Ne4 {White either gains the bishop pair or obtains strong initiative after} Be7 10. h4 $1 {with the idea of [Neg5].}) 8. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6] The more forcing choice, taking advantage of the exposed position of the bishop on [d6].} ({An interesting alternative is} 8. g3 {, with the automatic development, [Bg2], [O-O], [Rc1] when White will use the [d4]-square for a knight to exert pressure on the [c6]-square or pawn.}) 8... Be7 9. Be5 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Ge5c7,Gb5c7,Ga1c1,Gc1c7] Black experiences certain discomfort on the [c7]-square.} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7]} ({Or} 9... Na6 10. Rc1 c5 11. a3 {followed by [d4], when Black cannot easily get rid of the knight on [b5].}) 10. Qc2 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Gc2c7,Gb5c7,Ge5c7] White will win a pawn now.} ({But there is also} 10. Bd3 a6 11. Nbd4 {with ideas like [Qc2] and [Nf5].}) 10... c5 ({The move} 10... Na6 11. a3 {doesn't solve Black's problems, as the knight on [a6] is offside.}) 11. Bxb8 {[%csl Ya7][%cal Gb5a7] Black loses the [a7]-pawn.} Rxb8 ({The intermediate move} 11... a6 {doesn't help as} 12. Be5 axb5 13. Bxb5 {also wins a pawn. Note that with the queen on [c2] and the rook on [a1], the pawn on [a2] is protected on the a-file, which wouldn't have been the case had White played [Rc1] instead of [Qc2] on move 10.}) 12. Nxa7 {[%csl Yb8,Yd8][%cal Ga7c6,Gc6b8,Gc6d8] Now the threat is [Nc6].} Bd7 13. Nb5 {The knight easily escapes from [a7].} Nd6 14. Nxd6 {Exchanging in order to win a tempo to finish development.} Bxd6 15. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] With [O-O] next. 💡What we can emphasise here is that: 🔹White has a solid position and an extra pawn. 🔹Black has some compensation with the bishop pair, but nothing concrete so far.} *

