1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Bd6 {A flexible move that allows for different set-ups later on. The bishop is more active on [d6] than on [e7], but it's also more exposed to attacks with [Nb5].} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] Standard development for White, the bishop will be very good on the long diagonal.} O-O 6. Bb2 {In this position, Black has a wide choice.} dxc4 {An exchange similar to the Queen's Gambit Accepted.} 7. Bxc4 {White only needs to castle to finish development now.} a6 {[%cal Rb7b5,Gc8b7] In QGA style, Black wants to expand with ...[b5] in order to develop the bishop on [b7].} 8. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2h7,Gc2c8] The usual development for the queen, looking down the c-file and the [b1]-[h7] diagonal. This move also opens the option for a long castle.} ({White's} 8. a4 {wouldn't have stopped Black's development after} b6 {with ...[Bb7] next.}) 8... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 9. Bd3 {[%cal Gc2h7,Gb2h8,Gc3e4,Gf3g5] White can create threats on the kingside thanks to the long-range pieces on the [a1]-[h8] and [b1]-[h7] diagonals, combined with the knights approaching with [Ne4] and/or [Ng5].} Bb7 {[%cal Rb7h1] Black also develops.} 10. a4 {[%csl Yb5][%cal Ga4b5,Gc3b5,Gd3b5] White can combine play on both wings. The first target is the pawn on [b5].} c6 {[%cal Gc6b5,Ga6b5]} ({Taking on a4 would leave the a6-pawn exposed, while advancing} 10... b4 11. Ne4 {gives White queenside targets on the c-file after} Nxe4 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13. Qxe4 {with [Rc1] to come.}) 11. axb5 {This capture is motivated by tactical motifs: after [Ne4] and exchange on [e4], White will recapture [Bxe4] when the bishop on [b7] would be attacked, not giving Black a chance to close the [b1]-[h7] diagonal by ...[f5].} cxb5 {[%cal Rb7h1]} ({In case of} 11... axb5 12. Rxa8 Bxa8 13. O-O {Black has a passive bishop on [a8].}) 12. Ne4 {[%csl Yf6,Yh7][%cal Gb2h8,Ge4f6,Ge4g5,Gd3h7] White now turns the attention to the kingside.} Nxe4 ({Going for simplifications is safer as} 12... Be7 13. Neg5 h6 14. Bh7+ Kh8 15. h4 {gives White a dangerous attack and even though Black should be able to defend, doing so is anything but simple and easy.}) 13. Bxe4 {[%cal Ge4b7,Ge4h7] A double attack on the pawn on [h7] and the bishop on [b7]. If White hadn't inserted the exchange on [b5] Black would have been able to play ...[f5] here.} Bxe4 14. Qxe4 {[%csl Ya8][%cal Ge4a8]} Nd7 15. Qd4 {[%csl Yg7,Yd6][%cal Gb2g7,Gd4d6] An alternative is to simple castle and play [Rfc1] next.} Nf6 16. g4 $5 {[%csl Be1,Yg7,Yf6][%cal Gg4g5,Gg5f6,Gd4g7,Gb2g7,Ge1e2] An unexpected attack with the direct threat of [g5], which isn't easy to defend against. 💡White has the initiative even in a possible endgame for example after [Be7], when the queens will be exchanged as, in that case, he would already have a centralized king.} *

