1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Bd6 {A flexible move that allows for different set-ups later on. The bishop is more active on [d6] than on [e7], but it's also more exposed to attacks with [Nb5].} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] Standard development for White, the bishop will be very good on the long diagonal.} O-O 6. Bb2 {In this position, Black has a wide choice.} Nc6 {[%cal Re6e5,Rd5c4,Rc8g4] An idea from the Ragozin Defense. Black wants to release the tension in the center with ...[dxc4] and follow up with ...[e5], solving the problem of the development of the light-squared bishop by opening the [h3]-[c8] diagonal.} 7. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c8] White anticipates the opening of the c-file.} dxc4 {Black continues with his plan.} 8. Bxc4 {White completes development.} e5 9. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6] Going after the bishop pair.} a6 {[%cal Ra6b5]} 10. Nxd6 {Now White has the advantage of the bishop pair.} cxd6 11. O-O {[%csl Bb2,Bc4][%cal Gc4e2,Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Gf3e1,Gf2f4] White's pair of bishops is counter-balanced by Black's solid position. Nevertheless, the bishops are a long-term advantage. 💡Quid facere? White will: 🔹retreat the bishop to [e2], to avoid being attacked by [d5]; and, 🔹advance on the queenside with [a3] and [b4], to gain some space there. 🔹also monitor the situation in the center; and, 🔹seek ways to undermine Black's center either... • by pushing [f4] after [Ne1] to open the long diagonal, • or by [d4], though that move must be carefully planned to avoid leaving White in a bad French structure.} *

