1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Bd6 {A flexible move that allows for different set-ups later on. The bishop is more active on [d6] than on [e7], but it's also more exposed to attacks with [Nb5].} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] Standard development for White, the bishop will be very good on the long diagonal.} O-O 6. Bb2 {In this position, Black has a wide choice.} Re8 {[%cal Re6e5]} ({Like the move} 6... Nc6 {, Black prepares the freeing move ...[e5]. Now, after White's next move, play becomes concrete.}) 7. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5d6,Gb2f6,Gb5c7] A multiple attack. White goes after the bishop on [d6], but also threatens [Bxf6], as seen in the next comment.} Be7 {[%cal Ge7f6]} ({White's idea is seen after} 7... Bf8 $6 8. Bxf6 $1 gxf6 {this is the point, Black must keep the queen on [d8] in order to prevent [Nxc7]} 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 {with an advantage to White due to his superior pawn structure and the Black weaknesses on the kingside.}) 8. Be5 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Ge5c7,Gb5c7] Attacking the pawn on [c7] and forcing Black to put the knight on the rim on [a6].} Na6 {[%cal Ga6c7]} 9. Be2 {After disrupting the coordination of Black's pieces, White continues with the development.} c6 10. Nc3 Nc5 {[%csl Yd3,Ye5][%cal Gc5d7,Rd7e5,Rd5c4,Gc5d3,Rd8d3] Black wants to bring the knight back into the game via [d7], at the same time hitting the bishop on [e5]. Another threat is to take on [c4] and give the check on [d3]. The latter point makes White's next move understandable.} 11. Qc2 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Gc2d3,Ge2d3] White develops the queen and covers the [d3]-square.} Ncd7 {[%cal Rd7e5] Black continues with his plan.} 12. Bg3 {[%csl Yc8][%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d4,Ge2d3,Ge3e4] White has a stable position. 💡No need to be a fortune-teller to figure that out: 🔹White will continue with [O-O] and [d4]; 🔹Black will have problems with the development of the light-squared bishop; 🔹while White will aim to organize the [e4] advance with ideas like [Bd3] and [e4]; 🔹the rooks will come to [c1], [d1] or [e1], depending on Black's chosen set-up.} *

