1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Bd6 {A flexible move that allows for different set-ups later on. The bishop is more active on [d6] than on [e7], but it's also more exposed to attacks with [Nb5].} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] Standard development for White, the bishop will be very good on the long diagonal.} O-O 6. Bb2 {In this position, Black has a wide choice.} c5 {The most active move for Black.} ({Note that the moves} 6... Nbd7 7. Be2 c6 {and 6...c6 7.Be2 transpose to the Slav set-ups analyzed in the chapter on the Slav.}) 7. cxd5 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3e4] White takes on [d5] with the aim to fix Black's pawn on [d5] with [d4] in case of [exd5] or to obtain the [e4]-square for the knight in case of [Nxd5].} ({Worth mentioning is the very sharp} 7. g4 $5 {, which leads to double-edged play. See the model game Giri-Warmerdam for the details.}) 7... Nxd5 {Black avoids the positions with an IQP, but this move gives White a chance to start a dangerous kingside initiative.} 8. Ne4 {[%csl Be4,Yh7][%cal Ge4d6,Gb2g7,Gd1c2,Be4g5,Gc2h7,Bg5h7] White doesn't necessarily want to take on [d6] immediately, but will keep that option in case Black doesn't move the bishop. More important is the opening of the long diagonal and the option of placing a knight on [g5], which combined with a queen and/or bishop on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal can create dangerous threats against Black's king.} ({This move is more ambitious compared to} 8. Nxd5 {, as it seeks to start an attack against Black's king.}) 8... Be7 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Ge7g5] Black retreats the bishop and covers the [g5]-square.} 9. g4 $1 {[%cal Gh1g1,Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] White starts a pawn storm on the kingside. Thanks to White's good control of the center, it's not easy for Black to counter this attack.} Nc6 10. Rg1 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] Intending [g5] and [h4]-[h5].} f6 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Gf6g5] Still controlling the [g5]-square.} ({To show how dangerous White's attack is, after natural moves like} 10... b6 11. g5 Kh8 {not good, but it avoids possible [Nf6] tricks} 12. h4 Bb7 13. h5 {and White's attack is already decisive.}) 11. a3 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ga3b4,Gd1c2,Gc2h7,Gf1d3,Rc6b4,Rd5b4] A very important move for White in similar positions. It's vital to have the [b4]-square under control so that the queen can comfortably be developed on [c2] and also possibly the bishop to [d3], not fearing attacks after ...[Nb4] and allowing for continuous threats along the [b1]-[h7] diagonal.} e5 {Black erects a pawn chain on the long diagonal to defend against the potent bishop on [b2]. However, this weakens the light squares.} 12. Rc1 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Gc1c5,Ge4c5] Developing with tempo by attacking the pawn on [c5]. The king will be quite safe in the center and there is no need to connect the rooks as each is working on its own file.} b6 {[%cal Gb6c5]} 13. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4g8]} ({The alternative} 13. Bb5 {is also good.}) 13... Kh8 14. g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5f6] The following is an illustration of the power of White's attack.} f5 15. Nxe5 $1 {[%cal Gb2h8,Ge5c6] By sacrificing a piece White forces the opening of the long diagonal.} Nxe5 16. Bxe5 fxe4 17. Qh5 {[%csl Yh8,Yg7][%cal Gh5h6,Gg5g6,Ge5h8] White already has a decisive advantage. 💡There are too many threats to defend against: 🔹Bxg7; 🔹followed by [Qh6] and [g6]: • pushing [g6]; or, • simply [Qh6].} *

