1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Bd6 {A flexible move that allows for different set-ups later on. The bishop is more active on [d6] than on [e7], but it's also more exposed to attacks with [Nb5].} 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gb2h8] Standard development for White, the bishop will be very good on the long diagonal.} O-O 6. Bb2 {In this position, Black has a wide choice.} c5 {The most active move for Black.} ({Note that the moves} 6... Nbd7 7. Be2 c6 {and 6...c6 7.Be2 transpose to the Slav set-ups analyzed in the chapter on the Slav.}) 7. cxd5 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gc3e4] White takes on [d5] with the aim to fix Black's pawn on [d5] with [d4] in case of [exd5] or to obtain the [e4]-square for the knight in case of [Nxd5].} ({Worth mentioning is the very sharp} 7. g4 $5 {, which leads to double-edged play. See the model game Giri-Warmerdam for the details.}) 7... exd5 {The more classical recapture, leading to positions with an IQP after White's next move.} 8. d4 {[%csl Yd5] White fixes the pawn on [d5], which will become an IQP once the [d4] and the [c5] pawns are exchanged.} Nc6 9. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White has a harmonious development and will finish it by castling.} cxd4 {If Black doesn't take on [d4] White can time the capture on [c5], for example by preparing it with [Rc1].} 10. Nxd4 {[%csl Yd5] White has standard play against the isolated queen's pawn. Objectively, Black has enough activity for equal play. But, as usual in the IQP positions, the long-term prospects are with the side playing against it.} Re8 {Black can also start by taking on [d4], which would lead to a transposition.} ({For example,} 10... Nxd4 11. Qxd4 Re8 12. O-O {and we're back into the main line.}) 11. O-O ({In this case, White has the additional option of} 11. Nf3 {. But Black could have avoided it by taking on [d4] on the previous move.}) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Be5 13. Qd3 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Ga1d1,Gd1d5]} ({The move} 13. Qd2 {may look more natural, but it allows Black to simplify the position by the thematic} d4 $1 {, when – thanks to the attacks on the queen after ...[dxc3] or ...[dxe3] – the tactics work for Black.}) 13... Be6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6d5,Gf6d5,Gd8d5,Gf6e4] Defending the pawn on [d5] and creating the threat of ...[Ne4].} ({Now the move} 13... d4 $6 {doesn't work so well for Black and after the forcing line} 14. Rad1 Bg4 15. exd4 Qxd4 16. Qxd4 Bxd4 17. Bxg4 Bxc3 18. Bxc3 Nxg4 19. h3 Ne5 20. f4 Nc6 21. Rd7 {, Black faces a prospectless endgame, where White can press thanks to the superior light piece and the more active rooks.}) 14. Na4 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gb2e5,Ga4b2] Preventing possible ...[d4] thrusts by establishing control of the [d4]-square. 💡Take into account that, in this position: 🔹the exchange of the dark-squared bishops is also in White's favor, as with the remaining light-squared bishops it is White's that is not limited by the IQP. 🔹Black won't be able to get rid of the isolani and this gives White long-term prospects; 🔹however, objectively, Black should be able to hold the balance.} *

