1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Be7 ({The move} 4... c6 {would transpose to the chapter on the Slav Defense.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The standard development for White in this variation.} O-O 6. Bb2 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Rb7h1] Black wants to develop the light-squared bishop as soon as possible.} 7. cxd5 {[%csl Ya7,Yb6,Yc7] 📌As a rule of thumb, White takes on [d5] the moment Black plays ...[b6] because the desirable recapture ...[exd5] would leave Black's queenside somewhat weakened. Black would prefer to have the pawn back on [b7] and to have a pawn on [c6] instead.} Nxd5 {With this recapture Black wants to keep the long diagonal open for the light-squared bishop.} ({It's possible to take with a pawn. White can then follow the plan of waiting for Black to push ...c5 in order to counter with d4 and get play against the IQP or the hanging pawns:} 7... exd5 8. g3 $1 {the fianchettoed bishop will be very useful in both of the aforementioned scenarios} Bb7 9. Bg2 c5 10. O-O Nc6 11. d4 {and White is perfectly developed to deal with Black's central pawns with whichever transformation may occur.}) 8. Nxd5 {White keeps taking on [d5], trying to force a pawn on that square. Again, Black has the choice to concede or insist on keeping the long diagonal open.} exd5 {This is the better choice, though it may feel like a concession for Black.} ({After} 8... Qxd5 9. Bc4 Qd6 {the best spot for the queen} 10. h4 $1 {White threatens [Ng5] with dangerous threats on the kingside. Black's best is} Bf6 {, though after} 11. d4 Bb7 12. Qc2 {with [O-O-O] next, White has his sights set on Black's kingside.}) 9. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White completes development and waits for Black's ...[c5], which will be met by [d4].} c5 10. d4 {[%csl Bd5] Fixing the pawn on [d5]. Black's best is to keep the tension in the center as taking on [d4] would give White easy play against the IQP.} Nc6 11. O-O a5 $1 {[%cal Ra5a4] This move introduces ...[a4] ideas on the queenside.} ({After more automatic play, White obtains a slight advantage. For example:} 11... Be6 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Qd2 {and at some point, White will take on [c5] and exert pressure on the hanging pawns with [Ba3] and with the rooks on the c and d files.}) ({Similar is} 11... Bb7 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. Qd2 Re8 14. Rfd1 Bf8 15. Bd3 {intending [Bf5] when White is creating annoying threats Ba3 may become quite an important one at some stage that Black needs to be careful about.}) 12. Qc2 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gc1c8,Gd1d8,Gc2b3,Gc2a4] The queen is placed on [c2] from where it can keep control of the [a4]-square, thus discouraging ...[a4] ideas and lends extra cover to the [b3]-pawn. The rooks will come to [c1] and [d1] next. An attack with ...[Nb4] is not dangerous as the knight can easily be chased away with [a3] later on.} Qd6 {[%cal Gd6c6,Gd6c5] The queen defends both the knight on [c6] and the [c5]-pawn.} 13. Rfd1 {[%cal Gd1d8] White centralizes the rooks.} Rd8 14. Rac1 {[%csl Bc5,Yd5][%cal Gc1c8,Gd1d8,Gh2h3,Ge2b5,Bb5c6,Ge2d3,Gd3h7,Gd4c5,Gb2c3,Gc2b2,Gc2b1,Bd3b5] White is fully mobilized. 💡The position can further be improved with: 🔹h3, [Bd3] or [Bb5]; 🔹possibly [Bc3] and [Qb2]b1; 🔹 but, generally, White's plan is to: • take on [c5] at an appropriate moment; and, • exert pressure on the hanging pawns.} *

