[GameId "2102815303945747"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Be7 ({The move} 4... c6 {would transpose to the chapter on the Slav Defense.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The standard development for White in this variation.} O-O 6. Bb2 dxc4 ({To avoid the issue of cxd5 option in the line after} 6... b6 {, Black can first take on [c4] and then play ...[b6].}) 7. bxc4 {[%csl Bc4,Gd2,Bd4][%cal Gd2d4] White takes towards the center as the follow-up is to build a pawn center with [d4].} c5 {[%cal Gc5d4] Black fights for control of the [d4]-square.} ({In case of} 7... b6 8. d4 Bb7 9. Qc2 {followed by [Be2] and [O-O], White has a pleasant space advantage that can be used to further expand either by [Rd1] and [d5] or by [c5].}) 8. d4 {The more direct move, leading to a position with hanging pawns, only this time it will be White playing with them, rather than against them.} ({An alternative is a slower maneuvering game after} 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qc2 Nc6 11. Rad1 {when White can combine several ideas: 🔹the [d4] advance at an appropriate moment; 🔹the [f4] advance after moving the knight from [f3]; 🔹the knight transfers [Ne4]-[g3] for example after setting up a battery on the long diagonal with [Ba1] and [Qb2]; 🔹or [Ne5]-[g4].} ({There is also a third option, the sharp Qc2 b6 Be2 Bb7} 11. g4 $5 {when White will most likely castle queenside and will seek to attack on the kingside.})) 8... cxd4 9. exd4 {[%csl Bc4,Bd4][%cal Gd4d5,Gc4c5] With the hanging pawns White has excellent dynamic possibilities based on their further advance: both [d5] and [c5] are possible.} b6 {[%cal Gb6c5,Ge6d5,Gc8b7,Rb7h1] Black's task is to try to stop the hanging pawns from advancing favorably.} 10. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3h7,Gb2g7,Gd4d5] The most active spot for the light-squared bishop. Together with its colleague on [b2], they are both looking towards Black's kingside.} Bb7 11. O-O {White almost finished development, what remains is to develop the queen and place the rooks on the central files.} Nbd7 {The knight is safer on [d7], on [c6] it's more susceptible to attacks with [d5].} 12. Re1 {[%csl Ye7,Ye6][%cal Ge1e7,Gd4d5,Gd5e6] The rook is useful on the e-file: in case of its opening after [d5] [exd5], the rook will be targeting the bishop on [e7].} Re8 {A useful prophylactic move by Black.} ({After} 12... Rc8 13. a4 {, the same idea as in the main line, gains in force as Black won't have a rook on the a-file after [a5] and [axb6].}) 13. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5] A typical idea for White in the positions with hanging pawns. Black is well entrenched and can deal with White's main ideas of [d5] or [c5], so White throws in another pawn into the fray. White's a-pawn is an isolated one, so White wouldn't mind exchanging it for Black's a-pawn after [a5] and [axb6]. That would allow White to get rid of an isolated pawn and would create one in Black's camp on [b6], that can further be attacked. White may also consider [a5]-[a6], to remove Black's light-squared bishop from its ideal position on [b7]. Even if the [a5]-push is a pawn sacrifice, after ...[bxa5], [c5], White obtains a protected passed pawn on [c5] that is limiting Black's pieces while the doubled a-pawns can be attacked. Note that these ideas are only in addition to the standard ones of pushing [d5] or jumping [Ne5] and seeking play on the kingside.} Bf8 14. Ne5 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gd1c2,Gc2h7,Ge1e3,Ge3h3] With the knight jump, White introduces attacking ideas like [Qc2] and [Re3] with the rook swing to the kingside.} ({The idea of} 14. a5 {is also possible, after} bxa5 15. c5 {, White has good compensation for the pawn.}) 14... Nxe5 15. dxe5 {[%csl Bd6,Yf6][%cal Ge5d6,Ge5f6]} Nd7 16. Qc2 {[%csl Bd6,Yh7][%cal Gc2h7,Gc3b5,Gb5d6,Gc3e4,Ge4d6] Attacking the pawn on [h7] and freeing the [d1]-square for the rook. With the exchange on [e5], White got two isolated pawns on the queenside, [a4] and [c4], but also access to the [d6]-square for the knight, which can be reached after [Nb5]-[d6] or [Ne4]-[d6].} h6 ({This is better than} 16... g6 $6 {as then} 17. Be4 $1 {would exchange the light-squared bishops, after which the knight will occupy the [e4]-square, with access not only to the [d6]-square, but also the [f6]-square.}) 17. Rad1 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Gd1d8,Ge1e3,Ge3g3,Bc3b5,Bb5d6,Gg3g7,Bb2g7,Ge5d6,Gc3e4,Ge4d6] White is fully mobilized and has an active position. The active possibilities in the center and on the kingside give him the initiative, though Black's position is solid. 💡The main ideas in the position are: 🔹planting a knight on [d6] via [b5] or [e4]; 🔹the rook swing [Re3]-[g3], most likely played in combination, as the capture on [d6] would open the long diagonal after [exd6] when both the rook on [g3] and the bishop on [b2] would be attacking the [g7]-pawn.} *

