1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge2e4,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Gf3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Be7 ({The move} 4... c6 {would transpose to the chapter on the Slav Defense.}) 5. b3 {The standard development for White in this variation.} O-O {To avoid the issue of cxd5 option in the line after 6...[b6], Black can first take on [c4] and then play ...[b6].} 6. Bb2 dxc4 {To avoid the issue of [cxd5] option in the line after 6...b6, Black can first take on [c4] and then play ...[b6].} 7. bxc4 {White takes towards the center, as the follow-up is to build a pawn center with [d4].} c5 {Black fights for control of the [d4]-square.} ({In case of} 7... b6 8. d4 Bb7 9. Qc2 {, followed by [Be2] and [O-O], White has a pleasant space advantage that can be used to further expand either by [Rd1] and [d5] or by [c5].}) 8. d4 {The more direct move, leading to a position with hanging pawns. The notable difference is that, this time, White will be playing with them, not against them.} ({An alternative is a slower maneuvering game after} 8. Be2 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Qc2 Nc6 11. Rad1 {, when White can combine several ideas: 🔹the [d4] advance at an appropriate moment; 🔹the [f4] advance (after moving the knight from [f3]) ; 🔹the knight transfers [Ne4]-[g3] (for example after setting up a battery on the long diagonal with [Ba1] and [Qb2]) ; or, 🔹Ne5-[g4].}) ({There is also a third option, the sharp} 8. Qc2 b6 9. Be2 Bb7 10. g4 $5 {, when White will most likely castle queenside and will seek to attack on the kingside.}) 8... cxd4 9. exd4 {With the hanging pawns, White has excellent dynamic possibilities based on their further advance: both [d5] and [c5] are possible.} b6 {Black's task is to try to stop the hanging pawns from advancing favourably.} 10. Bd3 {The most active spot for the light-squared bishop. Together with its colleague on [b2], they are both looking towards Black's kingside.} Bb7 {White almost finished his development. What remains is to develop the queen and place the rooks on the central files.} 11. O-O Nc6 {[%csl Bc6][%cal Gd4d5,Gd5c6,Rc6d4] The knight is more active on [c6], but also more liable to attacks with [d5].} 12. Re1 {[%csl Be7][%cal Gd4d5,Ge1e7] White places the rook on the semi-open e-file. This is important after the central push [d5] as after ...[exd5], the rook will immediately target the bishop on [e7].} Nb4 {[%cal Rb4d3,Rb7f3] The knight escapes the possible attack with [d5] and targets the bishop on [d3]. At the same time, Black threatens ...[Bxf3] and ...[Qxd4].} 13. Be2 {[%cal Ge2f3] One move, two aims. The bishop's retreat is aimed at defending the knight on [f3] and neutralizing Black's idea of ...[Bxf3], which now can simply be met by [Bxf3].} Rc8 {[%cal Rc8c4] Black reintroduces the idea of ...[Bxf3], when [Bxf3] will lead to the loss of the pawn on [c4].} 14. Ne5 {[%csl Be5,Yb4][%cal Ga2a3,Ga3a4,Ga4a5,Ga5b6,Ga5a6,Ge2f3,Gf3b7,Yb4c6,Gd4d5] White avoids ...[Bxf3] and centralizes the knight. 💡The position is complex and White's ideas are connected with the pawn advances: 🔹on the queenside, the pawn advance [a4]-[a5] aims to create a weak pawn on [b6] after [axb6] or gain space by arriving on [a6]; 🔹while, in the center, White still will try to push [d5] after chasing away the [b4]-knight with [a3]. 🔹Note that in case of ...[Nc6], the move [Bf3] is a powerful one, pinning the knight on [c6] and supporting the [d5]-push.} *

