1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Be7 ({The move} 4... c6 {would transpose to the chapter on the Slav Defense.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The standard development for White in this variation.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {[%cal Rd5d4] The main move for Black, threatening ...[d4].} 7. cxd5 {White avoids the threat of ...[d4] by taking on [d5]. Now White keeps taking on [d5] until a pawn lands on [d5], when he follows up with [d4], aiming for positions with an IQP.} Nxd5 8. Nxd5 {White continues with the captures on [d5].} ({A more aggressive option is the move} 8. Qc2 $5 {, see the details in the model game Karjakin-Anand.}) 8... Qxd5 9. h4 $5 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gf1c4,Gd1b1,Gb1h7,Gf3g5,Gg5h7]} ({The usual move is} 9. Bc4 {, but after} Qd8 $1 10. h4 Bf6 $1 {, thanks to the queen being on [d8], Black manages to neutralize White's dark-squared bishop and the threats on the kingside. By inverting the move order White avoids that defense.}) 9... Nc6 ({If Black insists on} 9... Qd8 {, then White doesn't need [Bc4] and can start with} 10. Ng5 {, with dangerous threats after [Qb1] or [Qh5] next.}) 10. Bc4 {[%cal Gb2g7,Gc4g8] Now White completes the development of the kingside.} Qe4 $1 {[%cal Ge4b1]} ({In case of} 10... Qd8 11. Qb1 $1 {avoiding [Nb4] attacks in case the queen goes to [c2] with [Ng5], [g4]-[g5] or [h5] to come White starts one of those long-range attacks, which are typical for several lines in this chapter. With the queen on [e4] Black prevents the white queen from occupying the [b1]-[h7] diagonal.}) 11. d3 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Gd3e4] Chasing the queen away from the dominant position.} ({White can also start with} 11. h5 h6 12. d3 {.}) 11... Qg4 {[%csl Yg2][%cal Rg4g2]} 12. h5 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gh5h6,Gb2g7,Gh6g7] Continuing the long-range attack. The threat is [h6].} h6 ({Taking on g2 loses to} 12... Qxg2 $4 13. Rg1 {and there is a disaster happening on [g7].}) 13. Kf1 {[%cal Gh1h3,Gh3g3,Gg3g7,Gd1d2,Gd2c3,Gb2g7,Gf1g2] White defends the pawn on [g2] and prepares [Rh3]-[g3] and [Qd2]-[c3].} Qf5 {Moving out of harm's way in due time.} 14. g4 $1 {[%csl Yf5][%cal Gg4f5] " Just when I thought I was out, they pulled me back in! "} Qxg4 15. Rg1 {[%csl Yg7,Yg4][%cal Gg1g7,Gb2g7] White's attack is very dangerous.} Qh3+ {[%csl Rf1][%cal Rh3f1]} 16. Ke2 e5 {[%csl Ge5,Gf6,Gg7,Yf7][%cal Gc4g8] Black needs to close the long diagonal, but this opens the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 17. Rg3 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gd1g1,Gg1g7] Preparing to double on the g-file.} Qxh5 18. Qg1 {[%csl Yg7,Yf7][%cal Gg1g2,Ga1h1,Gh1h6,Gg1g7,Gc4g8,Gb2g7] 💡With Qg2 and Rh1/Rg1 coming, White's attack is extremely difficult to defend against. The best move for Black is 18...g5 .} *

