[GameId "2102815304027671"]

1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] An important move as White intends [e4].} d5 {The QGD reply.} ({It is important to have the move e4 ready in case of} 2... Nf6 3. e4 {, when we have a transposition to the chapter The Flexible 1...Nf6.}) ({Two more transpositions are} 2... f5 {, which leads us to the chapter on the Dutch, while 2...b6 3.e4 is analyzed in the chapter The English Defense 1...b6}) 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4] White needs to stop the threat of ...[d4].} ({The move} 3. d4 {would lead to the QGD.}) 3... Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Advancing} 3... d4 {allows White after} 4. exd4 Nc6 5. Nf3 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {followed by [Be3], [d4], [Qd2] and [O-O-O] to obtain a strong center and smooth development.}) ({Another rare move is} 3... c5 {, similar to the Tarrasch Defense. It would likely transpose, unless after} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 {Black plays} d4 $6 6. exd4 cxd4 7. Bb5+ Nc6 8. Ne4 {followed by [O-O] and [Re1], with initiative for White.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Ge3d4] White develops and controls the [d4]-square, now making ...[d4] impossible. In this position, the standard QGD move is 4...Be7 , but Black can develop in other ways as well.} Be7 ({The move} 4... c6 {would transpose to the chapter on the Slav Defense.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] The standard development for White in this variation.} O-O 6. Bb2 c5 {[%cal Rd5d4] The main move for Black, threatening ...[d4].} 7. cxd5 {White avoids the threat of ...[d4] by taking on [d5]. Now White keeps taking on [d5] until a pawn lands on [d5], when he follows up with [d4], aiming for positions with an IQP.} Nxd5 8. Nxd5 {White continues with the captures on [d5].} ({A more aggressive option is the move} 8. Qc2 $5 {, see the details in the model game Karjakin-Anand.}) 8... exd5 9. d4 {[%csl Bd5] White fixes the pawn on [d5] in standard fashion.} Nc6 ({The endgame after} 9... Qa5+ 10. Qd2 Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 {is better for White – without queens, there is less dynamism to compensate for the IQP on [d5].}) 10. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Rc5d4] White prepares castling.} cxd4 {Black starts active operations in the center.} ({In case of} 10... b6 {, we have a transposition to the line after 6...b6 7.cxd5 Nxd5 8.Nxd5 exd5 9.Be2 c5 10.d4 Nc6 .}) 11. Nxd4 Qa5+ {[%csl Bd4,Re1][%cal Ra5e1] This is Black's idea. White cannot cover the check and loses the right to castle. On the other hand, White has absolute control over the [d4]-square.} ({The check with the bishop is somewhat inferior, after} 11... Bb4+ 12. Kf1 {, the bishop is useless on [b4] and will have to spend a tempo to come back to [d6] or [e7]. White's plan then is to continue with [h4] and [g3], followed by [Kg2].}) 12. Kf1 Nxd4 ({Black can also play} 12... Ba3 13. Bxa3 Qxa3 {but after} 14. h4 {with ideas like [h5]-[h6] or simply [g3] and [Kg2], White keeps the game going thanks to the strong blockade on [d4].}) 13. Bxd4 {[%csl Bd4] Another piece arrived on [d4], but the control is still absolute.} Bf5 {Black has active piece play and good development. White uses the control of the dark squares and the blockade of the IQP to solve the problem of the uncastled king.} 14. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3f5] More exchanges favor White, fewer pieces mean less dynamism for Black.} Be4 15. f3 {[%cal Gf3e4,Gf1f2] Black's last move forced White to play this slightly weakening move, to free the [f2]-square for the king.} Bxd3+ {[%csl Rf1][%cal Rd3f1]} 16. Qxd3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gf1f2,Gh1c1,Gh1d1,Gd1d2] 💡With [Kf2] and the rooks connected Rhc1 or [Rhd1]-[d2] are possible continuations, White successfully solves the problem of the king. Objectively the game is equal, but it's again Black who needs to seek counterchances to compensate for the IQP.} *

