1. c4 c6 ({As against the QGD move order with} 1... e6 {, White has two options against the Slav systems, if he doesn't want to transpose to the Slav with} 2. d4 {:🔹to play the Réti with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop with [g3]; or, 🔹to choose the set-ups with [e3]. To stay consistent with the chosen lines in the repertoire, here, I also went for the set-ups with [e3].}) 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] The move order remains the same as against the QGD systems. With the knight on [c3], White threatens [e4].} ({There is also an issue with the move orders after the more usual} 2. Nf3 {, because apart from} d5 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 {, which would transpose to the lines analyzed in our repertoire, Black has two additional options:}) {2...g6 , with a possible transposition to KID structures when White cannot play the Botvinnik Setup since the knight is already on [f3], or simply playing ...[Bg7] and ...[d5] when White cannot play [b3]; and, ( 2...Nf6 3.Nc3 d6 , with the same idea of possibly transposing to KID positions with the white knight already on [f3]. ) ( In the latter case, White could play with d3 and e3, as suggested in the chapter The Reversed Sicilian 1…e5, via the move order 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 d6 3.Nf3 g6 4.d3 though here Black could develop the bishop on [e7] rather than on [g7], but why allow these two extra options for Black if it's possible to avoid them? )} 2... d5 ({In case of} 2... g6 3. e4 $1 {: the white knight is still on [g1], so White can play the Botvinnik Setup.}) 3. e3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Rd5d4] Stopping ...[d4].} Nf6 ({The only additional option Black gets because of the absence of the knight on f3 is} 3... e5 {, but after} 4. d4 {, White will soon obtain a position with an IQP on [d5].}) ({Here} 3... d4 $6 {is even worse than in the QGD as Black doesn't have access to the [c6]-square for the knight.}) 4. Nf3 {We reached the starting position of the variations with [e3] against the Slav.} *

