1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} Bg4 {[%cal Re7e6,Rg4d1] This move works nicely with a white pawn on [d4] without a knight on [c3]. In this case, White can pose more concrete problems thanks to the lead in development.} 5. cxd5 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gd1b3,Gb3b7,Gb3d5] White releases the tension, opens the [f1]-[a6] diagonal for the bishop the move [Bb5] is an important idea for White and intends to play [Qb3], immediately taking advantage of the weakness of the pawn on [b7].} ({If White plays} 5. Qb3 {, then after} Qb6 {Black will recapture with a knight on [d5] when White takes at a later stage.}) 5... Bxf3 $1 {Black must take on [f3] in this particular moment to prevent White's idea of [Qb3].} ({In case of} 5... cxd5 $6 6. Qb3 $1 Bc8 7. Ne5 {, we have the same position and a transposition to the position after 4...Bf5?! 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 Bc8 , where White has a stable advantage.}) ({Taking with the knight is inferior as} 5... Nxd5 $6 6. d4 {allows White to take over the center after a subsequent preparation of [e4].}) 6. Qxf3 cxd5 7. Bb5+ {[%csl Re8] A positional approach.} ({The aggressive} 7. g4 $5 Nc6 8. d4 {with [Bd3], [g5] and [h4] to come is also possible.}) 7... Nc6 8. Bxc6+ {[%csl Re8] White immediately saddles Black with a backward pawn on the c-file.} bxc6 9. b3 {[%csl Bc5,Yc6][%cal Gc1b2,Ga1c1,Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gc1c5] White's play is simple. After [Bb2] freeing the [c1]-square for a rook White will aim to place a rook on the c-file and continue with [Na4], targeting the backward pawn on [c6] and the weak square in front of it.} e5 ({This is more active than} 9... e6 {, which wouldn't alter White's plan to go for} 10. Bb2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 {followed by [Rac1] and a possible doubling of the rooks on the c-file.}) 10. Bb2 {White continues with the plan.} Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rac1 {[%csl Bc5,Yc6][%cal Gc3a4,Gc1c6,Ga4c5] Simple chess, again. It's worth noting that Black's pawn center is largely inoffensive because the exchange of a pair of light pieces has decreased the dynamic potential in the position, thus not allowing Black to create threats on the kingside after, for example, a possible ...[e4].} Rc8 {[%cal Gc8c6] Defending the pawn on [c6] in advance.} ({After} 12... e4 13. Qf5 {, White can continue with [Ne2], threatening [Bxf6] or simply [Nd4], using the opening of the long diagonal.}) 13. Rc2 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c8,Gc3a4] White prepares a doubling of the rooks on the c-file. This also prepares the move [Na4].} ({If that knight move is played immediately, it can be met by the semi-forcing} 13. Na4 Nd7 14. Rc2 Nb6 $1 15. Nc5 Qe7 16. Rfc1 Bxc5 17. Rxc5 Nc4 $1 {and Black wins the exchange.}) 13... Nd7 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gb6a4,Gf7f5] Black intends to meet White's [Na4] with ...[Nb6], as seen in the clickable in the previous comment. The move also frees the f-pawn to move forward.} 14. Qe2 {[%cal Ge2a6,Gf1c1,Ge3e4] The queen retreats to [e2] with several ideas: the doubling of the rooks is still possible, as are the moves [Qa6] and the push [e4]. The last point is an important one for White, as from a positional aspect it is in White's favor to fix Black's central pawns on dark squares, thus rendering Black's dark-squared bishop passive, and hoping to provoke ...[d4], which would give White control of the light squares, [c4] in particular.} e4 {Black stops White's idea of [e4], but after} 15. Na4 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c6] White continues with the plan to double on the c-file. The idea is to meet the obvious} Qh4 16. g3 {[%cal Gg3h4]} Qh3 17. f3 {[%cal Gf3e4,Ge2g2] Undermining Black's center.} f5 $6 {This desire to support the e4-pawn is not a good idea.} 18. f4 $1 {[%csl Bc5,Yc6,Yh3,Ya7][%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c6,Be2a6,Ba6c6,Ba6a7,Gb2d4,Ga4c5,Gd4c5] Successfully closes the kingside and places the queen on [h3] offside. 💡This being done, we see that: 🔹now White is free to continue with [Rfc1] and build up play against the backward [c6]-pawn. Other ideas are: 🔹Bd4 to maximize the control of the [c5]-square; and, 🔹Qa6, attacking the [c6]-pawn one more time, but also the pawn on [a7].} *

