1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} Nbd7 {[%cal Re7e5] Black wants to take advantage of the absence of a white pawn on [d4] and prepares ...[e5].} 5. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c8,Gc4d5] White prepares for the opening of the c-file after [cxd5]. This move is typical of White's set-up against almost all Slav systems.} ({The move} 5. d4 {would lead to the Semi-Slav.}) 5... e5 {[%csl Bd5,Be5] Black takes the center.} ({In case of} 5... e6 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Be2 {, we will have a transposition to the lines after 4...e6 5.b3 Bd6 6.Bb2 O-O 7.Be2 Nbd7 8.Qc2}) 6. cxd5 {With this capture White ensures that Black doesn't keep the pawn center.} Nxd5 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Rd5b4,Rb4c2]} ({Black cannot take with the pawn as} 6... cxd5 $2 7. Nb5 {wins at least a pawn for White after} Nc5 8. Nxe5 {.}) 7. a3 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ga3b4,Rd5b4,Rb4c2] Taking control of the [b4]-square, thus preventing possible ...[Nb4], which would harass the white queen.} ({An alternative is the move} 7. Bc4 {, which aims to dislodge the centralized knight from [d5], while after} N7b6 8. Be2 {, White would claim that the knight on [b6] is misplaced.}) 7... Bd6 {Black continues to develop.} 8. Be2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1,Ge3e4,Gd3d4,Gb2b4] The simplest development for White. It is the same as in the Sicilian Defense, [Be2], [d3], [O-O] and then either play in the center by pushing [d4] or [e4] or play on the queenside with [b4]. Alternatives are:} (8. Ne4 Bc7 9. Ng3 O-O 10. Bc4 {followed by [d3] and [O-O]; and,}) (8. d4 O-O 9. Bd3 {, which resembles Semi-Slav set-ups by both sides.}) 8... O-O 9. O-O f5 {[%cal Re5e4] The most natural move, taking some central space as in the Sicilian Defense with colors reversed.} ({In case of} 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 {, White should remember to push [d4] only after Black had played ...[f5], for example} Qe7 11. d3 $1 f5 12. d4 $1 e4 13. Nd2 {with [Nc4] and [a4] to come with good play on the queenside. The reason for provoking ...[f5] is that the pawn on [f5] limits the mobility of the bishop on [c8], thus making it more passive and not able to participate in any kingside play.}) 10. d3 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gd3e4,Gc3e4] White controls the [e4]-square and stops ...[e4].} N7f6 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gf6e4]} 11. Nxd5 $5 {A surprising exchange, but one with a concrete idea.} ({Good alternatives are} 11. b4 {and the very interesting 11.e4 Nxc3 12.Qxc3 Qe7 13.Re1 with good play for White.}) 11... cxd5 {[%csl Bd5,Be5,Bf5]} ({In case of} 11... Nxd5 12. Rd1 {, White threatens [e4] and [d4], to open the center. Black should prevent that by removing the knight with} Nf6 {, but then after} 13. b4 Kh8 14. e4 {with [Be3] next, White obtains a very pleasant Sicilian position with play on the queenside. Going back to the position on the board, it seems that the exchange only helped Black obtain a big center, but after}) 12. Bd2 {[%csl Bd4,Ge3,Be5][%cal Gd2b4,Gd3d4,Gf3e5] With the idea to exchange the dark-squared bishops after [Bb4], we begin to see White's idea – without the dark-squared bishops White wants to play [d4] and force all Black's pawns on light squares after ...[e4], after which the knight will nicely land on [e5], giving White an excellent reverse French structure with the better bishop and play on the c-file.} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Black should stop White's plan.} 13. Bc3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gc3e5,Gf3e5] White won't be able to exchange the dark-squared bishop, but he will be able to land a knight on [e5]. Now the pawn on [e5] is hanging.} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7e5]} 14. d4 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] Forcing Black's next.} e4 15. Ne5 {[%csl Ya5,Be5][%cal Gc2d2,Gd2a5,Gf1b1,Gb2b4] White established a dominating knight. 💡We will continue with: 🔹Qd2 attacking the pawn on [a5]; and, 🔹then with [Rfb1] and [b4], starting play on the queenside.} *

