1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5,Ge2e4,Ge4d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} Bf5 $6 {Of all the options, this is the worst one.} 5. cxd5 $1 {White takes on [d5] to be able to continue the attack with [Qb3] next. The point is that after [Qb3] the pawn on [d5] will hang, so Black won't be able to oppose White's attack with ...[Qb6].} cxd5 6. Qb3 {[%csl Yd5,Yb7][%cal Gb3b7,Gb3d5,Gc3d5] Hitting the weakened pawn on [b7].} Bc8 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black must go back with the bishop.} ({The move} 6... Qb6 $2 {loses a pawn to} 7. Nxd5 {.}) 7. Ne5 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf2f4,Gd2d4,Gf1d3] Centralizing the knight, which White plans to support by both d- and f-pawns.} e6 8. d4 {Expanding in the center.} Nc6 9. f4 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gd4e5,Gf4e5,Ge1g1,Gf1d3,Gc1d2] White has a pleasant advantage. 💡We can continue to play: 🔹on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4], etc. 🔹or on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.} *

