1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] The Schlechter Variation combines the Slav and the Grunfeld. It is not the happiest mix as the bishop on [g7] is passive doing nothing against White's fortified [d4]-pawn – it would rather prefer the c-pawn to be on [c5] like in the Grünfeld, undermining White's center than on [c6].} 5. cxd5 ({With this early exchange, White tries to avoid a direct transposition to the Schlechter Variation of the Slav by} 5. d4 {.}) 5... cxd5 6. Bb5+ {[%csl Re8][%cal Gb5e8,Gd1b3] White delays the [d4]-advance, as the pawn may also go to [d3] later on. Instead, White develops with tempo.} Bd7 {Since Black will likely play ...[e6], it makes sense for Black to exchange the potentially bad bishop.} ({After} 6... Nc6 7. Ne5 Bd7 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. b3 {, White managed to inflict structural weaknesses in Black's position, the backward pawn on [c6], just like in the 4...Bg4-line.}) 7. Qb3 {[%csl Yd5,Yb7][%cal Gb3d5,Gc3d5,Gb3b7] Continuing the development with tempo. The queen attacks the pawn on [d5] and also eyes the one on [b7].} e6 {Making sure the [d5]-pawn is safely defended.} ({In case of} 7... Bxb5 8. Qxb5+ Qd7 9. Ne5 Qxb5 10. Nxb5 Na6 11. b3 {, Black cannot get rid of the annoying knight on [b5] and is stuck with a knight on [a6] for the foreseeable future.}) 8. O-O {[%csl Bd2][%cal Gd2d3,Gd2d4] White still keeps the flexibility with the d-pawn.} Bg7 ({One of the benefits of having the pawn still on d2 is seen in the case of} 8... Bd6 9. d3 $1 {when White wants to push [e4] and exploit the position of the bishop on [d6] and knight on [f6] by threatening the fork [e5].}) ({Similarly,} 8... Nc6 9. d3 $1 a6 10. Bxc6 Bxc6 11. Ne5 {followed by [Nxc6] will weaken Black's queenside structure.}) ({A decent alternative is} 8... Qb6 9. a4 a6 10. a5 Qc7 11. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 12. d3 $1 {with [Bd2] and [Rfc1] to come when White has a slight initiative on the queenside where he can continue with [Qc2], [b4], [Na4] etc.}) 9. d4 {White cannot extract more gains by delaying the advance of the d-pawn.} O-O ({Black cannot take on b5 as} 9... Bxb5 $6 10. Qxb5+ Qd7 11. Ne5 {gives White a strong initiative.}) 10. Bd3 {[%csl Yb7,Bd3][%cal Gb3b7] White preserves the more active bishop.} Nc6 11. Bd2 {[%csl Bc5,Be5,Yg7,Yd7][%cal Gf1c1,Bc3a4,Ba4c5,Gc1c5,Gf3e5,Ga2a4,Gb3a3,Gb2b4,Ga4a5] White connects the rooks. The pawn on b7 is taboo in view of ❌11.Qxb7?? Rb8 12.Qa6 Nb4 , and White loses the bishop on [d3]. 💡White's ideas are: 🔹on the queenside, [Rfc1], [Na4]-[c5] or [a4]-[a5], [Qa3] and [b4], advancing with the pawns. These ideas can be combined. 🔹in the center, White will look for an opportune moment to play [Ne5]. Black has a solid position, but both the bishops are passive, thus severely limiting any active possibilities.} *

