1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} a6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ga8a7,Ga7b7,Gb7b5] Black plays in Chebanenko style. The move with the a-pawn prepares the move [Bf5] or [Bg4] since after an attack with [Qb3] that can be quite annoying as we saw in the Bg4-line Black can defend the [b7]-pawn with [Ra7] or [b5].} 5. Be2 {A developing and a waiting move. As is typical for White's play in the lines of this chapter, White delays the advance of the d-pawn.} Bg4 {This is a natural developing move, but White can once again take advantage of the d-pawn being on its starting position.} 6. Qb3 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gb3b7] First the queen is activated by attacking the pawn on [b7].} Ra7 {[%cal Ga7b7] In case of 5...b5 6.cxd5 cxd5 7.a4 , Black cannot defend the queenside.} 7. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] This forces Black to give up the bishop pair.} Bxf3 ({Keeping the bishop with} 7... Bh5 $6 {gives White an advantage after} 8. cxd5 {:} ({𓈓8...} 8. cxd5 {Qa4} Nbd7 {Qd4! hitting both the rook on [a7] and the pawn on [d5] Nb6} 9. g4 Bg6 10. Ne5 {with a complete bind. Or:}) ({𓈓8...} 8. Nxd5 {e4 Nxc3 dxc3 , with [Be3] next})) 8. Bxf3 e6 9. d3 ({The move} 9. d4 {is obviously possible, but it would lead to more Slav-like positions. By playing [d3], White keeps more flexibility with his central options.}) 9... Nbd7 10. Bd2 {White completes development and all that remains is to castle.} Bd6 11. O-O O-O 12. cxd5 ({It's possible to transpose to Slav-like positions with} 12. d4 {but this exchange gives the position a more original character. After}) 12... cxd5 ({The other recapture is met by} 12... exd5 13. e4 {, when the [d3] move comes in handy to support the central advance.}) 13. Rfc1 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf3g2,Ge2d4,Gd2c3,Gc3e2] 💡White has many moves to improve the position: 🔹g3 and [Bg2] remove the bishop from attacks with [Ne5] or [Be2]-[f1] in case of an immediate [Ne5]; 🔹Nce2-[d4] and [Bc3] to use the dark squares in the center. 🔹At some point, White will have to choose between [d4]- or [e4]-advance in the center and this will depend on the concrete circumstances.} *

