1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} a6 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Ga8a7,Ga7b7,Rb7b5] Black plays in Chebanenko style. The move with the a-pawn prepares the move [Bf5] or [Bg4] since after an attack with [Qb3] that can be quite annoying as we saw in the [Bg4]-line Black can defend the [b7]-pawn with [Ra7] or [b5].} 5. Be2 {A developing and a waiting move. As is typical for White's play in the lines of this chapter, White delays the advance of the d-pawn.} Bf5 {[%cal Ge7e6] Another typical Slav move, Black wants to follow up with ...[e6]. White reacts in the same way as in the line with 5...Bg4.} 6. Qb3 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gb3b7] First the queen attacks the pawn on [b7].} Ra7 {[%cal Ga7b7]} 7. d3 {[%csl Gd3][%cal Ge3e4] Again using the flexibility of the d-pawn. The [d3]-pawn restricts the bishop on [f5] and White intends to expand on the light squares in the center with [e4].} e6 8. cxd5 ({The immediate} 8. e4 {, which is also quite promising, leads to big complications after} dxe4 9. dxe4 Nxe4 10. Nxe4 Bxe4 11. Ng5 {, while the text is simpler.}) 8... cxd5 ({The other recapture is worse,} 8... exd5 $6 9. e4 $1 dxe4 10. dxe4 Nxe4 11. Nxe4 Bxe4 12. Qe3 {with a double attack on the rook on [a7] and the bishop on [e4].}) 9. O-O {[%cal Ge3e4] Castling and preparing the [e4] advance.} ({A good alternative is} 9. Qa4+ Qd7 10. Qxd7+ Nbxd7 11. Nh4 {when White will play an endgame with the pair of bishops.}) 9... Bg4 {[%cal Rg4f3] Getting away from the possible attack with [e4].} 10. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] Forcing the exchange of bishop for knight.} Bxf3 ({The bishop cannot escape,} 10... Bh5 $2 11. g4 $1 Bg6 12. e4 $1 {is tremendous for White, the point being that after} dxe4 13. dxe4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Be3 Ra8 16. Rfd1 {, White's lead in development is decisive.}) 11. Bxf3 Nc6 12. Bd2 {White finishes development} Bd6 13. Rfc1 {[%csl Bc5][%cal Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Gg2g3,Gf3g2,Gd3d4,Ge3e4,Gc1c5] The position we have reached is very similar to the position in the above-mentioned 5...[Bg4]-line, with exactly the same ideas. 💡White can play: 🔹Na4-c5, a possibility because, in this line, the knight is on [c6] and not on [d7], thus not controlling the [c5]-square; 🔹g3 and Bg2; and, 🔹at a later stage, can decide whether to push e4 or d4.} *

