 be met by} 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. b4 $1 e6 8. Qb3 {followed by [O-O] when White can take advantage of the weakened [c5]-square after [d4], [Ne1]-[d3]-[c5], and can also attack Black's queenside by [a4].}) ({The Schlechter plan with} 5... g6 {can be met with the same [b4]-idea after} 6. O-O Bg7 7. b4 {, when White wants to advance on the queenside with [a4], [Bb2], likely playing [d4] at a later stage.}) 6. a4 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Rb7b5,Rb5c4] Preventing ...[b5], which would allow Black safely to defend the pawn on [c4].} Be6 {[%cal Ge6c4] Black doesn't want to give up the [c4]-pawn easily, as doing so allows White smooth development.} ({For example} 6... Nbd7 7. Bxc4 e6 8. e4 c5 9. d3 {with [O-O], [a5] and [Qe2] intending [e5] being constructive moves for White.}) ({In case of} 6... Bg4 {, the simple} 7. Bxc4 {the pawn sacrifice b3!? is also very promising} e6 8. Qb3 Bxf3 9. gxf3 Qc7 10. d4 Be7 11. f4 {with [O-O], [Bd2], [a5] to follow gives White options to play on both wings: 🔹on the kingside with [Ne2], [Bc3] and [f5], with use of the g-file after [Kh1] and [Rg1]; and, 🔹on the queenside with [Qc2] and [b4].}) 7. O-O {White tucks away the king before commencing operations in the center.} Nbd7 8. Ng5 {[%csl Ye6,Yc4][%cal Gg5e6,Ge2c4] The most direct way to go after the pawn.} ({It's also possible to play for long-term compensation with moves like} 8. b3 {or 8.a5 , both of which are worth exploring.}) 8... Bd5 9. e4 {[%cal Ge4d5] The bishop has nowhere to run, but Black has} h6 {[%cal Rh6g5]} 10. exd5 {White now obtains the bishop pair. The position becomes unbalanced after the forcing moves} hxg5 11. dxc6 {[%cal Gc6d7]} bxc6 ({The move} 11... Ne5 {is also possible, leading to even sharper positions after} 12. cxb7 Rb8 13. d4 $1 cxd3 14. Bxg5 $1 {a very promising piece sacrifice by White whose idea is to finish development as soon as possible and obtain dangerous passed pawns on the queenside after} dxe2 15. Qxe2 {followed by [Qxa6].}) 12. d4 {[%csl Yc4,Yg5][%cal Gc1g5,Ge2c4] White must open the game for the bishops.} ({Taking on c4} 12. Bxc4 {allows} Qc7 13. h3 g4 {with unpleasant play against White's king.}) 12... cxd3 13. Qxd3 {[%cal Gc1g5] White wants to regain the pawn by taking on [g5]} g4 {Black tries to keep the extra pawn. Otherwise, White will regain the pawn and will have the bishops in an open position.} 14. Ne4 {[%csl Be4] Centralizing the knight. Black cannot exchange it because after [Qxe4] there would be a double attack on the pawns on [c6] and [g4].} e6 15. Qc2 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gc2c6]} Qc7 {[%csl Yh2][%cal Rc7h2,Gh8h2]} 16. g3 {[%csl Ya6,Bc1,Yc6,Bd6,Be2][%cal Gc1f4,Gf4c7,Ge4d6] Preventing mate and allowing for [Bf4]. White has good compensation because of the pair of bishops and the pawn weaknesses on the queenside that Black needs to cover. 💡What White should do? 🔹Keep in mind that both pawns on [a6] and [c6] are weak and isolated and need constant protection by the opponent's pieces. At some point, we'll have to take advantage of it. 🔹Continue with Bf4 and the possibility of [Nd6] to exchange Black's remaining bishop. It is an attractive plan, as it will give White absolute control of the dark squares and possibly keep the black king in the center.} *

