1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} e6 {The Semi-Slav option.} ({Of all the options mentioned, the move} 4... Bf5 $6 {is the worst because after} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {puts Black under immediate pressure, the pawns on [b7] and [d5] being under attack. Black's best is} Bc8 {, but after} 7. Ne5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. f4 {, White has a pleasant advantage as he can continue to play: 🔹on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4], etc; or, 🔹on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.}) ({Another sub-optimal move is} 4... dxc4 $6 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O {with [e4] and [d4] to come, when White obtains excellent play in the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... e5 {[%csl Bd5,Be5] The central advance is an important alternative.} 8. cxd5 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Gc3b5,Rc6d5] The exchange on [d5] frees the [b5]-square for the knight.} cxd5 9. Nb5 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gb5d6,Gb2e5,Gf3e5] The attack on the pawn on [e5] means that White will obtain the bishop pair by taking on [d6].} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5,Gd6e5] Black develops and defends the pawn on [e5].} ({An attempt to save the bishop with} 9... e4 {is possible. After} 10. Nfd4 Be7 {10...Be5 11.Ne6! still wins the bishop pair 11.Rc1 a6 12.Nc3 followed by [O-O], [Na4], [d3] White is harmoniously developed and will play on the queenside in combination with the undermining of the black center with [d3].}) 10. Nxd6 {Otherwise the bishop would run away to [b8].} Qxd6 11. d4 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] White must counter Black's pawn center.} e4 ({The endgame after} 11... Qb4+ 12. Qd2 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Ne4+ 14. Ke1 f6 15. Rc1 {is complex, but White still has the pair of bishops and pressure on the [e5]-pawn.}) 12. Ne5 {[%csl Be5,Be2,Bb2][%cal Ga2a4,Gb2a3,Ga3f8,Ge5c6,Ge1g1,Gd1d2] White has quite an acceptable reverse French with a strong knight on [e5] and the pair of bishops. 💡The subsequent play will likely see White: 🔹exchange the knight on [e5] for the black's knight on [c6], when White's primary aim will be to activate the dark-squared bishop by [a4] and [Ba3] ; 🔹proceed with play on the queenside by advancing the queenside pawns and using the c-file.} *

