1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} e6 {The Semi-Slav option.} ({Of all the options mentioned, the move} 4... Bf5 $6 {is the worst because after} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {puts Black under immediate pressure, the pawns on [b7] and [d5] being under attack. Black's best is} Bc8 {, but after} 7. Ne5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. f4 {, White has a pleasant advantage as he can continue to play: 🔹on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4], etc; or, 🔹on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.}) ({Another sub-optimal move is} 4... dxc4 $6 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O {with [e4] and [d4] to come, when White obtains excellent play in the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {As Black's knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: 🔹one is to push ...[e5]; and, 🔹the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Re6e5] We saw why Black cannot play ...[e5] and take on [d5] with the pawn – it is because of the weakness of the [b5]-square and White's option of [Nb5]. So with the move ...[a6] Black controls the [b5]-square and plans ...[e5]. Note that this position can also arise via the Chebanenko move order with 4...a6.} 9. d4 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] The only way for White to stop Black's idea of ...[e5].} e5 {Black continues with his plan.} ({The Chebanenko move} 9... b5 $6 {is not good as after} 10. O-O Qe7 11. e4 {, White expands in the center and as a rule of thumb in Semi-Slav positions, if White manages this then he is assured of at least a small advantage.} ({The move Qe7 O-O Re8} 11. Rad1 {transposes to the main line and is examined after 8...Re8 9.O-O Qe7 10.Rad1 a6 11.d4 , here.})) 10. dxe5 {White goes for a typical position with a black IQP on [d5].} Nxe5 11. cxd5 {[%csl Bd5] Now Black is forced to play with a pawn on [d5].} cxd5 12. O-O {[%csl Bd5] White achieved a standard position with an IQP where he enjoys smooth development. After} Be6 13. Rac1 {[%csl Bb2,Be2,Bg4][%cal Gc2b1,Gf3d4,Gd4e6,Gf1d1,Gh2h3,Gh3g4,Gc2d2,Ra8c8] Positioning itself in the fight for control of the open c-file. Typically, Black plays 13...Rc8 in this position. 💡White will continue with: 🔹h3 to prevent ...[Ng4] ideas and [Nd4]; and, 🔹will exchange on [e6]. This will give White the advantage of the pair of bishops, a transformation of the advantage, from an IQP to pair of bishops, since with all Black's pieces well centralized, it's difficult to obtain something tangible with direct play against the IQP.} *

