1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} e6 {The Semi-Slav option.} ({Of all the options mentioned, the move} 4... Bf5 $6 {is the worst because after} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {puts Black under immediate pressure, the pawns on [b7] and [d5] being under attack. Black's best is} Bc8 {, but after} 7. Ne5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. f4 {, White has a pleasant advantage as he can continue to play: 🔹on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4], etc; or, 🔹on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.}) ({Another sub-optimal move is} 4... dxc4 $6 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O {with [e4] and [d4] to come, when White obtains excellent play in the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {As Black's knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: 🔹one is to push ...[e5]; and, 🔹the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} Qe7 {A common developing move for Black in the Semi-Slav.} 9. O-O e5 {This will lead to positions similar to the one arising from 4...Nbd7 5.Qc2 e5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.a3 Bd6 8.Be2 .} ({The move} 9... b6 $6 {is dubious as} 10. cxd5 $1 {poses unpleasant problems: in case of} exd5 11. Nd4 {threatens the pawn on [c6] and [Nf5] which will win the bishop pair for White, while 10...cxd5 11.Nb5 Ba6 12.Nfd4 is a good illustration of how White can take advantage of the absence of a pawn on [d4]. Black will again be forced to give up the light-squared bishop in order to avoid the worst.}) 10. cxd5 {The usual reaction for White.} Nxd5 ({Taking with the pawn without controlling the b5-square is bad,} 10... cxd5 $6 11. Nb5 {is very problematic for Black.}) 11. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6] White would like to obtain the bishop pair by exchanging on [d6].} Bc7 12. Ng3 {[%cal Gg3f5] The knight wasn't stable on [e4], so White places it on [g3], from where it can come to [f5].} Re8 {[%cal Ge7f8] Black frees the [f8]-square for the queen in case of [Nf5].} ({After} 12... N7f6 13. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 14. d4 e4 15. Ne5 {, White can achieve one of the main ideas in this line: to establish a knight on [e5]. Then he can continue with [Rad1], [Qc1] and [f3], or if possible, to take the pawn on [e4] with [Nxe4], followed by [Qxe4] and [Bd3], creating threats on the [b1]-[h7] diagonal this can work in case Black had played [h6] before.}) ({Alternatively, White can always play with d3 like after} 12... Re8 {.}) 13. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4] In Sicilian fashion, since the pawn structure is like a reversed Sicilian, White wants to expand on the queenside with [b4].} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Black stops [b4].} 14. d3 {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge2f1,Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Gd3d4] White establishes the small center of pawns on [d3] and [e3]. These pawns allow the white pieces to maneuver behind them. 💡Ideas for White are: 🔹Rfe1 and [Bf1]; 🔹Nd2-[c4]; or, 🔹at some point, to push [d4], for example with a knight on [d2], so that Black cannot push ...[e4]. In that case, the [d4] and [e5] pawns will be exchanged, giving White a pawn majority in the center, which together with the concentration of pieces on the kingside will give White good chances in the center and the kingside.} *

