n the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {As Black's knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: 🔹one is to push ...[e5]; and, 🔹the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Developing the bishop on [b7] is an alternative to the plans with ...[e5].} 9. Rg1 $1 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gg5f6] This surprising move works and White can start pushing the g-pawn to dislodge the knight from [f6].} Bb7 ({Black can start with} 9... e5 10. g4 Bb7 {and we will have a transposition.}) 10. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5,Gh2h4,Ge1c1] White's play is very simple: advance with the kingside pawns and start an attack on the kingside. When and if necessary, the king can go to the queenside by castling long.} e5 {[%cal Gb2h8] Black closes the long diagonal for the white dark-squared bishop.} ({To show the problems that can happen to Black on the long diagonal, here's a sample line after} 10... c5 $6 11. g5 Ne4 12. cxd5 exd5 13. Nxe4 dxe4 14. Qc3 {and Black is already lost:} f6 15. gxf6 Rxf6 16. Bc4+ Kh8 17. Qxf6 $1 Nxf6 18. Ng5 {and White's initiative will continue after collecting more material after [Nf7xd6].}) 11. g5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Gg5f6] White continues with the plan.} Ne8 12. O-O-O {[%cal Gh2h4,Gd2d4] White castles so that now has an option to continue with the kingside attack with [h4]-[h5], but also to play in the center with [d4].} b5 {[%cal Rb5c4,Rd5c4] Black must try to organize counterplay as soon as possible.} ({Waiting with} 12... Nc7 13. h4 Ne6 14. h5 {with further ideas like [Nh4]-[f5] makes White's attack irresistible.}) 13. d4 {White strikes in the center. This forces Black to push [e4] as otherwise the long diagonal will be opened for the bishop on [b2] when the option for a positional piece sacrifice on [e4] appears.} e4 14. Nd2 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gd2e4,Gc3e4] At an appropriate moment the sacrifice on [e4] can be decisive.} bxc4 {Black must strive for counterplay.} ({To show the strength of the piece sacrifice, after} 14... b4 $2 15. Ncxe4 $1 dxe4 16. c5 {shutting the bishop on [b7]} Be7 17. Nxe4 {with [h4], [Ng3] and a mass advance of all White's central pawns will sweep everything in their path.}) 15. bxc4 Ba6 {[%cal Ra6e2]} 16. h4 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gh4h5,Gh5h6,Gg5g6,Gc4c5,Gc3e4,Gd2e4,Gf2f3,Gf3e4,Gc1b1,Gb1a1] White's pawns get closer to Black's king. 💡But White's play is not limited to the kingside: 🔹apart from the positional sacrifice on [e4], 🔹White can also play [c5] and [f3], to undermine Black's [e4]-pawn and remove it from the space-gaining central square by exchanging it. This, in turn, will give White's pieces more room for maneuver that can translate to an attack on Black's king. 🔹On the queenside, White can consider the consolidating move [Kb1]-[a1] to tuck away the king to safety in the corner. In this complex middlegame, White has all the chances to obtain an advantage with the aforementioned ideas.} *

