enter.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {Now that the black knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: one is to push ...[e5] and the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} Re8 {[%cal Re6e5] The most common move at the master level.} ({The immediate} 8... e5 9. cxd5 cxd5 $6 10. Nb5 Bb8 11. Rc1 {with [Nc7] is excellent for White. Taking on [d5] with the knight is better and would lead to similar positions to the ones analyzed in the variation 4...Nbd7 5.Qc2 e5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.a3 Bd6 8.Be2 where White has already fianchettoed the dark-squared bishop.}) 9. O-O {White castles since Black doesn't control the [b5]-square, so the advance ...[e5] can be met by [cxd5], forcing Black to recapture with a knight.} b6 {With the white king already on g1, Black doesn't fear an attack with g4 like in the line: 8...b6 9.Rg1! , so it's possible to switch to the plan with the fianchetto of the light-squared bishop.} 10. a4 $5 {[%cal Ga4a5,Gb2a3] A new move and a novel plan. White uses the a-pawn to cause problems by advancing it as far as possible in true Leela Chess Zero-style.} a5 {Stopping White's plan.} ({In case of} 10... Bb7 11. a5 bxa5 12. d4 {, White has good compensation for the pawn since both Black's pawns on the a-file are weak and subject to attacks.}) ({After} 10... c5 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nb5 Bb8 13. a5 {, White has initiative on the queenside and at some point will play [d4], to fix Black's [d5]-pawn.}) 11. Nd4 {[%csl Yc6,Be5][%cal Gd4c6,Gf2f4,Gf4e5] This is another original idea. White wins a tempo by attacking the pawn on [c6] so that he can advance with the f-pawn to stop Black's ...[e5] advance.} Bb7 12. f4 {[%csl Bb5,Be5][%cal Gf4e5,Gd4f5,Gf1f8,Ga1d1,Bd4f3,Bf3e5,Gd2d4,Gc4d5,Gc3b5] White's control of the [e5]-square discourages Black's ...[e5] advance, as that would open the f-file after [fxe5] and weaken the [f5]-square, which White can use after [Nf5]. 💡White's ideas are : 🔹Rad1, [Nf3]-[e5] followed by [d4], or in some cases even [g4]-[g5]; 🔹the capture [cxd5] would either gain access to the [b5]-square after ...[cxd5], or the [f5]-square after ...[exd5], so it should be timed accurately.} *

