1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} e6 {The Semi-Slav option.} ({Of all the options mentioned, the move} 4... Bf5 $6 {is the worst because after} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {puts Black under immediate pressure, the pawns on [b7] and [d5] being under attack. Black's best is} Bc8 {, but after} 7. Ne5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. f4 {, White has a pleasant advantage as he can continue to play: 🔹on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4], etc; or, 🔹on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.}) ({Another sub-optimal move is} 4... dxc4 $6 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O {with [e4] and [d4] to come, when White obtains excellent play in the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {As Black's knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: 🔹one is to push ...[e5]; and, 🔹the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} Re8 {[%cal Re6e5] The most common move.} ({The immediate} 8... e5 9. cxd5 ({𓈓9...} 9. cxd5 $6 {Nb5} Bb8 10. Rc1 {with [Nc7] is excellent for White.}) ({𓈓9...} 9. Nxd5 {is better for Black. With the notable difference that White has already fianchettoed the dark-squared bishop, taking on [d5] with the knight would lead to similar positions to the one analyzed in the variation : 4...Nbd7 5.Qc2 e5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.a3 Bd6 8.Be2 .})) 9. O-O {White castles since Black doesn't control the [b5]-square, so the advance ...[e5] can be met by [cxd5], forcing Black to recapture with a knight.} dxc4 {[%cal Re6e5] Black releases the tension in the center, thus avoiding [cxd5] and wants to advance with ...[e5]} 10. Bxc4 {[%cal Gc4g8] This recapture prevents Black from advancing with the planned ...[e5].} ({The other recapture} 10. bxc4 e5 11. d4 {leads to the theoretical lines of the Semi-Slav, which are similar to the positions we examine in the main line after:}) {9...Qe7 10.Rad1 a6 11.d4 dxc4 12.bxc4 e5 , but in the latter case Black has played the unnecessary move ...[a6] while White has played the useful centralizing [Rad1].} 10... b5 {[%cal Gc8b7]} ({Since} 10... e5 $6 {isn't good in view of} 11. Ng5 Rf8 12. Nce4 {with strong initiative, Black must find an alternative way to develop the light-squared bishop.}) ({If Black prepares the e5-push with} 10... h6 {, then after} 11. d4 e5 12. Rad1 {, White obtains initiative in the center thanks to the possibility to advance with the e-pawn, for example,} Qc7 13. h3 exd4 14. Nxd4 Bf8 15. e4 {with [Rfe1] to come and Black doesn't have many active possibilities.}) 11. Bd3 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gc2h7,Gf3g5,Gc3e4] White prepares [Ng5] and [Nce4].} h6 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Gh6g5]} 12. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6,Ge4f6] White used the threats on the kingside to establish central control and stop Black's liberating ...[c5] advance.} Nxe4 13. Bxe4 {[%csl Yc6,Ya8][%cal Ge4a8]} Bb7 14. a4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga4b5] Continuing the attack on the queenside. By forcing Black to play ...[b4] White obtains the [c4]-square for a piece, most likely a knight.} b4 15. d4 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Ga1c1,Gf1d1,Ge4a8] 💡White has easy play: 🔹the rooks will be centralized on [c1] and [d1]; and, 🔹the knight will be headed for [c4]. Black will find it problematic to achieve either ...[c5] or ...[e5] without issues.} *

