1. c4 c6 2. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge2e4,Ge4d5,Gc4d5,Gc3d5] Threatening [e4], when Black won't be able to counter with ...[d5].} d5 {[%cal Rd5d4] Black threatens...[d4] now, so White stops it with the next move.} 3. e3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge3d4]} Nf6 {The usual move.} ({Pushing} 3... d4 $6 {only helps White after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next.}) ({The only move that Black can try to take advantage of White's move order is} 3... e5 {, when after} 4. d4 {Black has two options:} ({𓈓4...} 4. e4 {Qa4! with [cxd5] will prevent Black from recapturing with the c-pawn, thus giving White central pawn advantage of [e3] and [d4] pawns vs. [e4]-pawn.}) ({𓈓4... exd4 Qxd4 Nf6} 4. Nf3 Be7 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Be2 Nc6 {Qd3 with [O-O], [Rd1], [b3] and [Bb2] to follow with a typical position where White plays against the IQP.})) 4. Nf3 {White develops the knight. Now, Black can choose from several Slav set-ups. These are: 🔹the Semi-Slav with 4...e6 ; 🔹the Chebanenko with 4...a6 ; 🔹the Schlechter with 4...g6 ; 🔹the Classical Slav attempts to develop the light-squared bishop outside the pawn chain before playing ...e6 like 4...Bg4 or 4...Bf5 ; and, ( 🔹the attempt to build a pawn center with 4...Nbd7 . ) ( With this outline in mind, it needs to be mentioned that White's move order is quite effective against Black's attempts at the Classical Slav 4...Bg4 and 4...Bf5?! . )} e6 {The Semi-Slav option.} ({Of all the options mentioned, the move} 4... Bf5 $6 {is the worst because after} 5. cxd5 cxd5 6. Qb3 $1 {puts Black under immediate pressure, the pawns on [b7] and [d5] being under attack. Black's best is} Bc8 {, but after} 7. Ne5 e6 8. d4 Nc6 9. f4 {, White has a pleasant advantage as he can continue to play: 🔹on the queenside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2], [Rfc1], [Na4], etc; or, 🔹on the kingside after [Bd3], [O-O], [Bd2]-[e1]-[h4], [Qd1]-[f3]-[h3] and so on.}) ({Another sub-optimal move is} 4... dxc4 $6 5. Bxc4 b5 6. Be2 Bb7 7. O-O {with [e4] and [d4] to come, when White obtains excellent play in the center.}) 5. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2] White develops the queenside along the usual lines.} Bd6 {The standard Semi-Slav development, which is aimed at pushing ...[e5]. Placing the bishop on [e7] makes less sense, as Black doesn't control the [e5]-square.} ({After} 5... Be7 {White continues with} 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Qc2 Nbd7 8. d4 {with simple development after [Bd3] and [O-O] when White will either try to push [e4] or plant a knight on [e5] and support it with [f4].}) 6. Bb2 O-O 7. Be2 $1 {It is important to play the correct move order and develop the bishop first.} ({In case of} 7. Qc2 $6 e5 $1 8. cxd5 cxd5 9. Nb5 Nc6 {the queen is exposed on [c2] to attacks by ...[Nb4] and this gives Black good play.}) 7... Nbd7 {This is the Semi-Slav development.} 8. Qc2 {As Black's knight can no longer come to [c6], White develops the queen on [c2]. Now Black has two plans in general: 🔹one is to push ...[e5]; and, 🔹the other is to develop the light-squared bishop to [b7]. Sometimes these two ideas are combined.} Re8 {[%cal Re6e5] The most common move.} ({The immediate} 8... e5 9. cxd5 ({𓈓9...} 9. cxd5 $6 {Nb5} Bb8 10. Rc1 {with [Nc7] is excellent for White.}) ({𓈓9...} 9. Nxd5 {is better for Black. With the notable difference that White has already fianchettoed the dark-squared bishop, taking on [d5] with the knight would lead to similar positions to the one analyzed in the variation : 4...Nbd7 5.Qc2 e5 6.cxd5 Nxd5 7.a3 Bd6 8.Be2 .})) 9. O-O {White castles since Black doesn't control the [b5]-square, so the advance ...[e5] can be met by [cxd5], forcing Black to recapture with a knight.} Qe7 ({The move} 9... e5 {leads to positions already analyzed after 8...Qe7 9.O-O e5 10.cxd5 Nxd5 11.Ne4 , here . Please check the model game Grischuk-Kramnik for details on how these positions are played out in practice.}) 10. Rad1 {White still waits with the d-pawn and Black runs out of useful moves. Now best for Black is} a6 {[%cal Ga6b5,Re6e5]} ({About the alternatives the motifs are already known:} 10... b6 $6 {runs into} 11. cxd5 {, to which Black can respond in two ways:} ({𓈓11...} 11. cxd5 {Nb5 that will net White the bishop pair.}) ({𓈓11... exd5} 11. Nd4 {with [Nf5] next, winning the bishop pair.})) {The move e5 leads to the already explored positions from the line 8...Qe7 9.O-O e5 10.cxd5 after 11.cxd5 Nxd5 12.Ne4 , also examined in the model game Grischuk-Kramnik.} 11. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5] The only way to stop ...[e5].} dxc4 {Black needs to release the tension if he is to push ...[e5].} 12. bxc4 {[%csl Bc4,Bd4] It's also possible to take with the bishop, but taking towards the center is more principled.} e5 13. c5 {[%csl Yf7,Bc4][%cal Ge2c4,Gc4f7,Gf3g5] Freeing the [c4]-square for the bishop.} Bc7 14. Bc4 {[%csl Yf7,Bg5][%cal Gc4f7,Gf3g5,Gg5f7] White threatens [Ng5].} h6 {[%cal Gh6g5] Black prevents [Ng5].} ({It's not good for Black to react in the center. For example} 14... exd4 15. exd4 {with [Rfe1] next here we see the depth of the move Rad1 – the rook on [f1] stayed put so that it can come to [e1] in this position. Or 14...e4?! 15.Ng5 Bxh2 16.Kh1! and too many things hang for Black: the pawns on f7 and e4 and the bishop on h2.}) 15. Nh4 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Gh4f5] With the [g5]-square unavailable, the knight targets the [f5]-square.} ({A good alternative is the simple} 15. g3 {, avoiding any tactics on the [h2]-[b8] diagonal and intending [Nh4]. After} exd4 16. exd4 Nf8 17. Rfe1 Qd8 18. Ne5 {, White has a pleasant position with active pieces and space advantage.}) 15... exd4 16. exd4 Nf8 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Gc8f5]} 17. Nf5 {White wins the bishop pair now.} Bxf5 18. Qxf5 {[%csl Bb2,Bc4][%cal Gg2g3,Gh2h4,Gf1e1,Ge1e5] With the pair of bishops and space advantage White has a good position. 💡Let's evaluate the options: 🔹playing [g3] and [h4] will further limit Black's pieces the bishop in particular, the pawn on [h4] can further gain space on the kingside with [h5]; 🔹if the queens are exchanged, for example after [Qd7], [Qxd7], White will place a rook on the e-file, with the idea to possibly double on it by putting a rook on [e5]. While Black is solid and can control the [d5]-square, the lack of active possibilities means that White can press without any risk.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
