[White "Introduction: The Flexible 1...Nf6"]
[Black "Introduction: The Flexible 1...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A18"]
[PlyCount "9"]
[GameId "2102815304478247"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White continues with [Nc3] as against the QGD and Slav move orders, threatening [e4].} ({The move} 2. g3 {would move order us out of the preferred Slav set-ups with 2...c6, and we can no longer play with [e3] and [b3] and also out of our Reversed Sicilian set-ups after 2...e5.}) ({The other move} 2. Nf3 {allows many options for Black:} g6 {, when we can no longer play the Botvinnik Setup; 2...e6 with ...[b6], something we avoided in the QGD move order by playing 2.Nc3; and 2...b6 which again gives Black flexibility by playing later with or without ...[d5] or ...[c5].}) 2... e6 ({This is the main move if Black doesn't transpose to the Reversed Sicilian with} 2... e5 {.}) {🔹2...d5 This is an attempt to play in Grünfeld style. Our answer is 3.e3 (The main move is 3.cxd5, but then Black will obtain positions à la Grünfeld after a later ...g6) . This [e3]-move nicely avoids those. 3...e5 4.cxd5 Nxd5 5.Qh5 is a fresh idea I saw in the blitz game Carlsen-Nakamura, while he also played it in a rapid game against Van Foreest. The standard move is 5.Nf3 , but Carlsen's move is unexplored and gives chances for more creative play. 🔹2...c5 This move order is not so common, but it appears we've been move-ordered out of our preferred 2.Nf3 and 3.d4 against in the Symmetrical English, keeping the knight on [b1] – here the knight is already on [c3]. But thanks to that knight, White can play 3.e4 And after 3...Nc6 4.Nge2 White will either play [g3] and [d3] and enter the Botvinnik Setup for example if Black fianchettoes his dark-squared bishop or will push [d4] in case of ...[e6], thus transposing to the lines after 2...e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.d4 . The only additional option Black has is 4...e6 5.d4 d5 Leading to unexplored positions after 6.cxd5 exd5 7.Bg5} 3. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Executing the main idea of [Nc3]. Now Black has two main theoretical moves.} d5 {Recently this move has taken over as the main one.} (3... c5 {is the alternative. In view of the move orders from the Symmetrical English 1…c5, where the knight is already on [f3], White needs to play 4.Nf3 . The main theoretical line is 4.e5 Ng8 5.d4 cxd4 6.Qxd4 Nc6 . If Black answer to Nf3 by 4...Nc6 , then: 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 . This position can be reached via other move orders, for example from the Symmetrical English. It is in fact a position that also arises from the Taimanov Sicilian after 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.c4 Nf6 6.Nc3 . It became popular lately as some new ideas were discovered for White and we explore these in detail.}) 4. cxd5 ({Usually White played} 4. e5 {immediately, but recent practice seemed to neutralize this attempt. Therefore, White tries an alternative way to push [e5] by first taking on [d5].}) 4... exd5 5. e5 {These positions are less explored than those after the immediate 4.e5 and lead to complex middlegame positions.} *

