1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} c5 {This is a rare move order, but it's important to examine it because with a knight on [c3] White cannot play like in the chapter on the Symmetrical English with [Nf3] and [d4] since in that line the knight stays on [b1] to avoid the pin after ...[Bb4].} ({Another rare option is} 2... c6 {, when after} 3. e4 d5 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. e5 d4 6. exf6 dxc3 7. bxc3 exf6 8. d4 {, White gets a good position thanks to the central pawns especially the passed d-pawn.}) ({In case of} 2... c6 3. e4 e5 4. Nf3 Bb4 5. Nxe5 O-O 6. Nd3 Bxc3 7. dxc3 Nxe4 8. Be2 {, White has a pleasant position thanks to the bishop pair.}) 3. e4 {[%cal Ge4e5] Instead of [Nf3] and [d4], White executes the move he prepared with [Nc3].} Nc6 ({The move} 3... e6 {transposes to the main line after 2...e6 3.e4 c5 , while 3...d6 4.Nge2 with [g3], [Bg2] to come we will have a transposition to the chapter The Botvinnik Setup, the plans where Black plays ...[c5] instead of ...[e5].}) 4. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d4] White wants to push [d4] and supports it with a knight from [e2], rather than [f3]. This would be useful in case Black decides to shut the center with 4...e5 , as then, with a knight on [e2], White would be much faster to play [f4] and take the initiative on the kingside.} ({An aggressive alternative is the move} 4. g4 $5 {, with the idea to reach the Botvinnik setup with an expanded kingside where the g-pawn is already on [g4] rather than on [g3].}) 4... e6 {[%cal Rd7d5] Black wants to counter in the center with ...[d5].} ({In case of} 4... g6 5. d3 {followed by [g3], [Bg2], etc. we have a transposition to the chapter The Botvinnik Setup.}) ({After} 4... e5 5. g3 d6 6. Bg2 {, White should start by playing on the queenside with [a3], [Rb1], and [b4], and then to seek an appropriate moment for kingside play with [f4], if necessary.} ({Note that the move} 6. Nd4 $2 {is bad in view of e5!})) 5. d4 d5 {[%cal Rd5e4,Rc5d4,Rd5c4] The most direct.} ({After} 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 {, we have a transposition to the lines '2...[e6] with 3...c5' #1 & #2 after 2...e6 3.e4 c5 4.Nf3 Nc6 5.d4 cxd4 6.Nxd4 .}) 6. cxd5 {The pawn on [c4] was without defense, so White exchanged it.} exd5 7. Bg5 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gg5d8,Gc3d5] The pin on the knight means that the pawn on [d5] is attacked.} cxd4 ({In case of} 7... dxe4 8. d5 Ne5 9. Ng3 {, White will regain the pawn and will have a strong passed pawn on [d5], while after:}) (7... Be7 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. dxc5 d4 10. Nd5 {, White is a pawn up with a strong centralized knight. Black has some compensation, but even if he manages to regain the pawn, White's strong knight and superior structure Black's pawn on [d4] is isolated and needs constant protection will remain.}) 8. Nxd5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Gd5f6,Gg5f6] Moving away from the attack by putting more pressure on the pinned knight on [f6].} Qa5+ {[%cal Ra5e1,Rf6d5] Black escapes the pin with tempo.} ({In case of} 8... Be6 9. Nxf6+ gxf6 10. Bd2 {, White will follow up with [Nf4], [Bd3] and 0-0 with a very compact position.}) 9. Bd2 {[%cal Gd2a5] Black also threatened ...[Nxd5], so White must cover the check with tempo.} Qd8 10. Nef4 {[%cal Gf4d5,Gf1d3] Connecting the knights and allowing the light-squared bishop to join the game.} ({Of course, if White wishes so, it's possible to repeat moves with} 10. Bg5 {.}) 10... Bd6 {Black also develops.} ({It's not recommendable to take the pawn on e4,} 10... Nxe4 $2 11. Qe2 Bf5 12. g4 d3 13. Qxd3 Ne5 14. Qb5+ {and White wins material after} Qd7 15. gxf5 Nf3+ 16. Kd1 Nxf2+ 17. Kc1 {as after taking on [h1] the knight will be lost, leaving White with two pieces for a rook.}) 11. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White develops and defends the pawn on [e4].} O-O 12. O-O {[%cal Gd3c2,Gc2b3,Gb3g8,Gd2f4,Gf2f4] Both sides almost finished development. White has very good central control thanks to the dominating knight on [d5]. White's pawn structure is also better, with no pawn weaknesses, while Black's pawn on [d4], while a passed one, is blockaded and requires constant defense. 💡White's plan is to: 🔹activate the bishops, for example by [Bc2]-[b3] and [Bf4] as the knight on [f4] will likely replace its brother on [d5] after an exchange on that square; and, 🔹ultimately advance the majority on the kingside by pushing [f4] and then either [e5] or [f5].} *

