1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} d5 {This move is an attempt to give the position a more Grunfeld-like flair.} 3. e3 {[%cal Gf1c4] A clever move order that aims to discourage Black's Grünfeld attempts.} e5 {[%cal Rd5d4] This is another option, giving the position a reversed Sicilian flair.} 4. cxd5 {Black was threatening ...[d4], so White takes on [d5].} Nxd5 5. Qh5 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gh5e5] A rare move, but one that poses concrete problems.} Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e5] Black develops and defends the pawn on [e5].} ({The move} 5... Be6 {leads to complications after} 6. Nf3 $1 {intending not only [Nxe5] but also [Ng5]} Nb4 7. Ng5 Qf6 8. Nxe6 Qxe6 9. Qd1 {when White managed to get the bishop pair. Black can claim White's after} e4 10. a3 Nd3+ 11. Bxd3 exd3 12. b4 {which leads to unclear play. White has good development after [Bb2] and the pawn on [d3] may turn out to be a weakness in the long run.}) 6. Bb5 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gb5e8,Gh5e5] Continuing the development and again targeting the pawn on [e5].} Qd6 {[%cal Gd6e5] Black defends the pawn.} ({The pawn sacrifice} 6... Ndb4 $6 {isn't sufficient after} 7. Qxe5+ Be6 8. Qe4 {and White defends everything.}) 7. Nf3 {[%csl Ye5,Yf7][%cal Gf3e5,Gh5e5,Gb5e8,Gf3g5,Gg5f7,Gh5f7] Still continuing the attack on the central [e5]-pawn. The alternative threat is [Ng5].} Nxc3 {Black releases the tension in the center to alleviate the pressure.} 8. bxc3 {[%cal Gd2d4] Threatening [d4].} e4 ({The move} 8... Bd7 {allows White to expand in the center with} 9. d4 {, after which White will castle short and use the b-file to activate his rook.}) 9. Ng5 {[%csl Yf7,Ye4][%cal Gg5e4,Gg5f7,Gh5f7] Moving away with tempo by attacking both pawns on [e4] and [f7].} g6 10. Qd1 {[%cal Gd1b3,Gg5e4] The queen is rerouted to the queenside, now that Black covered the kingside.} f5 {Black defends the pawn on [e4].} 11. Qb3 {[%csl Yf7][%cal Gb3f7,Gg5f7] Again threatening the [f7]-square, only this time from the other side!} Qe7 {[%cal Ge7g5,Ge7f7]} 12. h4 {[%csl Bf4,Gg5][%cal Gh4g5,Gg5h3,Gh3f4] White defends the knight and establishes control over the dark squares on the kingside. Ideally, the knight will be rerouted via [h3] to [f4].} h6 {Black chases away the knight and also fights for the dark squares.} 13. Nh3 g5 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gg5f4] Preventing the knight from coming to the desirable square on [f4].} 14. Ba4 {[%csl Yb7][%cal Gb3b7,Gc1b2,Ge1c1,Gh3g1,Gg1e2] A prophylactic move that prevents the development of the bishop on [c8] in view of the attack on the pawn on [b7]. 💡White will continue with: 🔹Bb2 and [O-O-O]; and, 🔹then [Ng1]-[e2] to bring the knight back into the game. 🔹 A possible ...[a6] will be met by [c4], stopping ...[b5]. Black has problems with the king stuck in the center and with the development of the queenside. The position is quite complex, but with good development and the somewhat exposed black kingside, White has good prospects.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
