1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} d5 {This move is an attempt to give the position a more Grünfeld-like flair.} 3. e3 {[%cal Gf1c4] A clever move order that aims to discourage Black's Grünfeld attempts.} c5 {[%cal Rd5d4]} ({Black reinforces the threat of ...d4, as the immediate} 3... d4 $6 {isn't very good after} 4. exd4 Qxd4 5. Nf3 {with [d4] next, which gives White a strong center.}) ({The fianchetto with} 3... g6 $6 {is met by} 4. Qa4+ $1 c6 5. cxd5 Nxd5 6. Qd4 $1 {the absence of a pawn on [d4] comes in handy} Nf6 7. Qxd8+ Kxd8 8. d4 {with a very comfortable endgame for White thanks to the space advantage and the passive character of Black's position. if 4...Nc6 , White should simply play 5.d4 with [Nf3], [Be2] and [O-O] and comfortable play as Black lacks the Grünfeld dynamism.}) 4. cxd5 {White naturally takes on [d5].} Nxd5 5. Nf3 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf3e5,Re7e5] Another natural developing move that also prevents ...[e5].} Nxc3 ({The move} 5... e6 {after} 6. Bc4 {leads to a transposition to the chapter on the QGD Systems, analyzed via the move order 1.c4 e6 2.Nc3 d5 3.e3 Nf6 4.Nf3 c5 5.cxd5 Nxd5 6.Bc4 .}) ({The Grunfeld attempt with} 5... g6 $6 {doesn't work because of of the same disruptive check} 6. Qa4+ $1 Nc6 7. Bb5 {and Black's queenside is under severe pressure. White will take on [c6] and wreck Black's queenside structure.} ({After Nc6} 7. Bc4 Nxc3 8. dxc3 {, we will reach positions very similar to the ones analyzed in the present line.})) 6. dxc3 ({Taking with the b-pawn would allow Black to obtain a Grunfeld-like position after} 6. bxc3 g6 {.}) 6... Qc7 ({The endgame after} 6... Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {is very pleasant for White. See the model game Radjabov-Svidler for the details.}) 7. e4 {[%csl Gc8,Gf8][%cal Gc1e3,Gf1d3] White takes space in the center and opens the [c1]-[h6] diagonal for the dark-squared bishop. This is the core difference in the position that makes it more pleasant to play for White: White's bishops can be developed freely, while Black's cannot. Black's light-squared bishop will either be limited by its own pawn after [e6], or by White's [e4]-pawn after [b6] and [Bb7]. The dark-squared bishop will be limited either by its own pawn on [c5] after [e6] or by White's [c3]-pawn after [g6] and [Bg7].} Nc6 8. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5] Attacking the pawn on [c5] and developing with tempo.} e6 {[%cal Gf8c5]} 9. Nd2 {[%cal Gd1g4,Gg4g7] White frees the path for the queen to [g4], from where it would target the [g7]-pawn.} Be7 10. Qg4 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gg4g7] White follows the plan. The queen is well-placed on the kingside.} O-O 11. Qg3 {[%cal Gg3c7] The endgames with this pawn structure are favorable for White as we can see in the model game Radjabov-Svidler, so White gets away from a possible discovered attack with [e5] and offers the trade.} Bd6 {Black is well-advised to avoid the exchange.} ({After} 11... Qxg3 12. hxg3 b6 13. Be2 {, White has the plan to advance on the kingside, whether by [f3] and [g4] or [f4] and [g4] and can also double the rooks on the h-file.}) 12. f4 {[%csl Be4,Bf4] White expands in the center.} Rd8 13. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1] White will castle short, centralize the other rook, and then seek ways to continue play on the kingside.} b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 14. O-O Bb7 15. Qh3 {[%csl Yg3][%cal Rc7g3,Ga1e1,Gd2f3,Gf4f5] The queen steps away from the pin on the [h2]-[b8] diagonal. 💡White can concentrate pieces on the kingside by: 🔹the coming of our a-rook on [e1] our knight on [f3]; 🔹the [f5]-advance which was prepared by the queen's retreat on [f5]. This regrouping of offensive forces would allow a promising attack.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
