[White "5) The Flexible 1...Nf6"]
[Black "Flexible Nf6: 2...e6 with 3...c5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "B44"]
[PlyCount "37"]
[GameId "2102815304531499"]

1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} e6 {[%cal Rf8b4] Black plays in Nimzo-Indian style, planning ...[Bb4].} ({The move} 2... d6 3. e4 {would transpose to the chapter on the Botvinnik Setup.}) 3. e4 {White executes the central advance with the e-pawn. Now Black has two main attempts: 3...c5 and 3...d5 .} c5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4] Black takes control of the [d4]-square.} 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gd2d4] White will nevertheless manage to push [d4].} ({The main theoretical move is} 4. e5 {.}) 4... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4] Black develops and doesn't close the [a3]-[f8] diagonal for the bishop.} ({In case of} 4... d6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {, we have a hedgehog position and these were analyzed in the chapter on the Symmetrical English, 2...[b6] variation via the move order 1.c4 c5 2.Nf3 b6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Bb7 5.Nc3 Nf6 6.f3 d6 7.e4 etc.}) 5. d4 {White pushes [d4] before Black can stop it, for example by ...[Nd4].} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {This position can also arise from the Sicilian, via 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.c4 Nf6 6.Nc3 . Black's best now is to pin the knight on b4 with 6...Bb4 .} Bc5 {[%cal Rc5d4,Rc6d4]} ({This is the main alternative to} 6... Bb4 {. Black attacks the centralized knight on [d4].}) 7. Nc2 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Gc2b4] The retreat to [c2] prevents ...[Bb4].} ({Black's idea is seen after} 7. Nb3 Bb4 8. Bd3 d5 {, when Black manages to simplify the position in the center and after some forcing play, to equalize.}) 7... Qb6 {[%csl Yf2][%cal Rb6f2] Black is practically forced to enter a forcing line where he will struggle to equalize.} ({The other moves allow White to stabilize the position, keeping the space advantage. For example} 7... O-O 8. Be3 b6 9. Qd2 Bb7 10. O-O-O {with a strong grip on the [d6]-square and the d-file, which White will dominate after an exchange on [c5] and [Qd6].}) 8. Qd2 {[%csl Yb6,Yc5][%cal Gd2f2,Gc3a4,Ga4b6,Ga4c5] White defends the pawn on [f2] and threatens [Na4].} Ng4 {[%csl Yf2][%cal Gg4f2,Gb6f2] The beginning of the forcing variation.} ({The alternative leads to a better endgame for White:} 8... O-O 9. Na4 Bb4 10. Nxb6 Bxd2+ 11. Bxd2 axb6 12. Be3 Nxe4 13. Bxb6 d5 14. c5 {and White will manage to stop Black's central advance while his own queenside pawn mass, helped by the bishop pair and the bishop on [b6] in particular is more difficult to stop.}) 9. f3 {[%cal Gf3g4] The pawn escapes the attacked square.} Nf2 {[%cal Gf2h1]} 10. Na4 {[%cal Ga4b6,Ga4c5] It appears that White simply wins two pieces for the rook, but Black musters some counterplay.} Qc7 11. Nxc5 Nxh1 {[%cal Gc7h2]} 12. f4 {[%cal Gd2f4] Preventing ...[Qxh2]. It will take some time to capture the knight on [h1] and Black manages to activate his pieces in the meantime.} O-O 13. Be2 {White should speed up the development before the game is opened.} d5 {Black must open the game, otherwise he's just lost.} 14. Kf1 {[%cal Gf1g1,Gg1h1] With the idea of [Kg1xh1].} dxe4 ({Taking on c4 allows White to keep the position more closed after} 14... dxc4 15. e5 b6 16. Ne4 {with [Bf3] next.}) 15. Nxe4 Rd8 {[%cal Rd8d2]} 16. Qe1 {[%cal Gc1e3] Allowing the bishop to develop to [e3].} e5 {[%csl Yc2,Ye4][%cal Rc8f5,Rf5c2] Black must continue aggressively. The threat is ...[Bf5].} 17. Nc3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc3d5] White avoids the attack with ...[Bf5] and threatens [Nd5].} Be6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge6d5] Black covers the [d5]-square, but with his next move White regains access.} 18. f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e6] Luring the bishop to [f5] to gain tempo for improving of the position of the knight on [c2].} Bxf5 19. Ne3 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge3d5,Gc3d5,Ge3f5] White managed to activate the knights and obtain control of the [d5]-square. Black has some compensation for the material currently he's an exchange up, but the knight on [h1] is lost. 💡However, in the long-term, White has the better chances once he manages to: 🔹complete development; and, 🔹take the knight in the corner.} *

