1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} e6 {[%cal Rf8b4] Black plays in Nimzo-Indian style, planning ...[Bb4].} ({The move} 2... d6 3. e4 {would transpose to the chapter on the Botvinnik Setup.}) 3. e4 {White executes the central advance with the e-pawn. Now Black has two main attempts: 3...c5 and 3...d5 .} c5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc5d4] Black takes control of the [d4]-square.} 4. Nf3 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gd2d4] White will nevertheless manage to push [d4].} ({The main theoretical move is} 4. e5 {.}) 4... Nc6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Gc5d4] Black develops and doesn't close the [a3]-[f8] diagonal for the bishop.} ({In case of} 4... d6 5. d4 cxd4 6. Nxd4 {, we have a hedgehog position and these were analyzed in the chapter on the Symmetrical English, 2...[b6] variation via the move order 1.c4 c5 2.Nf3 b6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Bb7 5.Nc3 Nf6 6.f3 d6 7.e4 etc.}) 5. d4 {White pushes [d4] before Black can stop it, for example by ...[Nd4].} cxd4 6. Nxd4 {This position can also arise from the Sicilian, via 1.e4 c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.c4 Nf6 6.Nc3 . Black's best now is to pin the knight on [b4] with ...[Bb4].} Bb4 {[%csl Ye4][%cal Rb4e1,Rf6e4] The main theoretical move.} ({After} 6... d6 7. Be2 Be7 8. O-O O-O 9. Be3 {with [Qd2], [Rac1], [Rfd1], [f3] to come, White develops in exactly the same way as in the hedgehog lines from the 2...[b6] variation of the Symmetrical English.}) ({Another alternative is} 6... Qc7 7. Be2 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Bc5 9. Qd3 O-O 10. Bg5 {, when White wants to wreck Black's kingside structure with [Bxf6] and then castle queenside, with play against Black's king.}) 7. Nxc6 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gf1d3,Gd3e4] White must exchange on [c6] in order to be able to defend the pawn on [e4] with [Bd3].} bxc6 ({The endgame after} 7... dxc6 $6 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. e5 {is excellent for White. Black's light-squared bishop won't be an easy piece to develop.}) 8. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Ge1g1] White defends the pawn on [e4] and plans to castle next.} e5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge5d4] This is Black's main move. It prevents [e5] and takes control of the dark central squares.} ({Exchanging on c3 first is premature,} 8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 e5 10. O-O O-O 11. c5 $1 {breaks Black's structure since Black will be forced to play ...[d6] and after the exchange [cxd6] we will have a symmetrical pawn structure with White having the bishop pair.}) ({Allowing e5 is not good for Black,} 8... O-O $6 9. e5 $1 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Qa5 11. Bf4 Qxc3+ 12. Kf1 Ne8 13. h4 {gives White a strong initiative on the kingside.}) ({It's also worth knowing that the exchanges in the center after} 8... d5 {do not solve Black's problems after} 9. exd5 exd5 10. O-O O-O 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Be3 {when the isolani on [d5] will be safely blockaded while White's queenside majority can advance freely.}) 9. O-O O-O 10. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c3] The queen on [c2] prevents the doubling of the pawns after ...[Bxc3].} Bc5 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Rc5g1] The bishop is repositioned on the [g1]-[a7] diagonal since there is no more point in staying on [b4].} ({A move like} 10... d6 {is met by} 11. Na4 $1 {cutting off the retreat of the bishop and preparing [a3] and [b4].}) 11. Na4 {[%csl Yd7][%cal Ga4c5,Gc4c5] White goes after the bishop. Play revolves on the queenside, where White wants to push [c5] to fix the pawn on [d7] and in doing so to force Black to push ...[d5], which after [cxd6] would leave the [c6]-pawn isolated and weak.} Bd4 12. Be3 $1 {[%cal Ge3d4] White persists in exchanging Black's dark-squared bishop.} Bxe3 13. fxe3 {[%csl Bd4,Bf4][%cal Ge3d4,Ge3f4,Gf1f8,Gc4c5] In exchange for the doubled e-pawns White obtained control of the important central squares especially the [e3]-pawn covers the vulnerable dark squares [d4] and [f4] and White's rook on [f1] obtained an open file. White still wants to play [c5], to fix the [d7]-pawn.} d6 {This doesn't stop White's next.} ({The open f-file comes in handy if Black tries to break free with} 13... d5 $2 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. exd5 Qxd5 16. Rxf6 $1 {and White wins as} gxf6 17. Be4 {wins the rook on [a8].}) 14. c5 {[%csl Yc6] White manages to break Black's structure. After} d5 15. exd5 cxd5 ({Or} 15... Qxd5 16. Rfd1 Qe6 17. Nc3 {with the idea [Ne4]-[d6].}) 16. Be2 {[%csl Be3][%cal Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Gc5c6] 💡What we can conclude from this position is that: 🔹we see how useful the doubled e-pawns were. The second e-pawn, the one on [e3], handily stops the advance of Black's central pawn duo. 🔹On the queenside, White's pawns are free to march forward. Objectively the position is balanced, but playing with the white pieces is easier thanks to these factors.} *

