1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} e6 {[%cal Rf8b4] Black plays in Nimzo-Indian style, planning ...[Bb4].} ({The move} 2... d6 3. e4 {would transpose to the chapter on the Botvinnik Setup.}) 3. e4 {White executes the central advance with the e-pawn. Now Black has two main attempts: 3...c5 and 3...d5 .} d5 4. cxd5 ({The alternative is} 4. e5 {, but Black has found good ways to deal with it after} d4 {.}) 4... exd5 5. e5 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ge5f6] White wins space in the center and wants to play [d4] next.} d4 {[%cal Rd4c3] The counterattacking move is the main move without the exchange on [d5], but here it's less good. This is one of the reasons why White should prefer taking on [d5] before pushing [e5].} 6. exf6 {White takes the knight as on the next move he will have a pleasant choice.} dxc3 7. Bb5+ {[%cal Gb5e8] White develops with tempo.} ({The simple} 7. fxg7 cxd2+ 8. Bxd2 Bxg7 9. Bc4 {with [Ne2] and [O-O] is also possible, as Black's king's shelter on the kingside has been permanently weakened by the absence of the [g7]-pawn.}) 7... Nc6 ({White obtains strong compensation after} 7... c6 8. Qe2+ Be6 9. Bc4 cxd2+ 10. Bxd2 Qxf6 11. Nf3 {with [O-O] next as Black is lagging back in development and White can use his pieces to active squares like [Bc3], [Re1] etc.}) 8. Qe2+ {[%cal Ge2e8] White continues developing with tempo.} Be6 9. dxc3 {[%cal Gf6g7] Finally time to take the pawn on [c3].} Qxf6 10. Nf3 {[%cal Gb5e8,Gf3d4,Gd4c6,Gd4e6] With this developing move White threatens [Nd4].} Bd6 11. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4c6,Gd4e6] The pinned pieces on [c6] and [e6] are both under attack.} O-O {Black would like to sacrifice a pawn for compensation in case White takes on [c6], but White goes for the bishop pair instead with} 12. Nxe6 Rfe8 {[%cal Re8e6]} 13. Bc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4e6] An important move.} ({The simple} 13. Be3 Rxe6 {is satisfactory for Black in view of the good centralization of his pieces. Therefore, White seeks to disturb the coordination in Black's position.}) 13... Na5 {[%cal Ra5c4] Black wants to avoid to have to take on [e6] with the pawn, which would ruin the pawn structure.} 14. Bg5 {[%csl Yf6][%cal Gg5f6,Ge6g5] White uses the still alive knight on [e6] to force a favorable endgame.} Qg6 15. Bd3 {[%cal Gd3g6] The bishop avoids the exchange and forces Black to exchange queens after the capture on [e6].} Qxe6 16. Qxe6 Rxe6+ 17. Kd2 {[%csl Ga5,Bd3,Gg5] White got there a winning endgame with the bishop pair in a symmetrical position. Black also needs to spend time to bring the knight on the rim back to the game. It's a technical position where White plays for two results either he wins or it's a draw and Black has no counterplay. 💡White's standard play in similar positions is: 🔹to advance on both wings, thus limiting the mobility of Black's light pieces; 🔹the exchange of all rooks is also acceptable for White.} *

