1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} e6 {[%cal Rf8b4] Black plays in Nimzo-Indian style, planning ...[Bb4].} ({The move} 2... d6 3. e4 {would transpose to the chapter on the Botvinnik Setup.}) 3. e4 {White executes the central advance with the e-pawn. Now Black has two main attempts: 3...c5 and 3...d5 .} d5 4. cxd5 ({The alternative is} 4. e5 {, but Black has found good ways to deal with it after} d4 {.}) 4... exd5 5. e5 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ge5f6] White wins space in the center and wants to play [d4] next.} Ne4 {The most active move, the knight is centralized on [e4].} ({Retreating to d7 is sub-optimal, after} 5... Nfd7 $6 6. d4 c5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Bb5 {, the pin on the [a4]-[e8] diagonal prevents Black from putting pressure on White's center. If Black challenges the bishop with} a6 {, the simplest is to take on [c6] and continue development with} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O {with [Re1] next with an advantage thanks to the better pawn structure.}) 6. Nf3 {White develops first before committing with the d-pawn.} ({The immediate} 6. d4 Bb4 {gives Black counterplay.}) 6... Nc6 {This is another way to develop, but it allows the following pin. Black develops and keeps the knight on [e4].} ({Exchanging on c3 is premature:} 6... Nxc3 $6 7. bxc3 {with [d4], [Bd3], and [O-O] gives White a strong center and an advantage.}) ({Another move that doesn't work for Black is} 6... c5 $6 {as it drops a pawn to} 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Qa4+ {and [Qxe4].}) 7. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5e8] With the knight on [c6] blocking the [c7]-pawn Black's central counterplay will be based on the move ...[f6].} Be7 {Both sides finish development now.} 8. O-O O-O 9. d4 {[%csl Bd4,Be5] White established a strong center. Black should try to undermine the [e5]-pawn by ...[f6] before White coordinates to eject the knight from [e4] and organize an attack on the kingside.} Bg4 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Rg4d1,Rc6d4] An active move that pins the knight on [f3], thus indirectly putting pressure on the [d4]-pawn.} ({The immediate} 9... f6 {is possible,} 10. Re1 Nxc3 11. bxc3 fxe5 12. dxe5 Bg4 13. Be2 {, when White will play in the center for example [Bg5]-[h4]-[g3] to defend the pawn on [e5] in order to allow for [Nd4] with the ultimate goal of moving his e and f pawns forward.}) ({Another alternative is} 9... Bf5 10. Ne2 {avoiding [Nxc3]} a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Be3 {when White wants to play [Ne1]-[d3], to control both [c5] and [e5].}) 10. h3 {[%cal Gh3g4] Opening a luft i. e. an escape square is useful, as the exchange on [f3] favors White.} Bh5 ({After} 10... Bxf3 $6 11. gxf3 Ng5 12. f4 Ne4 13. Ne2 {the knight on [e4] is in trouble.}) 11. Ne2 {[%csl Yh5][%cal Ge2f4,Gf4h5] Avoiding the exchange on [c3] and introducing [Nf4] ideas.} f6 {[%cal Rf6e5] As mentioned previously, Black's counterplay consists of undermining the [e5]-pawn.} ({After} 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 Ng5 13. Bxg5 Bxg5 14. f4 Bh6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Rc1 {White targets the doubled c-pawns and also has a mobile pawn pair in the center.}) 12. Be3 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Ge3d4,Ge3f2,Ga1c1,Gc1c6,Gb5c6] White completes the development. The bishop strengthens both the [d4]-pawn and the [f2]-pawn and frees the [c1]-square for the rook.} fxe5 13. Bxc6 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gf3e5] White wants to establish a strong knight on [e5].} ({It's possible to play} 13. Nxe5 Nxe5 14. dxe5 c6 15. Bd3 {which leads to a complex middlegame where White wants to take the knight on [e4] and has ideas like [Qb3], [Nf4] and [e6].}) 13... bxc6 14. Nxe5 {[%csl Bc5,Be5,Yc6][%cal Ge5c6,Gf2f3,Gf3e4,Ge2g3,Gg3h5,Be5d3,Bd3c5,Ga1c1,Gc1c6] White has a strong position in the center. The dominating knight targets the [c6]-pawn. 💡The English-player can put into practice these positional ideas: 🔹attacking Black's centralized knight with [f3] and proceed with [Ng3] next, taking control of the light squares. 🔹playing [Rc1] and [Nd3], taking control of the [c5]-square.} *

