1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to expand with [e4].} e6 {[%cal Rf8b4] Black plays in Nimzo-Indian style, planning ...[Bb4].} ({The move} 2... d6 3. e4 {would transpose to the chapter on the Botvinnik Setup.}) 3. e4 {White executes the central advance with the e-pawn. Now Black has two main attempts: 3...c5 and 3...d5 .} d5 4. cxd5 ({The alternative is} 4. e5 {, but Black has found good ways to deal with it after} d4 {.}) 4... exd5 5. e5 {[%cal Gd2d4,Ge5f6] White wins space in the center and wants to play [d4] next.} Ne4 {The most active move, the knight is centralized on [e4].} ({Retreating to d7 is sub-optimal, after} 5... Nfd7 $6 6. d4 c5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. Bb5 {, the pin on the [a4]-[e8] diagonal prevents Black from putting pressure on White's center. If Black challenges the bishop with} a6 {, the simplest is to take on [c6] and continue development with} 9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. O-O {. [Re1] will follow and White will have an advantage thanks to the better pawn structure.}) 6. Nf3 {White develops first before committing with the d-pawn.} ({The immediate} 6. d4 Bb4 {gives Black counterplay.}) 6... Bf5 {Black develops and keeps the knight on [e4].} ({Exchanging on c3 is premature:} 6... Nxc3 $6 7. bxc3 {with [d4], [Bd3], and [O-O] gives White a strong center and an advantage.}) ({Another move that doesn't work for Black is} 6... c5 $6 {as it drops a pawn to} 7. Nxe4 dxe4 8. Qa4+ {and [Qxe4].}) 7. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2d4] White continues development and keeps the d-pawn on [d2].} ({The immediate} 7. d4 {is met by} Bb4 8. Bd2 c5 {. By playing [Be2] first White avoids this option.} ({In case of d3} 8... Nxc3 9. bxc3 c5 {d4 Qa5 gives Black good counterchances.})) 7... d4 {Black's most principled reply, stopping White's [d4]. Against all other moves White continues with [d4] when Black cannot conveniently play ...Bb4 followed by ...c5.} ({For example,} 7... Nc6 8. d4 Bb4 9. Qb3 O-O 10. O-O Bxc3 11. bxc3 Na5 12. Qb2 c5 13. dxc5 $5 {keeps the position open enough for White's bishops as White can plant a knight on [d4] and advance with [f4].}) ({After} 7... c5 8. d4 Nc6 9. O-O c4 10. Be3 Be7 11. Ne1 {frees the path for the f and g pawns while another idea is the move [Bg4] as after the exchange of the light-squared bishops the queen will be very active on [g4].}) 8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4,Gc1f4] White stops the further advance of the [d4]-pawn and opens the [c1]-[h6] diagonal for the dark-squared bishop.} Bd5 10. O-O {White only needs to develop the dark-squared bishop to [f4] to complete development, while Black is still lagging behind.} Nc6 {[%cal Rc6e5,Rd5f3]} ({Playing one more move with a pawn with} 10... c5 {is possible, though after} 11. Nd2 $1 {with [f4] and [Bf3] next, White will obtain the [e4]-square for the knight, with a mobile pawn pair on [e5] and [f4].}) 11. Bf4 {[%cal Gf4e5,Gf4g3,Gf3d2,Gf2f4] White defends the [e5]-pawn and develops the last light piece. White plans to continue with [Nd2] and [f4].} Be7 {[%cal Ge8g8] Preparing castling.} ({After} 11... Qd7 12. Bg3 Be7 13. Nd2 Qf5 14. f4 {White wants to play [Ne4] next even if it involves a pawn sacrifice – by eliminating the black light-squared bishop White will obtain excellent compensation thanks to his own unopposed light-squared bishop.}) 12. Nd2 {[%cal Gf4g3,Gf2f4]} ({White waits for Black to castle and then to retreat the bishop to g3, though the immediate} 12. Bg3 h5 $5 {this is what White wants to avoid by waiting for Black's castle} 13. h3 {with [Nd2] next is also possible.}) 12... O-O 13. Bg3 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gf2f4,Gd2e4,Ge2f3,Gd1c2,Ga2a3,Ga1e1] Now there is no ...[h5], so the bishop can drop back to [g3] to allow for [f4]. 💡After [f4] White will: 🔹centralize the knight on [e4], play [Bf3], [Qc2] possibly preceded by [a3] to stop [Nb4], and [Rae1], concentrating the pieces in the center; and, 🔹then, look for opportunities to increase his activity in the center and the kingside.} *

