1. c4 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7] In this chapter, we look at the variations where Black chooses to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop in King's Indian style. These KID positions do not impose great move order challenges on White because Black doesn't challenge White's center. This gives White a wide array of set-ups to choose from, but it's important to keep in mind the move orders from the other chapters. In the other variations, we have seen that White uses the move order of [Nc3] and [e4], so it was only natural that the same set-up should be played against the KID as well.} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and, for instance after} Bg7 {,} 3. e4 {.}) 2... Bg7 3. Nc3 d6 4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg1e2] The start of the Botvinnik Setup. White develops with [Bg2] and [Nge2]. Black has a choice whether to push [e5] or [c5] or, rarely, both, but White usually manages to keep some initiative in the opening.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
