1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again, Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... e5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg1e2] White continues with the intended development.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Botvinnik Setup. After White's next move Black has a wide choice.} ({If Black decides to lock in the center with} 5... c5 {, White starts with queenside play first after} 6. Rb1 Nc6 7. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 {stopping [b4], but weakening the [b5]-square} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {and White will use the [b5]-square for the knight as after [Nb5] and [Bd2] he will be able to push [b4] and obtain initiative on the queenside.} ({Note that f5?! isn't possible as exf5 opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2] and after gxf5} 10. d4 $1 {White immediately starts an attack on Black's center.})) 6. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1] White's usual development. Now Black has a wide choice, but in all the lines the following 📌rules of thumb are worth remembering: 🔸1 White should jump [Nd5] only when Black cannot conveniently capture with a knight. This usually means that White plays [Nd5] when Black's light-squared bishop is already on [e6], as the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is very favorable for White, who in that case would obtain control over the light squares thanks to the unopposed light-squared bishop and the central pawns on light squares most likely on [d5] and [e4]. 🔸 White develops with [Be3] and [Qd2], but with a Black pawn on [f5] the pawn sacrifice [f4] must be taken into consideration. To ensure against problems of this kind, White often plays the move [f3], which allows for [Bf2] and blocks [f4]-[f3]. 🔸3 With a black pawn on [f5], the moment to take on [f5] is important: White only takes on [f5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight, because after [Nxf5] Black obtains strong control of the [d4]-square. In this case, White keeps the tension in the center and most likely will advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5]. When Black cannot recapture with a knight, after taking [exf5], there are two possibilities: ➢ a In case of [Bxf5], White would like to continue with [d4], expanding in the center with the likely idea of [d4]-[d5], which gains space and secures the [e4]-square for a knight; ➢ b In case of [gxf5] the threat of [f4] can be dangerous, so White stops it by pushing [f4] himself. If Black takes on [f4] White recaptures with a piece likely a knight, obtaining an excellent blockading square on [f4] in front of the isolated pawn on [f5]. If Black keeps the tension, White will revert to the central break [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and possibly again intending [d5]. 🔸4 White's main pawn advances are [b4]-[b5] on the queenside, [d4] in the center and [f4] on the kingside. By keeping these ideas in mind, White should be able to navigate the following lines even without remembering the exact moves.} Nge7 {[%cal Ge8g8,Rf7f5] Black develops the king's knight without blocking the f-pawn and plans to castle.} 7. O-O {Both sides castle now.} O-O 8. d3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd1d2] White's further plan is [Be3] and [Qd2], when he will have completed the development.} Be6 {Black also develops.} ({Note that the move} 8... Nd4 9. Nxd4 exd4 {is analyzed via the move order 6...Nd4.}) ({After} 8... f5 9. Nd5 Be6 {,we will have a transposition.}) 9. Nd5 $1 {[%csl Bd5] White follows the rule of thumb to jump to [d5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight – here that would lose a piece to the fork after [cxd5].} Qd7 10. Be3 {White continues with development.} f5 {After completing development, Black starts activity on the kingside.} 11. Qd2 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gd2f4,Ge2f4,Ge3f4,Gg3f4,Gd5f4] White also completes development. At this point there is no threat of ...[f4], since White controls that square 5 times.} Rf7 {[%cal Ga8f8] Black plans to double on the f-file.} 12. b4 $1 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gd5e7,Ge4f5] White pursues the plan detailed in the third rule of thumb: he wants to play [b5], to prevent Black from recapturing on [e7] with a knight, so that after [Nxe7] in whichever way Black recaptures White can follow up with [exf5] and [d4].} Raf8 ({It's worth noting that White's plan is tactically sound, as the 'trick'} 12... f4 $6 {works in White's favor after} 13. gxf4 exf4 14. Nexf4 Bxa1 15. Nxe6 Qxe6 16. Nxc7 Qc8 17. Nxa8 Bg7 18. d4 Qxa8 19. b5 {followed by [c5] and White's central pawn mass supported by the pair of bishops is worth more than Black's piece.}) 13. b5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gd5e7,Ge4f5] White follows his plan.} f4 {[%cal Rf4e3,Rf4f3] Black seeks counterplay.} ({White's plan is ideally implemented after} 13... Nd8 14. Nxe7+ Qxe7 15. exf5 Bxf5 16. d4 {and we have the perfect scenario from the third rule of thumb, case a＊ Black recaptures on [f5] with a piece.}) 14. gxf4 {The pawn has to be taken as the bishop had nowhere to go.} Nd4 ({The only way, as} 14... exf4 $2 15. Ndxf4 {simply wins for White as the knight on [c6] is hanging and Black gave up a pawn for nothing.}) 15. Nxe7+ {[%cal Gg2b7] Now White simplifies the position by opening the long diagonal and eventually wins the pawn on [b7].} Qxe7 16. Bxd4 {White must take with the bishop as otherwise ...[exd4] would trap the bishop on [e3].} exd4 17. f5 $1 {[%cal Gf5e6,Ge4f5,Gg2b7,Ge2g3] The key move to open the long diagonal.} gxf5 {If the bishop retreats then White plays [Ng3], [f4] and [Rae1], with a very strong position in the center and the kingside, with both black bishops being very passive.} 18. exf5 {[%cal Gg2b7,Gf5e6]} Bxf5 {If the bishop moves back then [Ng3] and [Rae1] come.} 19. Bxb7 {[%cal Gb7g2,Ge2g3,Ga1e1,Gf2f3,Gf3f4] White won a pawn and will have a winning endgame thanks to the well-advanced queenside. Black has certain compensation on the kingside, but it's not very concrete. 💡White will consolidate with: 🔹the retreat of the bishop on [g2] and [Ng3] [f3] or [f4], [Rae1]; and, 🔹if everything is defended on the kingside, the way is to continue with [a4]-[a5] on the queenside.} *

