1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... e5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg1e2] White continues with the intended development.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Botvinnik Setup. After White's next move Black has a wide choice.} ({If Black decides to lock in the center with} 5... c5 {, White starts with queenside play first after} 6. Rb1 Nc6 7. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 {stopping [b4], but weakening the [b5]-square} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {and White will use the [b5]-square for the knight as after [Nb5] and [Bd2] he will be able to push [b4] and obtain initiative on the queenside.} ({Note that f5?! isn't possible as exf5 opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2] and after gxf5} 10. d4 $1 {White immediately starts an attack on Black's center.})) 6. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1] White's usual development. Now Black has a wide choice, but in all the lines the following 📌rules of thumb are worth remembering: 🔸1 White should jump [Nd5] only when Black cannot conveniently capture with a knight. This usually means that White plays [Nd5] when Black's light-squared bishop is already on [e6], as the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is very favorable for White, who in that case would obtain control over the light squares thanks to the unopposed light-squared bishop and the central pawns on light squares most likely on [d5] and [e4]. 🔸 White develops with [Be3] and [Qd2], but with a Black pawn on [f5] the pawn sacrifice [f4] must be taken into consideration. To ensure against problems of this kind, White often plays the move [f3], which allows for [Bf2] and blocks [f4]-[f3]. 🔸3 With a black pawn on [f5], the moment to take on [f5] is important: White only takes on [f5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight, because after [Nxf5] Black obtains strong control of the [d4]-square. In this case, White keeps the tension in the center and most likely will advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5]. When Black cannot recapture with a knight, after taking [exf5], there are two possibilities: ➢ a In case of [Bxf5], White would like to continue with [d4], expanding in the center with the likely idea of [d4]-[d5], which gains space and secures the [e4]-square for a knight; ➢ b In case of [gxf5] the threat of [f4] can be dangerous, so White stops it by pushing [f4] himself. If Black takes on [f4] White recaptures with a piece likely a knight, obtaining an excellent blockading square on [f4] in front of the isolated pawn on [f5]. If Black keeps the tension, White will revert to the central break [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and possibly again intending [d5]. 🔸4 White's main pawn advances are [b4]-[b5] on the queenside, [d4] in the center and [f4] on the kingside. By keeping these ideas in mind, White should be able to navigate the following lines even without remembering the exact moves.} h5 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Rh5h4] This move has been around for quite some time, but in view of Lc0's preferences of pushing the h-pawn may get more attention. With a white knight on [e2], not defending the [h4]-square as compared to being on [f3] it makes sense to advance the h-pawn as far as possible. The drawback of the move is that after Black plays [f5], the [g5]-square will become eternally weak, and a white knight keep in mind the maneuver [Ng1]-[h3]-[g5] or bishop Bg5 can slot in it nicely.} 7. h4 {[%csl Gh4] It's best for White to stop the advance immediately.} Nh6 {[%cal Rh6g4] The knight targets the [g4]-square, but White usually plays [f3] in these lines, safely covering the [g4]-square.} ({In case of} 7... Bg4 8. f3 Be6 9. d3 Qd7 10. Nd5 {first rule of thumb} f5 11. Bg5 {shows how White can use the weakening of the [g5]-square. The rules of thumb on when to take on [f5] and how to advance with [b4]-[b5] or [d4] are still valid and will guide White's subsequent play.}) 8. d3 {White continues with the usual development.} O-O 9. O-O Be6 10. Nd5 {[%csl Bd5] The knight jumps on [d5] when a bishop is on [e6] and Black cannot exchange it.} f5 {[%csl Bg5] This is Black's way to obtain counterplay, but as mentioned earlier, this weakens the [g5]-square. If Black refrains from ...[f5] White simply prepares a queenside advance with [b4]-[b5].} ({For example} 10... a5 11. b3 {in order to stop [a4] followed by [Rb1], [a3] and eventually [b4]-[b5].}) 11. Bg5 {[%csl Bg5][%cal Gg5d8] The bishop is more active on [g5] than on [e3].} Qd7 12. Qd2 {[%csl Yh6][%cal Gd2h6] White completes development with the usual development of the queen. In this case it also attacks the knight on [h6].} Kh7 {[%cal Gg7h6,Gh7h6] The knight has to stay on [h6] as going to [f7] allows [Bf6] or [Nf6] and the option for White to take on [f5] when Black won't be able to recapture with a knight as per the third rule of thumb.} 13. Rad1 {[%cal Gd1d8,Gd3d4] A move that may look vague at first, but it's a prophylactic one. White's main plans when not taking on [f5] are advancing on the queenside with [b4]-[b5] or pushing in the center with [d4].} ({After} 13. b4 Nd8 {, while:} ({𓈓14.} 13... b5 {is possible, Black can counter it with c6 , chasing away the knight on [d5]})) {𓈓14. d4 is a better try Ndf7 Rad1 , which leads to complications. Anticipating Black's idea of ...[Nd8] and ...[c6], White prepares for the central [d4]-push by placing the rook in the center, hence [Rad1].} 13... Nd8 $6 {[%cal Rc7c6] This isn't very good, but it's useful to see White's play that refutes Black's idea as it's typical for White's central play in this line.} ({After} 13... a5 14. b3 {, White will prepare [a3] and [b4] if Black does nothing.}) ({A move like} 13... Nf7 {is met by} 14. Bf6 {when the dark-squared bishops are exchanged and this weakens the position of the black king. White will then proceed with [b4]-[b5].}) 14. d4 $1 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gd1d7] This is White's idea. The rook on [d1] comes in very handy when the d-file is opened.} Ndf7 {[%cal Rf7g5]} ({Now} 14... c6 $2 {is prevented as} 15. dxe5 cxd5 16. cxd5 {with [e6] next regains the piece and gives White a winning position.}) 15. dxe5 {[%cal Gd1d7] White opens the d-file.} Nxe5 {Taking with a pawn loses to [Nf6] followed by a double capture on [d7].} 16. Nef4 {[%cal Gf4e6] White's superior coordination gives him a substantial advantage.} Nxc4 {[%cal Rc4d2] If Black avoids the exchange of the light-squared bishop with 16...[Bg8] , then after the calm} (16... Nxc4 17. Qc2 {followed by [Rfe1], White simply improves the position until Black one's cracks.}) 17. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gd5c7,Gf4e6] Threatening the knight on [c4], but also [Nxc7], as the bishop on [e6] is still under attack from the knight on [f4].} Bxd5 18. Nxd5 {[%cal Gc2c4,Gd5c7,Gc2c7] White easily regains material as the pawn on [c7] hangs in case Black moves the knight.} c6 {[%cal Rc6d5]} 19. Qxc4 {White regains the pawn and obtains a technically winning position after} cxd5 20. Rxd5 {[%csl Yd6,Bg2,Bg5] 💡The position is clear: 🔹Black's weaknesses the pawn on [d6], the kingside structure; and, 🔹White's bishop pair... give White a winning advantage.} *

