1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... e5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg1e2] White continues with the intended development.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Botvinnik Setup. After White's next move Black has a wide choice.} ({If Black decides to lock in the center with} 5... c5 {, White starts with queenside play first after} 6. Rb1 Nc6 7. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 {stopping [b4], but weakening the [b5]-square} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {and White will use the [b5]-square for the knight as after [Nb5] and [Bd2] he will be able to push [b4] and obtain initiative on the queenside.} ({Note that f5?! isn't possible as exf5 opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2] and after gxf5} 10. d4 $1 {White immediately starts an attack on Black's center.})) 6. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1] White's usual development. Now Black has a wide choice, but in all the lines the following 📌rules of thumb are worth remembering: 🔸1 White should jump [Nd5] only when Black cannot conveniently capture with a knight. This usually means that White plays [Nd5] when Black's light-squared bishop is already on [e6], as the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is very favorable for White, who in that case would obtain control over the light squares thanks to the unopposed light-squared bishop and the central pawns on light squares most likely on [d5] and [e4]. 🔸 White develops with [Be3] and [Qd2], but with a Black pawn on [f5] the pawn sacrifice [f4] must be taken into consideration. To ensure against problems of this kind, White often plays the move [f3], which allows for [Bf2] and blocks [f4]-[f3]. 🔸3 With a black pawn on [f5], the moment to take on [f5] is important: White only takes on [f5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight, because after [Nxf5] Black obtains strong control of the [d4]-square. In this case, White keeps the tension in the center and most likely will advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5]. When Black cannot recapture with a knight, after taking [exf5], there are two possibilities: ➢ a In case of [Bxf5], White would like to continue with [d4], expanding in the center with the likely idea of [d4]-[d5], which gains space and secures the [e4]-square for a knight; ➢ b In case of [gxf5] the threat of [f4] can be dangerous, so White stops it by pushing [f4] himself. If Black takes on [f4] White recaptures with a piece likely a knight, obtaining an excellent blockading square on [f4] in front of the isolated pawn on [f5]. If Black keeps the tension, White will revert to the central break [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and possibly again intending [d5]. 🔸4 White's main pawn advances are [b4]-[b5] on the queenside, [d4] in the center and [f4] on the kingside. By keeping these ideas in mind, White should be able to navigate the following lines even without remembering the exact moves.} Nd4 {[%csl Bd4] Black can play this move at various stages, but the ensuing pawn structure will be the same after the knights are exchanged.} 7. Nxd4 {White takes on [d4] and now the [d4]-square will be occupied by a pawn rather than a piece. After the natural moves} exd4 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Rd4c3]} 8. Ne2 Ne7 (8... c5 {then White employs the same idea as in the comment to Black's 10th move, i.e.} 9. d3 {followed by [O-O] and [b4]. If Black closes down the queenside and prevents [b4] by ...[a5], the play will resemble the main line.}) 9. d3 {[%csl Bc4,Bd3,Be4] White stabilizes the center with the usual move [d3].} O-O 10. O-O {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gf2f4,Ge2f4,Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] We reach a position where White can play on both wings. The [d4]-pawn gives Black some central space, but on the other hand it is a double pawn that left the control of the [f4]-square and this gives White the chance to advance with the f-pawn or to use that square for a knight. White can advance on the queenside with [b4], [a4] and on the kingside with [f4] or, the more restrained approach with [Nf4] and [h4].} a5 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ga5b4] Black stops [b4].} ({If the same is done with the c-pawn, then after} 10... c5 {: 𓈓11. b4!? is a very interesting pawn sacrifice in Benko Gambit style cxb4 a3 bxa3 Bxa3 with the simple plan of playing on the queenside with [Qd2] and [Rfb1]. This can be supported by the knight transfer [Nf4]-[d5]. 𓈓11. Nf4 is a slower alternative approach, and [h4]-[h5], probing on the kingside and still thinking of pushing [b4] on the queenside with the help of [Bd2].}) 11. b3 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Gd2b4] White stops ...[a4] and prepares [Bd2], [a3] and [b4]. However, Black is faster with queenside play after} Bd7 {[%cal Rb7b5] Already preparing ...[b5], so White should stop that by playing} 12. a4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga4b5,Gc4b5,Gc1d2,Gb3b4,Gd2b4] This doesn't mean that White had given up on queenside play since [Bd2] and [b4] are still on the cards.} c5 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Gc5b4,Ga5b4] This is a drastic solution, locking in the queenside. Otherwise, White has the option to open the b-file by pushing [b4], obtaining play on the semi-open b-file. White will not do this immediately, but it will always be an option after improving the position and achieving active play on the kingside first, with [Nf4], [h4]-[h5], [Bh3] exchanging the light-squared bishops is in White's favor since his own is the more limited one and because without it Black only has the knight to control the [d5]-square, possibly [Ra2], [f3], [Rg2], [g4] etc. similar to the plan in the main line.} 13. Nf4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gf4d5] White targets the [d5]-square.} Qc7 14. Ra2 {[%cal Ga2h2] The rook can easily be centralized on [e2] or can join the play on the kingside for example after [f3], [Bh3] and [Rg2] along the second rank.} b6 {Black cannot do much. Pushing ...[f5] can only lead to an exchange of the [f5]-pawn for the [e4]-pawn, thus giving White an extra pawn of 3 vs 2 on the kingside.} 15. Bh3 {[%csl Bd5,Yd7,Yh3][%cal Gh3d7] White wants to exchange the light-squared bishops. Without it, Black will only have the knight tied down to the [e7]-square to guard the hole on [d5].} Bc6 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc6d5] The bishop helps control the [d5]-square.} 16. f3 {[%cal Ga2g2,Gg3g4,Gg4g5,Gh3g4,Gh2h4,Gh4h5] A move that prepares the rook swing to the kingside. 💡What Is to Be Done? 🔹after moving the a-rook to [g2] and [g4]-[g5]; 🔹White can play [Bg4] and [h4]-[h5]; 🔹then develop an attack on the kingside.} *

