1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... e5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg1e2] White continues with the intended development.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Botvinnik Setup. After White's next move Black has a wide choice.} ({If Black decides to lock in the center with} 5... c5 {, White starts with queenside play first after} 6. Rb1 Nc6 7. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 {stopping [b4], but weakening the [b5]-square} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {and White will use the [b5]-square for the knight as after [Nb5] and [Bd2] he will be able to push [b4] and obtain initiative on the queenside.} ({Note that f5?! isn't possible as exf5 opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2] and after gxf5} 10. d4 $1 {White immediately starts an attack on Black's center.})) 6. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1] White's usual development. Now Black has a wide choice, but in all the lines the following 📌rules of thumb are worth remembering: 🔸1 White should jump [Nd5] only when Black cannot conveniently capture with a knight. This usually means that White plays [Nd5] when Black's light-squared bishop is already on [e6], as the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is very favorable for White, who in that case would obtain control over the light squares thanks to the unopposed light-squared bishop and the central pawns on light squares most likely on [d5] and [e4]. 🔸 White develops with [Be3] and [Qd2], but with a Black pawn on [f5] the pawn sacrifice [f4] must be taken into consideration. To ensure against problems of this kind, White often plays the move [f3], which allows for [Bf2] and blocks [f4]-[f3]. 🔸3 With a black pawn on [f5], the moment to take on [f5] is important: White only takes on [f5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight, because after [Nxf5] Black obtains strong control of the [d4]-square. In this case, White keeps the tension in the center and most likely will advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5]. When Black cannot recapture with a knight, after taking [exf5], there are two possibilities: ➢ a In case of [Bxf5], White would like to continue with [d4], expanding in the center with the likely idea of [d4]-[d5], which gains space and secures the [e4]-square for a knight; ➢ b In case of [gxf5] the threat of [f4] can be dangerous, so White stops it by pushing [f4] himself. If Black takes on [f4] White recaptures with a piece likely a knight, obtaining an excellent blockading square on [f4] in front of the isolated pawn on [f5]. If Black keeps the tension, White will revert to the central break [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and possibly again intending [d5]. 🔸4 White's main pawn advances are [b4]-[b5] on the queenside, [d4] in the center and [f4] on the kingside. By keeping these ideas in mind, White should be able to navigate the following lines even without remembering the exact moves.} Nf6 7. d3 O-O 8. O-O {This position can arise via different move-orders when Black puts the knight on [f6]. Usually, Black aims for the ...[f5] push in these positions, but White is well-prepared for it.} Ne8 {[%cal Rf7f5] A move that is typical for the KID. Black plans ...[f5].} ({The other way to prepare ...f5 after} 8... Nh5 9. Nd5 f5 10. exf5 {is analyzed via the move-order 6...f5 7.d3 Nf6 8.O-O O-O 9.Nd5 Nh5 10.exf5 here.}) ({The move} 8... Nd4 $6 {is worse here than in the position with a knight on [e7] as after} 9. Nxd4 exd4 10. Ne2 {, the pawn on [d4] is hanging. After} Nd7 11. b4 $1 {White has already grabbed space on the queenside.}) 9. Be3 {White continues with the usual development.} f5 10. exf5 $1 {Since Black cannot recapture with a knight, White follows the rule of thumb to capture on [f5].} Bxf5 ({Taking with the pawn is met with the standard reaction} 10... gxf5 11. f4 {. White will then either prepare [d4] or [b4]-[b5].}) 11. d4 {[%cal Gd4d5,Gd4e5] Simply following the guidelines from the third rule of thumb, case ➢ a Black recaptures with a bishop.} Nf6 {[%cal Rf6g4,Rg4e3] Black improves the position of the knight and threatens ...[Ng4] to harass the bishop on [e3].} 12. dxe5 {The most direct option.} ({Good alternatives are keeping the tension with} 12. h3 {and 12.d5 Nb4 13.Bg5 , with excellent control of the [e4]-square.}) 12... Nxe5 13. Nd4 {[%cal Gd4f5,Gd4e6] Centralizing the knight and threatening to take on [f5].} ({Good alternatives are} 13. h3 {, 13.Qb3 and 13.c5 .}) 13... Bg4 {[%cal Rg4d1] Forcing White to play [f3] before retreating.} 14. f3 {[%cal Gf3g4]} ({In case of} 14. Qb3 c5 $1 {Black obtains active counterchances.}) 14... Bd7 15. b3 {[%csl Gc4,Bd5][%cal Gb3c4,Gd1d2,Gd4e2,Gc3d5,Ga1d1,Gd1c2] White stabilized the position. The pawn structure is in White's favor as his three pawns on the queenside effectively control the for's ones of his opponent, thanks to the control of the [d5]-square. 💡White will improve the position with: 🔹Qc2 or d2 and [Rad1]; and, 🔹the c-knight will eventually jump to [d5].} *

