1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... e5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg1e2] White continues with the intended development.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Botvinnik Setup. After White's next move Black has a wide choice.} ({If Black decides to lock in the center with} 5... c5 {, White starts with queenside play first after} 6. Rb1 Nc6 7. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 {stopping [b4], but weakening the [b5]-square} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {and White will use the [b5]-square for the knight as after [Nb5] and [Bd2] he will be able to push [b4] and obtain initiative on the queenside.} ({Note that f5?! isn't possible as exf5 opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2] and after gxf5} 10. d4 $1 {White immediately starts an attack on Black's center.})) 6. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1] White's usual development. Now Black has a wide choice, but in all the lines the following 📌rules of thumb are worth remembering: 🔸1 White should jump [Nd5] only when Black cannot conveniently capture with a knight. This usually means that White plays [Nd5] when Black's light-squared bishop is already on [e6], as the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is very favorable for White, who in that case would obtain control over the light squares thanks to the unopposed light-squared bishop and the central pawns on light squares most likely on [d5] and [e4]. 🔸 White develops with [Be3] and [Qd2], but with a Black pawn on [f5] the pawn sacrifice [f4] must be taken into consideration. To ensure against problems of this kind, White often plays the move [f3], which allows for [Bf2] and blocks [f4]-[f3]. 🔸3 With a black pawn on [f5], the moment to take on [f5] is important: White only takes on [f5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight, because after [Nxf5] Black obtains strong control of the [d4]-square. In this case, White keeps the tension in the center and most likely will advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5]. When Black cannot recapture with a knight, after taking [exf5], there are two possibilities: ➢ a In case of [Bxf5], White would like to continue with [d4], expanding in the center with the likely idea of [d4]-[d5], which gains space and secures the [e4]-square for a knight; ➢ b In case of [gxf5] the threat of [f4] can be dangerous, so White stops it by pushing [f4] himself. If Black takes on [f4] White recaptures with a piece likely a knight, obtaining an excellent blockading square on [f4] in front of the isolated pawn on [f5]. If Black keeps the tension, White will revert to the central break [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and possibly again intending [d5]. 🔸4 White's main pawn advances are [b4]-[b5] on the queenside, [d4] in the center and [f4] on the kingside. By keeping these ideas in mind, White should be able to navigate the following lines even without remembering the exact moves.} f5 {[%cal Rg8f6] Black wants to follow up with ...[Nf6].} ({The plan consists of a quick ejection of the knight on d5 after} 6... Be6 7. d3 Qd7 8. Nd5 Nce7 9. d4 c6 10. Ne3 {followed by [O-O] is analyzed in the model game Kasparov-Short played in Linares.}) 7. d3 {White follows the usual development.} Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 {The exception to the rule of thumb. There is no bishop on [e6] and Black can exchange knights on [d5], but in this particular case the exchange of knights on [d5], while possible for Black, works nicely for White.} ({From White's side, it's a bit premature to take on f5 as} 9. exf5 Bxf5 10. d4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Ng4 $1 {gives Black counterplay.}) 9... Nh5 {[%cal Rf5f4] Black reinforces the threat of ...[f4].} 10. exf5 {Now it's time to follow the rule of thumb.} Bxf5 ({After} 10... gxf5 11. f4 {, White is solid as a rock.}) 11. Nec3 {[%cal Gg3g4,Gg4f5,Gg4h5,Gd1g4] Slight deviation from the continuation explained in the rule of the thumb to follow up with [d4]. The move [Nec3] threatens [g4] and intends to fight Black's planned occupation of the [d4]-square.} ({An alternative is the standard} 11. h3 {.}) 11... Be6 12. a4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Gc3b5,Ga4b5,Gc4b5] Connected to the previous move, an important prophylactic idea. White anticipates ...[Nd4] and plans to meet it with [Nb5], so in case of ...[Nxb5] to be able to recapture with the a-pawn.} Nd4 ({If Black tries to stop Nb5 with} 12... a6 $6 {then after} 13. a5 $1 {he will never be able to chase away the knight from [d5] with ...[c6] because in that case the [b6]-square will be weakened and White will play [Nb6].}) 13. Nb5 {[%csl Bb5,Yc7][%cal Gb5d4,Gb5c7,Gd5c7] This is White's idea. An exchange on [d4] would double Black's d-pawns, giving White a healthy kingside majority.} c6 14. Nxd4 {[%cal Gd4e6] This forces Black to double the d-pawns.} exd4 15. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4e6,Gf4h5] Forcing another exchange.} Nxf4 16. Bxf4 {[%cal Gf4d6,Gg2b7,Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Ga4a5] White has an extra pawn on the kingside, but the bishops point to the queenside. 💡Considering the latter, a further attack with [b4]-[b5] and [a5] is a natural plan to follow.} *

