1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... e5 5. Bg2 {[%cal Gg1e2] White continues with the intended development.} Nc6 {This is a major tabiya of the Botvinnik Setup. After White's next move Black has a wide choice.} ({If Black decides to lock in the center with} 5... c5 {, White starts with queenside play first after} 6. Rb1 Nc6 7. a3 {intending [b4]} a5 {stopping [b4], but weakening the [b5]-square} 8. Nge2 Nge7 9. O-O O-O 10. d3 {and White will use the [b5]-square for the knight as after [Nb5] and [Bd2] he will be able to push [b4] and obtain initiative on the queenside.} ({Note that f5?! isn't possible as exf5 opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2] and after gxf5} 10. d4 $1 {White immediately starts an attack on Black's center.})) 6. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Ge1g1] White's usual development. Now Black has a wide choice, but in all the lines the following 📌rules of thumb are worth remembering: 🔸1 White should jump [Nd5] only when Black cannot conveniently capture with a knight. This usually means that White plays [Nd5] when Black's light-squared bishop is already on [e6], as the exchange of the light-squared bishop for a knight is very favorable for White, who in that case would obtain control over the light squares thanks to the unopposed light-squared bishop and the central pawns on light squares most likely on [d5] and [e4]. 🔸 White develops with [Be3] and [Qd2], but with a Black pawn on [f5] the pawn sacrifice [f4] must be taken into consideration. To ensure against problems of this kind, White often plays the move [f3], which allows for [Bf2] and blocks [f4]-[f3]. 🔸3 With a black pawn on [f5], the moment to take on [f5] is important: White only takes on [f5] when Black cannot recapture with a knight, because after [Nxf5] Black obtains strong control of the [d4]-square. In this case, White keeps the tension in the center and most likely will advance on the queenside with [b4]-[b5]. When Black cannot recapture with a knight, after taking [exf5], there are two possibilities: ➢ a In case of [Bxf5], White would like to continue with [d4], expanding in the center with the likely idea of [d4]-[d5], which gains space and secures the [e4]-square for a knight; ➢ b In case of [gxf5] the threat of [f4] can be dangerous, so White stops it by pushing [f4] himself. If Black takes on [f4] White recaptures with a piece likely a knight, obtaining an excellent blockading square on [f4] in front of the isolated pawn on [f5]. If Black keeps the tension, White will revert to the central break [d4], attacking the [e5]-pawn and possibly again intending [d5]. 🔸4 White's main pawn advances are [b4]-[b5] on the queenside, [d4] in the center and [f4] on the kingside. By keeping these ideas in mind, White should be able to navigate the following lines even without remembering the exact moves.} f5 {[%cal Gg8f6] Black wants to follow up with ...[Nf6].} ({The plan consists of a quick ejection of the knight on d5 after} 6... Be6 7. d3 Qd7 8. Nd5 Nce7 9. d4 c6 10. Ne3 {followed by [O-O] is analyzed in the model game Kasparov-Short played in Linares.}) 7. d3 {White follows the usual development.} Nf6 8. O-O O-O 9. Nd5 {The exception to the rule of thumb. There is no bishop on [e6] and Black can exchange knights on [d5], but in this particular case the exchange of knights on [d5], while possible for Black, works nicely for White.} ({From White's side, it's a bit premature to take on f5 as} 9. exf5 Bxf5 10. d4 exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Ng4 $1 {gives Black counterplay.}) 9... Be6 ({Taking on d5 after} 9... Nxd5 10. cxd5 Ne7 11. Be3 {gives White easy play as the knight on [e7] is very passive. To activate it Black will have to play ...[c6]. After} c6 12. dxc6 bxc6 13. Qd2 d5 14. Bg5 {Black's center is under pressure as White threatens [Qb4] and/or [Rfc1], to target the backward [c6]-pawn and the pinned knight on [e7].}) ({The idea} 9... f4 {is also possible, though White can deal with it with the precise} 10. gxf4 Nh5 11. Kh1 $1 {which removes the king from the [g1]-[a7] diagonal useful in case of a later [f4] and frees the [g1]-square for the idea of [Ng1]-[f3] in case of need, while the main threat is to return the pawn with [f5] and continue with [Ng3].}) 10. exf5 {The third rule of thumb is again on display.} Bxf5 ({After} 10... gxf5 11. Bg5 {is an improved version of the idea to push [f4]. White first simplifies the position by exchanging two pairs of light pieces on [f6] and then fixes the [f5]-pawn by pushing [f4]. With less material on the board, Black has fewer chances to seek dynamic counterchances to compensate for the static weakness on [f5].}) 11. h3 {[%csl Gg4][%cal Gh3g4,Gg3g4] Covering the [g4]-square is always useful for White. It allows for [Be3], not fearing ...[Ng4], but also for a kingside expansion with [g4].} ({The move} 11. d4 $6 {is premature in view of} Nxd5 12. Bxd5+ Kh8 {and there is too much pressure on the [d4]-pawn.}) 11... Qd7 {[%cal Gd7h3]} 12. Kh2 {[%csl Gh3][%cal Gh2h3,Gg2h3] White defends the [h3]-pawn and keeps the kingside compact.} Rae8 13. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] White finished development and has a pleasant position. 💡We will continue with: 🔹the central advance with [d4] – the idea indicated in the third rule of thumb; 🔹the possible exchanges on [d4] lead to a positionally favorable transformation with White's three pawns on the queenside holding Black's for pawns, thanks to the control of the [d5]-square.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
