[White "6) The Botvinnik Setup vs. ...g6 Systems"]
[Black "Botvinnik: 4...Nf6 with 6...e5"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A24"]
[PlyCount "31"]
[GameId "2102815304785463"]

1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... Nf6 ({This is the standard KID development, but after the move} 4... e5 {, we will explore the lines where Black develops the king's knight to [e7] or plays ...[f5] first before developing the knight to [f6].}) ({Black can also try a plan akin to the Closed Sicilian with} 4... c5 5. Nge2 Nc6 6. Bg2 e6 7. d3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Rb1 b6 10. a3 Bb7 11. b4 {, when White expands on the queenside and plans to advance further with the b-pawn and a4-a5. If Black jumps ...Nd4, after the exchange of knights and with a black pawn landing on d4, the white knight will go to a2 and b4, targeting the c6 and d5-squares on the queenside.}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nge2 {White plays the usual moves, but now Black needs to make a major decision. There are two options: to play ...[e5], with KID-style positions, or ...[c5], which is more in the style of the English Defense 1...b6 .} e5 {This move is the KID approach. Via this move order, we will analyze the positions where Black doesn't put the knight on [c6]. We analyzed these positions via the move order 4...e5 5.Bg2 Nc6 6.Nge2 Nf6 7.d3 O-O 8.O-O here.} 7. O-O c6 {[%csl Bb5,Bd5][%cal Gc6d5,Gc6b5] This is Black's main alternative to putting the knight on [c6]. The pawn controls the [d5] and [b5] squares and this prevents White's standard [Nd5]. The control of the [d5] and [b5] squares allows Black to play in the center, by preparing the ...[d5] push and on the queenside, by preparing the ...[b5] push.} ({The plan to exchange the light-squared bishops with} 7... Be6 8. d3 Qd7 {is slow and allows White to expand on the queenside unhindered with} 9. b4 Bh3 10. a4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 {and White continues to push [a5], [Rb1], [b5] while Black has achieved nothing on the kingside.}) 8. d3 a6 {[%cal Rb7b5] Black prepares ...[b5]. There are several other options that Black can try.} ({It is no longer possible to exchange the light-squared bishops with} 8... Be6 9. h3 Qd7 {because White has} 10. Kh2 {and is ready to push either [f4] or [d4].} ({The move Nbd7 is a neutral move without a clear idea, so White simply advances on the queenside with} 10. b4 a5 11. b5 {Nc5 Rb1 and even though Black established a knight on [c5] his position lacks dynamism, while White simply plays [h3], [Be3] and [f4]-[f5] with an advantage on the whole board.}) ({An attempt to prepare ...d5 with Na6 h3 Nc7 is met by play in the center with} 10. d4 {and the knight on [c7] is out of place. Exchanging it after} exd4 11. Nxd4 Re8 12. Be3 {Ne6 Rc1 Nxd4 Bxd4 doesn't solve Black's problems as he remains passive. If Black doesn't take on [d4] White can follow up with [f4] and obtain a massive pawn center.} ({An attempt to establish a knight on c5 is slow, a5 h3 Na6} 12. Be3 {Nc5 f4 already threatens [fxe5] , while exf4 gxf4 with [Ng3] next gives White a tremendous center.}))) 9. h3 {[%csl Bg4][%cal Gh3g4,Gc1e3] White secures the [e3]-square for the bishop by controlling the [g4]-square, thus avoiding ...[Ng4].} b5 {[%cal Rb5b4,Rb5c4]} 10. a3 {[%csl Bb4,Bc4][%cal Rb5b4,Ga3b4,Gb2b3,Gb3c4] White stops ...[b4] and on the next move will stabilize the queenside with [b3]. In this way White controls Black's queenside activity.} Be6 {[%cal Re6c4,Rb5c4] This is a more active development of the bishop, as it targets the pawn on [c4].} ({Placing it on b7 is worse, for example} 10... Re8 11. b3 Nbd7 12. Be3 Bb7 13. b4 {and White slowly expands on the queenside. Indeed, without pressure on the c4-pawn White no longer needs the pawn to stay on b3 and can use it to gain space on the queenside.}) 11. b3 {[%csl Gc4][%cal Gb3c4,Gd3c4] The [c4]-pawn is well defended now.} Nbd7 ({Black cannot strike in the center with} 11... d5 $6 {because after} 12. exd5 cxd5 13. Bg5 $1 {White wins the [d5]-pawn thanks to the pin on the long light-squared diagonal.}) 12. Be3 {[%cal Gd1d2] With the center stable, White continues development.} Re8 13. Qd2 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5] White completed the development. If Black is passive the [f4]-[f5] advance will come quickly.} Rb8 {[%csl Yb3][%cal Rb5c4,Rb8b3,Rd7c5,Rc5b3] Black uses the b-file to create counterplay. The idea is to take ...[bxc4] and then after ...[Nc5] to target the [b3]-square.} 14. Rab1 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gb1b3,Gf2f4,Gf4f5] White still wants to play [f4]-[f5], possibly by inserting [cxb5] first.} bxc4 {[%cal Rb8b1] Black opens the b-file for counterplay.} ({Against} 14... Qc7 {an interesting move is} 15. Nd5 $5 {aiming to win the bishop pair after} cxd5 16. cxd5 {as the bishop on [e6] is trapped.}) (14... bxc4 {The other idea is to proceed with f4 after cxb5 axb5} 15. f4 exf4 16. Nxf4 {with active play in the center.}) 15. dxc4 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gd2d6] Taking with the [d3]-pawn opens the d-file and exposes the [d6]-pawn, but taking with the [b3]-pawn is entirely possible, too.} Qc7 {[%cal Gc7d6]} 16. Rb2 $5 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gf1b1,Gb1b3,Gc3a4,Ge2c3,Gc4c5,Be2c1,Bc1d3] The start of a curious regrouping. 💡White has more than one good way to arrange the pieces: 🔹for example 16.Rfc1 with the threat of [Nd5], or Rfd1; 🔹but the move [Rb2] is a flexible one. White intends to play [Rfb1] prophylactically defending the pawn on [b3]; and, 🔹then either [Na4] and [Nec3] with the idea of [c5] that is why the pawn on [b3] needs protection, since after [c5] it is attacked by both the rook on [b8] and the bishop on [e6] or [Nc1]-[d3] with the same idea.} *

