1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc4d5,Ge4d5]} ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2]} ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... Nf6 ({This is the standard KID development, but after the move} 4... e5 {, we will explore the lines where Black develops the king's knight to [e7] or plays ...[f5] first before developing the knight to [f6].}) ({Black can also try a plan akin to the Closed Sicilian with} 4... c5 5. Nge2 Nc6 6. Bg2 e6 7. d3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Rb1 b6 10. a3 Bb7 11. b4 {, when White expands on the queenside and plans to advance further with the b-pawn and a4-a5. If Black jumps ...Nd4, after the exchange of knights and with a black pawn landing on d4, the white knight will go to a2 and b4, targeting the c6 and d5-squares on the queenside.}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nge2 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge2d4] White plays the usual moves, but now Black needs to make a major decision. There are two options: 🔹to play ...[e5], with KID-style positions; or, 🔹...[c5], which is more in the style of the English Defense 1...b6 .} c5 {[%cal Rg7a1] By advancing the c-pawn Black doesn't block the long diagonal for the fianchettoed dark-squared bishop.} 7. O-O ({White has an interesting alternative in} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nde2 {, leading to a Maróczy bind type of position immediately.}) 7... Nc6 8. d3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd3d4,Gb2b4,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd1d2] White completed the natural moves. The ensuing play is guided by the following ideas: if possible, White wants to play [Be3] and [d4], establishing a Maróczy bind. This is usually favorable for White, though sometimes Black allows it and counterattacks the bind with the ...[b5] break. If the [d4] advance is not possible, White turns the attention to the flanks. On the queenside the desirable push is [b4], while on the kingside it is [f4]-[f5] with the exchange of the dark-squared bishops with [Be3], [Qd2] and [Bh6] and a subsequent attack by doubling of the rooks on the f-file and/or a pawn storm.} a6 {[%cal Rb7b5] Generally a useful move for Black as the ...[b5] break is one of Black's main sources of activity.} ({The maneuver} 8... Ne8 {with the idea [Nc7]-[e6]-[d4] is another typical idea for Black, but here it allows White to play on the kingside after} 9. Be3 {threatening [d4]} Nd4 10. Qd2 Nc7 11. Bh6 {and after [Bxg7] White will continue with [f4]-[f5] combined with a pawn storm on the kingside and/or doubling of the rooks on the f-file.}) 9. Rb1 $1 {[%csl Ya1][%cal Gb2b4,Rg7a1] A precise move. The rook is removed from the long diagonal and is ready to support the [b4] advance.} Rb8 {[%cal Rb7b5] Black prepares ...[b5].} ({The immediate} 9... b5 $2 {runs into} 10. e5 $1 {and White wins material thanks to the pin on the long diagonal, resulting in a double attack on both knights.}) 10. a4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga4b5,Gc4b5,Gc3b5] It's important to stop Black's counterplay. The weakening of the [b4]-square doesn't mean that White has given up on the idea to push [b4]. In fact, the rook on [b1] nicely prepares the push, particularly in cases where Black plays ...[Nd4] and abandons control of the [b4]-square.} Ne8 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Ge8c7,Gc7b5,Rb7b5,Gc7e6,Re6d4] This maneuver is typical for Black in these structures. Black sends the knight to [c7] to support the ...[b5] push or to [e6] and [d4], to establish total control of the [d4]-square.} 11. Be3 {[%cal Ge3d4,Ge2d4,Gd3d4] Without a knight on [f6] White doesn't need the move [h3] before placing a bishop on [e3] - there is no threat of ...[Ng4].} Nc7 {[%cal Rb7b5] Black continues with the plan.} ({In case of} 11... Nd4 {the rook on [b1] comes in handy as White plays} 12. b4 {, being the first to start play on the queenside. After} b6 13. bxc5 dxc5 14. a5 b5 15. Nd5 {White obtains pleasant initiative.}) 12. d4 {[%cal Gd4c5,Gd4d5] White achieved the central advance.} b6 {[%csl Bc5,Bd4][%cal Gb6c5,Gd6c5,Re7e5,Gc6d4,Re5d4] An important idea for Black. The pawn on [c5] is reinforced and Black plans to play ...[e5] and establish control of the [d4]-square. Exchanges on d4 don't solve all Black's problems, 12...cxd4 13.Nxd4 Nxd4 14.Bxd4 Bxd4 15.Qxd4 b5 16.cxb5 axb5 17.b3 and White obtains an outside passed pawn on the a-file. With a pair of light pieces exchanged, White's advantage is more difficult to challenge actively, so Black must be patient in defending.} 13. b3 {[%cal Gb3c4]} ({Black's idea is seen after the natural} 13. d5 Na5 {attacking the [c4]-pawn} 14. b3 b5 {with counterattack on the queenside. Therefore White defends the c4-pawn in advance.}) 13... e5 {[%csl Yd4,Yd5][%cal Rc5d4,Re5d4,Gc4d5,Ge4d5] Black attacks the [d4]-pawn and forces White to concede the control of that square. In exchange, White obtains total control of the [d5]-square.} 14. dxe5 ({This is better than} 14. d5 Nd4 {, when Black has a strong piece on the [d4]-square while the [d5]-square is occupied by a pawn.}) 14... dxe5 15. Qxd8 ({It's also possible to keep queens on board with the immediate} 15. Nd5 {.}) 15... Rxd8 16. Nd5 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gd5c7] White occupies the central square first.} Ne6 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Re6d4,Gc6d4] Black plans to do the same.} 17. f4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gf4f5,Gf5f6] The move that gives White some initiative. With the centralized knight, White is the first to start active play. The immediate threat is [f5]-[f6] while, in case of an exchange on [f4], White obtains pawns on [e4] and [f4] that control the central squares and can be set in motion, for example with [e5], opening the [h1]-[a8] diagonal for the fianchettoed bishop on [g2].} Ned4 18. Nxd4 $1 {Is an important exchange for White. Black obtains a protected passed pawn on [d4] after} exd4 ({Or} 18... cxd4 19. Bd2 {when Black's central pawn duo is already undermined by the [f4]-pawn and White also has a mobile queenside pawn majority.}) 19. Bd2 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Ge4e5,Gg2a8,Gh2h3,Gg3g4] The [d4]-pawn will not go much further, while White's 4 vs 3 on the kingside is mobile. 💡White can continue with: 🔹e5, which limits the bishop on [g7] and at the same time opens the long diagonal for the bishop on [g2]; but also with, 🔹h3, [g4] and advance on the kingside.} *

