1. c4 g6 {This chapter covers all possible move orders that lead to a King's Indian set-ups by Black. The opponent can also start with: 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...Nf6 2.Nc3 d6 3.e4 , or: ( 🔹1...d6 2.Nc3 g6 3.e4 and so on. ) )} 2. e4 ({White can also start with} 2. Nc3 {and follow up with 3.e4.}) 2... Bg7 {Again Black is flexible with the move orders, but they will all transpose to the lines that follow. For example:} (2... d6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. g3 {, or:}) (2... c5 3. Nc3 Bg7 4. Nge2 {with [g3], etc.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg1e2,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1] White's set-up is automatic. It consists of a kingside fianchetto, [Nge2], [d3] and [O-O].} d6 4. g3 ({It's also possible to start with} 4. Nge2 {and then after, for instance,} Nf6 {play} 5. g3 {followed by [Bg2].}) 4... Nf6 ({This is the standard KID development, but after the move} 4... e5 {, we will explore the lines where Black develops the king's knight to [e7] or plays ...[f5] first before developing the knight to [f6].}) ({Black can also try a plan akin to the Closed Sicilian with} 4... c5 5. Nge2 Nc6 6. Bg2 e6 7. d3 Nge7 8. O-O O-O 9. Rb1 b6 10. a3 Bb7 11. b4 {, when White expands on the queenside and plans to advance further with the b-pawn and a4-a5. If Black jumps ...Nd4, after the exchange of knights and with a black pawn landing on d4, the white knight will go to a2 and b4, targeting the c6 and d5-squares on the queenside.}) 5. Bg2 O-O 6. Nge2 {White plays the usual moves, but now Black needs to make a major decision. There are two options: 🔹to play ...[e5], with KID-style positions; or, 🔹...[c5], which is more in the style of the English Defense 1...b6 .} c5 {[%cal Rg7a1] By advancing the c-pawn Black doesn't block the long diagonal for the fianchettoed dark-squared bishop.} 7. O-O ({White has an interesting alternative in} 7. d4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 9. Nde2 {, leading to a Maróczy bind type of position immediately.}) 7... Nc6 8. d3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd3d4,Gb2b4,Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd1d2] White completed the natural moves. 💡The ensuing play is guided by the following ideas: 🔹if possible, White wants to play [Be3] and [d4], establishing a Maróczy bind. This is usually favorable for White, though sometimes Black allows it and counterattacks the bind with the ...[b5] break. 🔹If the [d4] advance is not possible, White turns the attention to the flanks: • on the queenside, the desirable push is [b4]; while, • on the kingside, it is [f4]-[f5] with the exchange of the dark-squared bishops with [Be3], [Qd2] and [Bh6] and a subsequent attack by doubling of the rooks on the f-file and/or a pawn storm.} a6 {[%cal Rb7b5] Generally a useful move for Black as the ...[b5] break is one of Black's main sources of activity.} ({The maneuver} 8... Ne8 {with the idea [Nc7]-[e6]-[d4] is another typical idea for Black, but here it allows White to play on the kingside after} 9. Be3 {threatening [d4]} Nd4 10. Qd2 Nc7 11. Bh6 {and after [Bxg7], White will continue with [f4]-[f5] combined with a pawn storm on the kingside and/or doubling of the rooks on the f-file.}) 9. Rb1 $1 {[%csl Ya1][%cal Gb2b4,Rg7a1] A precise move. The rook is removed from the long diagonal and is ready to support the [b4] advance.} Rb8 {[%cal Rb7b5] Black prepares ...[b5].} ({The immediate} 9... b5 $2 {runs into} 10. e5 $1 {and White wins material thanks to the pin on the long diagonal, resulting in a double attack on both knights.}) 10. a4 {[%csl Bb5][%cal Ga4b5,Gc4b5,Gc3b5] It's important to stop Black's counterplay. The weakening of the [b4]-square doesn't mean that White has given up on the idea to push [b4]. In fact, the rook on [b1] nicely prepares the push, particularly in cases where Black plays ...[Nd4] and abandons control of the [b4]-square.} Bg4 $1 {[%cal Rg4d1] This subtle move is Black's best. It aims to provoke [f3] before developing the bishop to [d7]. The pawn on [f3] limits the activity of the bishop on [g2] and weakens the white king as it opens the [g1]-[a7] diagonal.} ({To compare with the main line, after} 10... Bd7 11. h3 Ne8 12. Be3 Nc7 13. d4 cxd4 14. Nxd4 b5 15. cxb5 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 axb5 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 18. b3 {, with the bishop on [g2] not being limited by the [f3]-pawn, White can play [Nd5] at some point and have the [d5]-pawn after an exchange on [d5] safely guarded. Additionally, White's king is safer with a pawn on [f2].}) ({Another move for Black is} 10... Nd4 11. Bd2 {preparing [b4], which immediately isn't good as after the exchange on [b4] Black has the annoying move [Qa5].}) 11. f3 {[%cal Gf3g4] White must chase away the bishop and prevent it from taking on [e2].} ({It cannot be done with} 11. h3 $6 {as after} Bxe2 12. Qxe2 Nd4 13. Qd1 b5 {Black has the initiative on the queenside.}) 11... Bd7 12. Be3 {[%cal Gd3d4] White now continues along the familiar lines. The threat is [d4].} Ne8 {[%cal Ge8c7] Black also plays along the usual lines. The knight goes to [c7].} ({An alternative is to lock in the center with} 12... e5 {, though after} 13. Kh1 {preparing [f4] by freeing the [g1]-square for the bishop in case of [Ng4]} Nd4 {, the best for White is to retreat the bishop:} ({𓈓14. Bd2!} 13... b5 14. cxb5 axb5 15. Nd4 cxd4 16. Nxb5 {. And after Black regains the pawn by taking on [b5], White will emerge with a passed b-pawn and a pair of bishops. The light-squared bishop can be activated via [h3].}) ({𓈓14. f4} 13... b5 {and Black is faster, by retreating the bishop White prepares to take on [d4].})) 13. b3 $1 {[%csl Ga4][%cal Gb3a4] An important preparatory move.} ({The immediate} 13. d4 $6 {shows a potential danger for White after} cxd4 14. Nxd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 b5 16. cxb5 axb5 17. b3 bxa4 18. Bxg7 Nxg7 {the knight was very useful on [e8], so it can recapture on [g7], thus preventing the check [Qd4] after the king's recapture on [g7], though the knight usefulness on [e8] is also seen in case of the king's recapture because then the check [Qd4] can be met by [e5] and the knight defends the [d6]-pawn} 19. bxa4 Qa5 {and suddenly White's passed a-pawn is under attack and will likely be lost.}) 13... Nc7 {With the knight on [c7], White can proceed with the plan of [d4].} ({Stopping d4 with} 13... Nd4 {allows} 14. b4 cxb4 15. Rxb4 Qa5 16. Na2 {and the knight on [d4] is hanging, while the exchange of the [c5]-pawn for the b-pawn gave White a pawn advantage in the center and the semi-open b-file.}) 14. d4 {[%cal Gd4c5,Gd4d5] White executes the central advance now.} cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nxd4 {Black exchanges in the center so that he can push ...[b5].} ({It's possible to invert the move order with} 15... b5 16. cxb5 Nxd4 {.}) 16. Bxd4 Bxd4+ {If Black doesn't take on [d4] White will take on [g7] and give the check [Qd4], thus leading to the same position.} 17. Qxd4 b5 {[%cal Rb5a4,Rb5c4]} 18. cxb5 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Ga4a8] White takes with the c-pawn in order to keep the a-pawn on the board, thus obtaining an outside passed pawn.} axb5 19. f4 {[%csl Ba4][%cal Gg2a8,Ge4e5,Gf4f5,Ga4a8] White needs to spend tempo to push the f-pawn in order to activate the fianchettoed bishop. The [f4]-pawn allows for the opening of the long diagonal with [e5], but it can also serve to create threats on the kingside with [f5]. 💡The position is objectively balanced, but: 🔹White's outside passed pawn and the space advantage; 🔹coupled with the ideas to push [e5] or [f5]... ... provide some guidelines on how to continue from here.} *

[Event "1.c4: Simplified"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction: The Dutch 1…f5"]
[Black "Introduction: The Dutch"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A10"]
[PlyCount "9"]
[GameId "2102815304855098"]

1. c4 f5 {The Dutch has three sub-systems that comprise the whole Dutch complex: 🔹the Leningrad, which sees the fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop; 🔹the Stonewall, where the pawns are placed on [e6], [d5] and [c6]; and, 🔹the Classical, where after ...[e6] Black decides whether to develop the dark-squared bishop to [e7] or to [b4].} 2. Nc3 {This move is the usual one.} Nf6 {Black still keeps all options open.} 3. Nf3 {With the Botvinnik System as our weapon of choice against the KID, it was natural to propose it against the Dutch as well.} ({However, there is one particular line that the Leningrad Dutch players choose when the Botvinnik System is played against them. It arises after} 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. e4 fxe4 $1 7. dxe4 c5 $1 {with ...[Nc6] next, often followed by ...[e5] and ...[Nd4]. This line is quite a good one for Black and I preferred to avoid it.}) ({Therefore, I chose a simple set-up against the Dutch starting with} 3. Nf3 {.}) 3... e6 {[%cal Rd7d5,Rf8b4]} (3... g6 {: against the Leningrad White develops in reversed Sicilian fashion with the only difference that when Black threatens ...[e5] White stops it by playing [d4]:} 4. e3 Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. d4 {, with the straightforward plan of queenside advance [b4], [a4], etc. This is a very simple plan for White that doesn't require much memorization to play.}) 4. d3 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge2e4] Anticipating ...[Bb4] and preparing [e4].} Bb4 ({The proposed move order effectively neutralizes the Stonewall after} 4... d5 {, because without a white pawn on [d4] White obtains an impregnable position after} 5. cxd5 exd5 6. g3 {followed by [Bg2], [O-O], [e3] when Black cannot approach White's position thanks to the wall of pawns on [e3] and [d3]. White's plan is very simple, to advance on the queenside. The model game Kasparov-Short, the Rapid one held in Paris, perfectly illustrates the desperation Black experiences when playing against this set-up.}) 5. Bd2 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gf1e2,Gd2c3,Gc3h8] followed by [e3] and [Be2] in reversed Sicilian style. Later on, White will concentrate on prophylactic measures on the kingside by pushing [f4] and opening the long diagonal for the dark-squared bishop, which will come to [c3] and after the exchange ...[Bxc3], [Bxc3].} *

