[White "7) The Dutch 1…f5"]
[Black "Dutch: 3...g6"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A85"]
[PlyCount "25"]
[GameId "2102815304867387"]

1. c4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 ({After} 2... e5 3. d4 {, we have a transposition to the chapter The Reversed Sicilian 1…e5, the line analyzed after 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 f5 3.d4 , mentioned as a clickable in the comments to Black's 2nd move.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf3e5] White stops the immediate ...[e5]. In the Dutch, Black needs to choose which iteration of the opening to play: 🔹the Leningrad Dutch which has the dark-squared bishop fianchettoed on [g7]; 🔹the Stonewall which places the pawns on light squares on [e6], [d5] and [c6]; or, 🔹the Classical, which develops the dark-squared bishop on [e7] or [b4] and aims for the [e5] push. In this position, Black already has to make the choice.} g6 {[%cal Gf8g7,Ge8g8] The fianchetto is the defining feature of the Leningrad Dutch.} 4. e3 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Gd2d4,Gd4e5,Gf3e5] White develops in reversed Sicilian fashion, the only moment of importance coming when Black threatens to push ...[e5]. In that moment White will play [d4] to stop it.} Bg7 5. Be2 O-O 6. O-O d6 {[%cal Re7e5] The moment of importance. Black threatens ...[e5].} 7. d4 {[%csl Be5][%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5,Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5,Ga4a5,Gc1b2,Gb2a3] White stops ...[e5] and simply continues with a queenside advance.} a5 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ga5b4,Gb2b4] Black stops White's planned [b4]. Otherwise, White's play is very simple: take on e5 when Black plays it and advance on the queenside. For example:} (7... Qe8 8. b4 e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. b5 $1 {with [Ba3] to come with initiative as [Nd5] is also a threat;}) (7... c6 8. b4 Qe8 9. a4 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. a5 {with [Ba3], [b5], [a6] all becoming threats on the queenside;} ({Nc6 d5 Nb8} 11. Nd4 {with [b3] and [Bb2] to follow.}) ({e5 This pawn sacrifice dxe5 dxe5} 11. Nxe5 {should give Black some compensation, but it's rather vague, as White has no weaknesses in the position.})) 8. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Gc1a3] Since [b4] isn't possible, White plays [b3] in order to develop the bishop on [b2] or in some lines on [a3].} c6 {[%cal Gd8e8,Re7e5,Gb8a6,Gc8d7,Rb7b5] Black's typical moves in the Leningrad are [Na6]-[c7], [Bd7] and [Qe8], preparing both [e5] and [b5].} 9. Bb2 {[%csl Bb6,Bc5][%cal Gf1e1,Ge2f1,Ge3e4,Ge1e4,Ga1c1,Gc3a4,Ga4b6,Ga4c5,Gc4c5,Gd4d5,Gd4e5,Ge2d3] White completes development. In the ensuing play, the main ideas will be to take on [e5] when Black plays it, to prepare [e4] by [Re1] and [Bf1]/[Bd3], and to target Black's queenside weaknesses by moves like [Na4], [c5] or [d5].} Na6 {Standard development of the knight.} ({Putting a knight on e4 doesn't achieve much as White simply forces its exchange after} 9... Ne4 10. Qc2 {and the knight cannot stay on [e4].}) ({Black can start with} 9... Qe8 10. Rc1 {and now instead of a transposition with ...[Na6] he could try} e5 $6 {but that only exposes his position after} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. c5 $1 {intending [Na4] and fixing the [d6]-square.}) 10. Rc1 {[%cal Gc1c8,Gc4c5] The rook is useful on the c-file as often it supports the [c5]-advance.} Qe8 ({After} 10... Bd7 11. Re1 {White follows the same plan to prepare [e4] by [Bf1] or [Bd3].}) 11. Re1 {[%cal Ge2d3,Ge2f1,Ge3e4,Ge1e4] Planning [Bf1] or [Bd3] and [e4].} e5 {This is one of Black's main ideas in the Leningrad, but here it doesn't work.} ({After} 11... Bd7 12. Bf1 {, White prepares [e4].}) 12. dxe5 {White always takes on [e5].} dxe5 13. Na4 {[%csl Bb6,Bd6,Ye5][%cal Ga4b6,Gb6a8,Gb6c8,Gb2e5,Gf3e5,Gc4c5,Gc5d6,Gc5b6] With a double threat of [Nb6] and [Nxe5]. 💡The move [c5] is a positional threat that fixes Black's dark-square weaknesses on the queenside.} *

