1. c4 f5 2. Nc3 Nf6 ({After} 2... e5 3. d4 {, we have a transposition to the chapter The Reversed Sicilian 1…e5, the line analyzed after 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 f5 3.d4 , mentioned as a clickable in the comments to Black's 2nd move.}) 3. Nf3 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Gf3e5] White stops the immediate ...[e5]. In the Dutch, Black needs to choose which iteration of the opening to play: 🔹the Leningrad Dutch which has the dark-squared bishop fianchettoed on [g7]; 🔹the Stonewall which places the pawns on light squares on [e6], [d5] and [c6]; or, 🔹the Classical, which develops the dark-squared bishop on [e7] or [b4] and aims for the [e5] push. In this position, Black already has to make the choice.} e6 {This move indicates that Black will either play the Stonewall with ...[d5] next, or the Classical with ...[Be7] or ...[Bb4].} 4. d3 {[%cal Gc1d2,Ge2e3,Ge3e4] White anticipates ...[Bb4] so that it can be met by [Bd2], while preparing a possible [e4] in the center.} d5 {[%cal Gd5c4,Gd5d4] The Stonewall is a major option for Black, but it is not recommended when White doesn't have a pawn on [d4].} 5. cxd5 {White must take as the threats of ...[dxc4] or ...[d4] were serious.} exd5 6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Ge2e3,Ge1g1] White will fianchetto the bishop and play [e3], keeping the [d4]-square vacant. It will come in handy for the knight maneuvers in the center. With pawns on [e3], [d3] and [g3], White's position is extremely solid and renders Black without any counterplay. This is the reason why the Stonewall is not a great option for Black without a pawn on [d4] – he doesn't have the [e4]-square at his disposal, thus lacking any active play.} c6 {The Stonewall formation. If Black develops a knight on [c6] it doesn't affect White in the least. See the model game Kasparov-Short played in Paris for an excellent example of how to exploit the advantages of White's position.} ({Note that the tempting} 6... d4 $6 {is not good because of} 7. Qa4+ Nc6 8. Nb5 Bc5 9. Bg2 {with [O-O], [Bf4] and [Rc1] and coming up when Black can hardly sustain his center.}) 7. Bg2 Be7 ({Black should be careful, as the development of the bishop on d6 allows a quick e4 by White. Indeed, after} 7... Bd6 8. O-O O-O 9. e4 $1 {with a big advantage as Black's center crumbles. After ...[dxe4] White will have the idea of [Qb3] and [Ng5] to regain the pawn on [e4].} ({Again} 9. d4 $6 {isn't very good as after Nb1 followed by [O-O], [Qa4], [Nbd2] White will attack the advanced [d4]-pawn and Black's queenside in general.})) 8. O-O O-O 9. e3 {[%csl Gd3,Ge3,Gg3][%cal Gd3c4,Gd3e4,Ge3d4,Ge3f4,Gg3f4] Setting up the central barrier that keeps Black's pieces at bay.} Nbd7 10. b3 {[%cal Gc1b2,Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Gc3e2,Ge2d4,Ge2f4,Gf3d4] 💡White will finish development with [Bb2] and the general plan will be to: 🔹advance on the queenside with [a3] and [b4]; 🔹while at the same time using the [d4] and [f4] squares for the knights to increase the impact of that advance. Please see the model game Kasparov-Short to see how the World Champion uses these advantages to suffocate his opponent.} *

