1. c4 b6 {The English Defense against the English Opening is not a very bad idea.} 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} ({White continues in the usual way, preparing e4, even though the immediate} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {should transpose.}) 2... Bb7 3. e4 {White takes over the center. Now, Black usually goes for the Hedgehog formation.} e6 {[%cal Rc7c5,Rf8b4]} ({The move} 3... e5 {is an alternative. White obtains good play after} 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 {stopping [Bb4]} Nf6 6. d3 {followed by [g2], [Bg2], [O-O] when the main plan is to execute [f4] with an attack on the kingside. In this central structure of pawns on [c3], [d3] and [e4] Black's bishop on [b7] is hopelessly out of play.}) 4. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1]} ({After} 4. d4 Bb4 {, Black obtains play typical for the English Defense. Therefore, White plays [Nge2], in line with the Botvinnik System, with [g3], [Bg2] and [O-O] to follow, keeping the game at a slower pace. This will allow White to decide how to continue later on.}) 4... Nf6 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White starts with [d3] because Black can also play in the center with ...[d5]. Therefore, White keeps the long diagonal closed.} c5 {Black doesn't really have much of a choice.} ({Play in the center backfires after} 5... d5 $6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. d4 c5 9. f4 {and White established a solid pawn center.}) 6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] White continues along the lines of the Botvinnik development.} d5 {[%cal Rd5e4,Rd5c4] This is an attempt to play in the center.} 7. exd5 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] White takes with the e-pawn in order to open the long diagonal.} exd5 8. Bg2 {[%csl Yb7,Yd5][%cal Gg2b7,Ge2f4,Gc4d5,Gf4d5,Gc3d5] Now Black faces certain problems given the undefended bishop on [b7]. White would like to continue with [Nf4] and win the pawn on [d5].} Qd7 {[%cal Gd7b7,Gd5c4,Gd5d4] Black defends the bishop on [b7] and wants to release the tension in the center either by ...[dxc4] or ...[d4].} 9. Nf4 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gc4d5,Gc3d5,Gf4d5,Gg2d5] White now obtains control of the central [d5]-square.} dxc4 {[%cal Rb7g2,Rc4d3]} 10. Bxb7 {A forced exchange.} Qxb7 {[%cal Rb7h1]} 11. O-O {[%cal Gf1e1,Ge1e8] White develops fast and Black doesn't have time to pick up pawns.} Nc6 ({Taking on d3 is dangerous,} 11... cxd3 $6 12. Re1+ Be7 13. Nfd5 $1 Nxd5 14. Qf3 {and with [Nxd5] next White has a decisive attack.}) ({Less precise than the main move is} 11... Be7 12. Nfd5 $1 Nxd5 13. Qf3 Nc6 14. Nxd5 O-O-O 15. dxc4 {when the dominating knight and the unsafe position of the black king give White the more promising chances.}) 12. Re1+ {[%cal Ge1e8]} Be7 13. dxc4 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Gc3d5,Gf4d5,Gc4d5] White obtained control of the [d5]-square. After} O-O 14. Nfd5 {[%csl Bd4,Bd5][%cal Gc1e3,Ge3d4] The difference between the strong outposts on [d5] and [d4] is that White can control the [d4]-square with the bishop while Black cannot do the same. 💡This means that the scenario of White ending up with a dominating knight on [d5] versus a passive black-squared bishop is likely, giving White better long-term prospects.} *

