1. c4 b6 {The English Defense against the English Opening is not a very bad idea.} 2. Nc3 {[%cal Ge2e4]} ({White continues in the usual way, preparing e4, even though the immediate} 2. e4 Bb7 3. Nc3 {should transpose.}) 2... Bb7 3. e4 {White takes over the center. Now, Black usually goes for the Hedgehog formation.} e6 {[%cal Rc7c5,Rf8b4]} ({The move} 3... e5 {is an alternative. White obtains good play after} 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 {stopping [Bb4]} Nf6 6. d3 {followed by [g2], [Bg2], [O-O] when the main plan is to execute [f4] with an attack on the kingside. In this central structure of pawns on [c3], [d3] and [e4] Black's bishop on [b7] is hopelessly out of play.}) 4. Nge2 {[%cal Gd2d3,Gg2g3,Gf1g2,Ge1g1]} ({After} 4. d4 Bb4 {, Black obtains play typical for the English Defense. Therefore, White plays [Nge2], in line with the Botvinnik System, with [g3], [Bg2] and [O-O] to follow, keeping the game at a slower pace. This will allow White to decide how to continue later on.}) 4... Nf6 5. d3 {[%cal Gd3e4] White starts with [d3] because Black can also play in the center with ...[d5]. Therefore, White keeps the long diagonal closed.} c5 {Black doesn't really have much of a choice.} ({Play in the center backfires after} 5... d5 $6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e5 Nfd7 8. d4 c5 9. f4 {and White established a solid pawn center.}) 6. g3 {[%cal Gf1g2,Gg2a8] White continues along the lines of the Botvinnik development.} d6 {The 🦔 formation is the more solid choice.} 7. Bg2 {[%cal Ge4e5,Gg2b7] Now both sides develop as things are calm in the center, but there is one trick in the position based on the double attack after [e5] that White needs to know.} Be7 ({The fianchetto of the dark-squared bishop is dubious, after} 7... g6 8. O-O Nbd7 {8...Bg7?? 9.e5 loses a piece 9.f4 Qc7 Black must defend the bishop on [b7] before developing the other bishop on [g7] because of the [e5] trick 10.d4 cxd4 11.Nxd4 a6 12.Be3 and now Black has to abandon the idea of the fianchetto as 12...Bg7? runs into 13.Ndb5! , exposing the weakness of the [d6]-pawn and the long diagonal after [Nxd6xb7] and [e5].}) 8. O-O Nc6 ({Developing on d7 is a blunder,} 8... Nbd7 $4 9. e5 {wins material. This trick must always be kept in mind when the bishop on [b7] is not protected. The same trick works against moves like:} ({a6?} 9. e5 $1 {, and: O-O? e5! .})) 9. d4 {Going for the Hedgehog formation.} ({An alternative is to play on the kingside with} 9. h3 O-O 10. Be3 a6 11. f4 {with [g4] and [Ng3] to come, though the attack will need some time to have an effect.}) 9... cxd4 10. Nxd4 {[%csl Yb6,Bc4,Yd6,Be4,Ye6] The bind by the pawns on [c4] and [e4] gives White a stable space advantage, while Black is well-developed and entrenched behind the Hedgehog formation of pawns along the 6th rank.} Nxd4 {If Black doesn't exchange the knights White will play the same: [b3] and [Ba3].} 11. Qxd4 O-O 12. b3 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gc1a3,Ga3d6,Gd4d6,Gf1d1,Gd1d6] A straight-forward plan. White places the bishop on [a3] and piles up on the d-file after [Rfd1], thus targeting the [d6]-pawn.} Qc7 13. Ba3 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Ga3f8] The bishop is active on the [a3]-[f8] diagonal.} a6 14. Rfd1 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Ga3d6,Gd1d6] Now the pawn on [d6] is hanging, so Black must defend it.} Rfd8 15. Bb4 {[%csl Yb6][%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Ga5b6] 💡This move introduces another idea for White in the position: 🔹that of the advance of the a-pawn to [a5]. The aim is to exchange White's a-pawn for Black's [b6]-pawn, thus weakening Black's structure. 🔹The opening of the a-file will also expose the pawn on [a6] and will give White access to the [a5]-square. Black is solid in the Hedgehog, but White has the more active possibilities.} *

