1. c4 d5 {The Anglo-Scandinavian. Not the best of lines.} 2. cxd5 {The most natural continuation. White exchanges a c-pawn for a d-pawn, obtaining a pawn advantage in the centre.} Qxd5 ({If Black sacrifices a pawn with} 2... c6 {, then after} 3. dxc6 Nxc6 4. Nc3 {with [Nf3], [d3], [e3], [Be2] and [O-O] White will obtain a weakness-free position with an extra pawn.}) 3. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5] Developing with tempo.} Qa5 {The queen can retreat to [d6] or [d8], like in the Scandinavian, but here White has an e-pawn instead of a c-pawn and it makes a huge difference as it allows a full central control after [d4] and [e4].} 4. d4 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gg1f3] Intending [e4], [Nf3] with a powerful development and centre.} e5 {[%cal Re5d4] Direct play in the center.} ({After} 4... Nf6 5. Nf3 {defends the pawn on [d4] in advance and White continues with [Bd2] next, planning [e4].}) 5. dxe5 {White lures the queen to [e5] in order to gain further time for development with [Nf3].} Qxe5 ({After} 5... Nc6 6. e4 {is the simplest, gaining space in the center and continuing development with [Bd2], [Nf3] or [f4] if Black doesn't capture on [e5].}) 6. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3e5] Developing with tempo.} Qd6 7. Qc2 {[%cal Ge2e4,Gc1e3,Ga1d1] White avoids the exchange of queens as the black queen can further be harassed after [e4], [Be3] and [Rd1]. White has an obvious development advantage as Black has lost serious time by moving the queen four times in the first six moves.} *

