1. c4 d5 {The Anglo-Scandinavian. Not the cream of the crop in terms of theory.} 2. cxd5 {The most natural continuation. White exchanges a c-pawn for a d-pawn, obtaining a pawn advantage in the center.} Nf6 {[%cal Rc7c6] Black wants to sacrifice a pawn by continuing with ...[c6] next in case White defends the pawn on [d5] by [e4].} 3. d4 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ge2e4] Since White has an extra pawn in the center White takes over the center.} ({After} 3. e4 {: 𓈓3... c6 dxc6 Nxc6 d3 , Black has some compensation in a reversed Morra Gambit position. 𓈓3... Nxe4?? Qa4 wins the knight on [e4]}) 3... c6 ({In case of} 3... Nxd5 4. Nf3 {followed by [e4] White has excellent play with a full pawn center.}) 4. dxc6 {White accepts the pawn sacrifice.} Nxc6 {[%cal Rc6d4,Rd8d4]} 5. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gd1d4] White develops and defends the pawn on [d4].} e5 {Black's only try to create some counterplay, otherwise it's just a sad position a pawn down.} 6. dxe5 {White doesn't mind the queen exchange as that leads to an endgame with an extra pawn.} Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 Ng4 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Rg4e5,Rc6e5,Rg4f2]} 8. Ke1 {Defending against the fork on [f2]. Black will regain one pawn, the one on [e5], but White will still be a pawn-up. 💡The development plan is [Nc3], [e3], [Bd2], [Be2]/[d3]/[c4]/[b5], [Ke2].} *

