1. c4 Nc6 {Is another rare attempt, but more often than not it will transpose to other lines. After White's standard move:} 2. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3d5,Gc4d5] White controls the [d5]-square and Black will most likely have to transpose to the other lines analized in the course.} e6 {This is somewhat independent, but not that great. Other moves transpose. For example:} (2... e5 {transposes to the Reversed Sicilian after} 3. Nf3 {via 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Nf3 . 2...Nf6 3.e4 e5 4.Nf3 is another transposition to the Reversed Sicilian via 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 Nf6 3.Nf3 Nc6 4.e4 . 2...d6 3.Nf3 e5 4.d4 transposes to the Reversed Sicilian via 1.c4 e5 2.Nc3 Nc6 3.Nf3 d6 4.d4 , mentioned as a clickable to Black's 3rd move.}) 3. e3 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2,Gg1f3]} ({White has many good options, like} 3. d4 {, 3.Nf3 or 3.g3 , but playing along the lines of the system against the Queen's Gambit Declined with [e3] and [b3] is probably the simplest, in analogy with the chapter the QGD Systems.}) 3... d5 ({After} 3... Bb4 4. Qc2 {, White can continue with [Nf3], [Bb2] etc.}) 4. Nf3 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gc1b2] White plays the same as against the QGD systems. Now with a knight on [c6] Black can try} d4 {But after the exchanges on [d4] White will push [d4] and obtain space advantage in the centre.} 5. exd4 Nxd4 6. Nxd4 Qxd4 7. d3 {[%cal Gc1e3,Gd3d4] With the idea [Be3] and [d4].} *

