{🏆Grenke Chess Classic Baden-Baden / Karlsruhe, Round April White: Elo – Black: Elo. Note from Chessable: GM Alex Colovic was inspired by this Sicilian game played by Magnus Carlsen to concoct this course's lines against the Reversed Sicilian for you. To study Magnus' strategy from the point of view of the former World Champion, please 🔂 flip the board.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 e5 {Now we have our English structure on the board, only with colors reversed.} 4. Bc4 Be7 5. d3 d6 6. Nd2 {[%csl Bd5][%cal Rd2f1,Rf1e3,Re3d5,Rc3d5,Rc4d5] White plans [Nf1]-[e3] to control the [d5]-square.} Nf6 7. Nf1 Nd7 $5 {[%csl Yc4][%cal Gd7b6,Ge8g8,Gb6c4,Gf7f5] Here is Carlsen's idea that White implements in the theoretical section. The knight aims for [b6] to harass the bishop on [c4] while at the same time opening the path for the f-pawn.} 8. Nd5 {White uses the fact that Black doesn't control the [d5]-square and hops there immediately. This move is connected with the idea to exchange the black knight once it appears on [b6] in order to keep the bishop on [c4].} Nb6 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gb6c4] Black continues with his plan.} 9. Nxb6 {White exchanges knights and keeps the bishop on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} axb6 {[%cal Ge7g5] Black recaptures with a pawn in order to keep the queen on [d8] and have the idea of ...[Bg5] at his disposal. In this pawn structure Black's dark-squared bishop is quite limited, so Black wouldn't mind exchanging it.} 10. c3 {[%csl Bb4,Bd4][%cal Gc3d4,Gc3b4] Taking control of the central [d4]-square, thus limiting the mobility of the black knight.} O-O 11. Ne3 Bg5 {[%cal Gg5c1] Black activates the dark-squared bishop, an important idea in this pawn structure. White won't be able to avoid the exchange of the bishops.} 12. O-O Kh8 $5 {[%cal Gf7f5] An ambitious choice, introducing the idea of ...[f5] by removing the king from the [a2]-[g8] diagonal. Black could have equalized easily by taking on [e3], followed by ...[Qe7] and ...[Be6], thus neutralizing the strong bishop on [c4].} 13. a3 {[%cal Gc4a2] Opening a safe spot for the bishop on [a2], but soon we will see a surprising transformation: the magnificent bishop will turn out to be a useless piece looking down an empty diagonal.} f5 $1 {Carlsen follows his plan.} 14. Nxf5 Bxc1 15. Rxc1 Bxf5 16. exf5 d5 {[%csl Bd5,Be5][%cal Gf8f5] This was Black's idea. He obtains a strong center and will recapture the pawn on [f5] next.} 17. Ba2 {[%cal Ra2d5] Svidler keeps the bishop on the [a2]-[g8] diagonal and hopes to pin Black down to the defense of the [d5]-pawn.} Rxf5 18. Qg4 {[%cal Rg4f5]} Rf6 {[%cal Gd8d6,Ga8f8,Gf8f1]} 19. f4 {White wants to exchange his f-pawn and open the f-file in order to avoid Black's doubling or tripling of his heavy pieces on it.} exf4 20. Qg5 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Rg5d5,Ra2d5,Rf1f4]} ({A necessary intermediate move, since the immediate capture} 20. Rxf4 $2 Ne5 21. Qg3 Rxf4 22. Qxf4 Nxd3 {wins the exchange.}) 20... Qf8 $1 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf8f4] The moment where the game turns in Black's favor. Carlsen correctly evaluates that the loss of the [d5]-pawn and the opening of the [a2]-[g8] diagonal for the bishop are less valuable than keeping the [f4]-pawn alive. Keeping the [f4]-pawn is will give Black attacking chances, while the bishop will only be a useless bystander doing nothing on the empty [a2]-[g8] diagonal.} 21. Qxd5 Rd8 {[%cal Gd8d3] Activating the other rook with tempo.} 22. Qf3 {[%cal Gf3d3] White defends the [d3]-pawn.} Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3,Ge5f3] Black invites everyone to the party!} 23. Qe4 {[%cal Re4e5]} ({Taking on b7 allows} 23. Qxb7 f3 {with a strong attack.}) 23... Ng4 $1 {[%csl Be3][%cal Gg4e3] Landing a knight on a protected square on the third rank is stronger than taking the pawn on [d3].} 24. Rce1 Ne3 {[%csl Ba2,Be3][%cal Ge3g2,Ge3f1] Just compare the light pieces – the knight on [e3] and the bishop on [a2], and it's clear that Black is practically playing with a piece up!} 25. Rf2 Re8 26. Qxb7 g5 $1 {[%cal Gg5g4,Gg4g3,Gf4f3] The march of the g-pawn will decide the attack. Observe how hopeless White is to prevent it.} 27. Rfe2 g4 28. Rf2 Qh6 $1 {[%csl Yh2][%cal Gg4g3,Gh6h2,Gg3h2] Threatening ...[g3].} 29. Qc7 {[%cal Rc7g3] White defends against ...[g3] by controlling that square with the queen.} Ref8 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gf8f4,Gg4g3] Black reinforces the presence on the f-file. The final breakthrough is near.} 30. h3 {This allows a pretty finish.} gxh3 31. g3 fxg3 32. Rxf6 h2+ $1 33. Kh1 g2# {An impressive attack by Carlsen. 💡But the real mastery was the understanding that: 🔹the loss of the central [d5]-pawn would leave White with a pretty, but useless bishop; while, 🔹the [f4]-pawn and the knight could generate the winning attack on the dark squares.} *

