{🏆86th Tata Steel Masters, Wijk aan Zee, Round January White: Elo – Black: Elo.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 e6 4. Bb2 Bd6 5. c4 O-O 6. Nc3 c5 7. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5]} ({A sharp alternative to the more positional move} 7. cxd5 {analyzed in the theoretical section.}) 7... Nc6 {[%cal Rd5d4,Rc6d4]} ({Black develops, as taking the pawn is dangerous after} 7... Nxg4 8. Rg1 {.}) 8. g5 {[%cal Gg5f6]} Ne4 {A natural move, centralizing the knight.} 9. h4 {White just pushes the pawns forward.} Re8 $2 {A mistake, but it's hard to envision why this would be a bad move.} ({Moves like} 9... f5 {or 9...b6 were better suited to the needs of the black position. As it turns out, the rook is worse on [e8] than on [f8], as from [f8] it can support the ...[f5] push.}) 10. Qc2 {[%cal Gc2e4,Gc3e4,Ge1c1] White continues with standard development and attacks the knight on [e4].} Nxc3 ({Black cannot keep the knight on e4 as after} 10... f5 11. gxf6 Nxf6 12. Ng5 {, the attack is very strong.}) ({A move like} 10... Nb4 {is simply met by} 11. Qb1 {and all the threats remain.}) 11. dxc3 $1 {[%csl Bd4][%cal Gc3d4,Ge3d4] This is how White usually recaptures on [c3] in these lines. It may appear illogical to shut the bishop on [b2], but the pawns on [c3] and [e3] prevent Black's idea of ...[d4], which would have shut the bishop anyway.} g6 ({Now} 11... d4 {lacks punch and White simply plays} 12. Bd3 g6 13. h5 {with a decisive attack.}) 12. h5 {[%cal Gh5g6,Gc2g6,Gf1d3,Gd3g6] Possible, but it was stronger to castle. The attack won't run away and there is little Black can do against [Bd3], [h5] etc.} Ne5 {[%csl Bd3][%cal Re5d3] The only move to stay in the game. The knight prevents the white bishop from coming to [d3], while in case of the exchange the dark-squared bishop controls the long diagonal and protects the black king.} 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {[%cal Re5a1,Ge5h8]} 14. O-O-O Bg7 15. f4 $6 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gh5g6,Gc2g6] White is still much better, but the attack is not decisive anymore.} ({A better alternative was the move} 15. Bd3 {.}) 15... e5 {[%cal Gc8f5,Rf5c2] Black opens the center and activates the bishop on [c8], but sacrifices the pawn on [d5] in the process.} 16. hxg6 $6 ({It was better to take the pawn with} 16. cxd5 exf4 17. exf4 Qd6 18. Qf2 {with an unclear position, but at least White is a pawn up.}) 16... hxg6 17. Bd3 $6 {[%csl Yg6][%cal Gc2g6] After this, Black takes over the initiative. White hopes for some sacrifices on [g6], but they don't work. Which doesn't mean they won't work in the future.} ({Better was} 17. Bh3 {, but Black was already fine by this point.}) 17... exf4 18. exf4 Qc7 $6 {[%cal Rc7f4]} ({It was better to play} 18... Bg4 19. Rdg1 dxc4 $1 {with active counterplay.}) 19. Rh4 {[%cal Gh4f4] This stops ...[Bg4] and defends the pawn on [f4].} dxc4 20. Bxg6 $1 {This isn't winning, but it's confusing enough and puts Black under pressure.} fxg6 21. Qxg6 {[%cal Gg6e8,Gg6h7] The position looks scary for Black, but objectively he should be able to hold.} Kf8 $6 ({Best was} 21... Qc6 22. Qh7+ Kf7 23. Rh6 Re6 {and Black defends.}) 22. f5 {[%csl Bf5,Bg5][%cal Gf5f6] It's still around equal, but the practical difficulties Black needs to solve are insurmountable in practice.} Qf7 23. Qd6+ Kg8 $6 {It was better to cover with the queen.} 24. f6 {[%cal Gf6g7]} Qg6 {[%cal Gg6d6]} ({Pinning the pawn on f6, but finally finishing development with} 24... Bf5 {was better.}) 25. Qf4 Qf5 $2 {[%cal Gc8f5]} ({Now it was the last moment for the saving} 25... Bf5 26. Qxc4+ Re6 {and Black is still in the game.}) 26. Qg3 Be6 ({The toughest resistance was the move} 26... Re5 {, but White has excellent winning chances after} 27. fxg7 Qxg5+ 28. Qxg5 Rxg5 29. Rxc4 {as the black king is too far from the queenside.}) 27. fxg7 Bf7 28. Rf4 {[%cal Gf4f7] Now White attacks with an extra pawn!} Qe6 29. Qh2 {[%cal Gh2h8]} Kxg7 30. Rxf7+ {An elegant finish.} Qxf7 31. g6 {[%cal Gh2h7,Gd1g1,Gg1g7]} Qe6 32. Rd7+ $1 {[%cal Gh2h7,Gh7d7,Ye6d7] After the rook is captured [Qh7] will win the black queen.} *

