{🏆Candidates Tournament, Moscow, Round March White: Elo – Black: Elo.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. b3 Be7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. Nc3 c5 7. cxd5 Nxd5 8. Qc2 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gc2h7,Gh2h4,Gf3g5,Ge1c1,Gf1d3,Gg5h7]} ({In the theoretical chapter, we look at} 8. Nxd5 {. By playing [Qc2] White prepares long castling and introduces attacking ideas on the kingside like [h4], [Ng5], [Bd3] etc.}) 8... Nc6 9. h4 {[%csl Yh7][%cal Gf3g5,Gg5h7,Gc2h7] An ambitious move, preparing the blunt threat of [Ng5].} ({Note that it's possible to treat the position in another way, for example by reverting to a Hedgehog with} 9. a3 {, followed by [Be2], [d3] etc.}) 9... b6 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black wants to finish development.} ({An attack on the queen with} 9... Ndb4 {is met by} 10. Qb1 {and the knight will be chased away with [a3].}) 10. a3 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Ga3b4,Rd5b4,Rc6b4] White takes the time to neutralize the threat of ...[Nb4]. With a queen on [c2] and not on [b1], it's possible to castle long.} ({The immediate} 10. Ng5 {is met by} f5 {, so White waits for Black's ...[Bb7] and then [Ng5] is more serious, as ...[f5] won't work in view of the hanging pawn on [e6].}) 10... f5 {Black decides to stop any possible attack on his king.} ({After} 10... Bb7 11. Ng5 {is dangerous.}) 11. Bb5 {[%cal Gb5c6] White can no longer attack on the kingside, so he switches to positional means. This means the capture on [d5] followed by [d4], just like in the theoretical chapter, only this time with a black pawn on [f5], which makes Black's position less compact.} Bb7 12. Nxd5 exd5 ({Black avoids} 12... Qxd5 13. Bc4 {when the pawn on [e6] requires attention.}) 13. d4 {[%csl Bd5] The standard move, fixing the black pawn on [d5].} Rc8 14. dxc5 bxc5 15. O-O {[%csl Bc5,Bd5,Bf5][%cal Gf1d1,Ga1c1,Gc1c5,Gd1d5] White's play against the hanging pawns is fairly straight-forward: place the rooks on the semi-open files and probe for further weaknesses, or force one of the pawns to advance and establish a blockade. The peculiarity of this position is the white pawn on [h4] and the black pawn on [f5]. It works in White's favor because the [f5]-pawn requires protection, and it somewhat weakens the black king.} Bf6 {Black wants to neutralize the strong bishop on [b2].} 16. Rfd1 {[%cal Gd1d5] White continues with his plan.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5,Ge7f5] The knight covers both pawns on [d5] and [f5], but it's a purely defensive piece now, without any active possibilities.} 17. Bxf6 Rxf6 18. g3 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Ge3f4,Gg3f4] White stabilizes the structure on the kingside, at the same time preventing ...[f4].} ({There was no real need for this move, though, as White could have continued with the planned} 18. Rac1 {.}) 18... Ba6 $6 {The exchange of the light-squared bishop means that the knight on [e7] is doomed to passivity.} ({It was better to keep the bishop and play} 18... Qb6 {, with more active piece play.}) 19. Bxa6 Rxa6 20. Qc3 {[%csl Bc5,Bd5,Ye7,Bf5][%cal Ge7d5,Ge7f5] With less pieces on the board, Black has problems due to the over-extended pawns. To compare, with the [f5]-pawn on [f7] and the knight on [f6], he would be fine, but now he is doomed to passive defense.} Rb6 21. Rac1 {[%csl Yc5,Yd5][%cal Gc1c5,Gd1d5,Bf3e1,Be1d3,Gd3c5,Bd3f4,Bf4d5,Gf3e5,Ge5d3] White's heavy pieces are ideally placed. He only needs to improve the position of the knight and this will be done via [e5] e1 and [d3].} Qd6 22. Ne5 {[%cal Ge5d3]} Rb7 23. Nd3 c4 {Black cannot stand the pressure and advances one of the pawns.} 24. bxc4 Rxc4 ({After} 24... dxc4 25. Ne5 {, the pawn on [c4] will be lost.}) 25. Qe5 {[%csl Yd5,Yf5] Now White plays against an IQP. Black's defense is further exacerbated by the weaknesses created by the [f5]-pawn.} Qxe5 26. Nxe5 Rxc1 27. Rxc1 g6 28. Rc5 {[%csl Ya7,Yd5][%cal Gc5d5,Gc5a5,Ga5a7] The endgame is practically untenable for Black. He must stay passive to defend all the weaknesses and such positions are always lost in practice.} Kg7 29. Ra5 {[%csl Ba5,Bb7][%cal Ga5a7,Ga5d5] Compare the activity of the rooks.} Kf6 {[%cal Rf6e5]} 30. Nd3 {[%csl Yd5][%cal Gd3f4,Gf4d5]} Rc7 31. Ra6+ {[%csl Rf6][%cal Ga6f6] Pushing the king back.} Kg7 32. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4d5,Gf4e6,Ge6c7,Ge6g7] Threatening [Ne6].} Rd7 33. Kf1 {[%cal Gf1e2,Ge2d3,Gd3d4] White's pieces are active to the maximum, so it's time for the king to come and decide the game.} Ng8 34. Ne6+ {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge6g7] It was also possible to continue the centralization of the king, but White finds a forcing way to pin Black down to the defense of the [a7]-pawn.} Kf7 35. Nd4 {[%csl Ya7][%cal Gd4b5,Gb5a7,Ga6a7]} Ne7 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Ge7c8,Gc8a7,Gd7a7] The only way to defend the [a7]-pawn is to rush with the knight to [c8].} 36. Nb5 {[%cal Gb5a7,Ga6a7]} Nc8 {[%csl Ga7][%cal Gc8a7,Gd7a7]} 37. a4 {[%cal Ga4b5] Improving ad infinitum.} Rb7 38. Rc6 Ne7 {[%cal Re7c6]} 39. Ra6 Nc8 40. Rc6 Ne7 41. Rd6 {After repeating moves to reach move 40, White ties down the knight to the defense of the [d5]-pawn.} Rb6 {Black cracks. He should have stayed passive, but then the White king would have marched into the center with decisive effect.} 42. Rd7 {[%csl Ya7][%cal Gd7a7,Gb5a7]} a6 43. Nc3 {[%csl Ye7,Yd5,Yb6][%cal Gc3d5,Gd7e7,Gd5b6,Gd5e7,Yf7e7] With the indefensible threat of [Rxe7] followed by [Nxd5].} *

