{🏆Tata Steel-A Wijk aan Zee, Round January White: Elo – Black: Elo.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. Qc2 e6 6. b3 Bd6 7. Bb2 O-O 8. Be2 Re8 9. O-O e5 10. cxd5 Nxd5 ({As mentioned in the theoretical part, this recapture is a must as} 10... cxd5 $6 11. Nb5 {wins the bishop pair for White.}) 11. Ne4 {[%cal Ge4d6]} Bc7 12. Ng3 {[%csl Bf5][%cal Gg3f5] A standard knight maneuver in these positions. The knight from [g3] targets the [f5]-square.} Nf8 {[%cal Gc8f5]} 13. a3 {[%csl Bb4][%cal Gd5b4,Gb3b4,Ga3b4] Stopping any ...[Nb4] ideas and intending a queenside expansion with [b4].} a5 {[%cal Ga5b4] Black stops [b4].} 14. d4 {[%cal Gd4e5,Gf3e5,Gb2e5] The central break gives White the initiative.} Ng6 {[%cal Gg6e5,Gc7e5,Ge8e5]} ({In case of} 14... exd4 15. Nxd4 {followed by [Rad1], [Bc4] White has excellent central control. Black now defends the pawn on [e5], but he isn't able to hold the tension after White's next move.}) 15. Bd3 {[%csl Ye5][%cal Gd3g6,Gf3e5] Threatening the simple [Bxg6] and [Nxe5], winning a pawn.} exd4 {There was no other choice for Black.} 16. Nxd4 {[%csl Bf5,Yg7][%cal Gd4f5,Gg3f5,Gd3f5,Gb2g7] These positions tend to favor White as his pieces have more scope for active play. Especially the [f5]-square is of importance.} Bg4 $6 {Black's light-squared bishop isn't an easy piece to develop, but this allows White to obtain a big advantage.} ({It was better to play} 16... Be5 {, trying to oppose the strong bishop on [b2].}) 17. Bf5 $1 {[%cal Gf5g4]} Nf6 {[%cal Gf6g4]} ({The bishop cannot be exchanged as after} 17... Bxf5 18. Ndxf5 f6 19. Nh5 {, Black loses the pawn on [g7].}) 18. f3 $6 {[%csl Ye3] Not bad, but somewhat weakening.} ({It was much stronger to attack the bishop from the other side with} 18. h3 $1 Bh5 19. Nxh5 Nxh5 20. Rad1 {with a fantastic position for White, who has the more active pieces and the bishop pair.}) 18... Bh5 ({Black had the tactical opportunity with} 18... Nd5 {here, thanks to White's last move that weakened the [e3]-pawn.}) 19. Rae1 {[%cal Ge1e3]} Nf8 20. Nxh5 Nxh5 21. f4 {[%csl Bb2,Bf5,Be3] White is still much better. The bishop pair and the central majority are important factors in his favor.} Bb6 22. Bg4 $2 {White spoils everything in one move.} ({The simple} 22. Bd3 {kept everything together.}) 22... Nf6 $1 {[%cal Rf6g4]} 23. Bf3 Nd5 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Rd5e3,Re8e3] The knight transfer from the rim to the excellent central square from where it attacks the [e3]-pawn solves Black's problems. The position is equal now.} 24. Bxd5 Qxd5 25. Nf5 {[%csl Yg7][%cal Gf5g7,Gb2g7]} f6 26. Rd1 Qe4 27. Qxe4 Rxe4 {[%csl Ye3][%cal Rb6e3,Re4e3] Black still attacks the pawn that White unnecessarily weakened with his 18th move.} 28. Rf3 g6 29. Nh6+ Kg7 30. Ng4 {[%cal Gg4f6,Gb2f6]} Kf7 {[%cal Rb6e3,Re4e3]} 31. Nh6+ {[%csl Rf7][%cal Gh6f7]} ({Taking the perpetual check as} 31. Nxf6 Rxe3 {leads nowhere.}) 31... Kg7 32. Ng4 Kf7 33. Nh6+ {[%csl Rf7]} Ke7 34. Ng8+ {[%csl Re7]} Kf7 {[%cal Rf7g8]} *

