{🏆Geneva Grand Prix Round July White: Elo – Black: Elo.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e3 Nxc3 6. dxc3 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gc1e3] White wants to play [e4] and [Be3].} Bf5 {[%csl Be4][%cal Gf5e4,Ge3e4] Black wants to prevent [e4].} 8. Nd2 {[%cal Ge3e4] Now [e4] cannot be prevented but White was forced to place the knight on [d2] in order to achieve it, thus slowing down his development.} Nc6 9. e4 Be6 10. Kc2 {[%cal Ga2a4,Gd2b3,Gd2c4,Gf1c4,Gc4b5,Gc1e3] White slowly untangles. His play lies on the queenside and is pretty automatic. The pawn will come to [a4], the knight to [b3] or [c4], the light-squared bishop to [c4] or [b5] the exchange of light-squared bishops is good for White, as that leaves the light squares on the queenside like [b5], [a6] and [c6] with less protection and the dark-squared bishop will come to [e3] or [f4].} g6 {The bishop will be passive on [g7], but there is no other option to develop it once the other one prevented the movement of the e-pawn.} 11. Bc4 {[%cal Gc4e6] White seeks the exchange of the light-squared bishops.} Bd7 ({The exchange on c4 after} 11... Bxc4 12. Nxc4 {is pleasant for White. He tempts Black to expand with} b5 $6 13. Ne3 Bg7 {only to attack the exposed queenside structure with} 14. a4 $1 b4 15. Nc4 {, with an eternal knight on [c4].}) 12. Nb3 {[%cal Gb3c5,Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gc1e3,Ge3c5] White puts pressure on the queenside. The pawn on [c5] is attacked and the knight from [b3] also supports the pawn's march to [a5]. In the meantime, the bishop can also be developed to [e3].} b6 13. a4 {[%cal Ga4a5,Ga5b6,Ga1a8] With the idea to further advance with [a5].} Ne5 {[%cal Re5c4]} 14. Bb5 {White again seeks the exchange of the light-squared bishops and this time succeeds.} a6 15. Bxd7+ Nxd7 16. Be3 {[%csl Yb6,Yc5][%cal Ga4a5,Ga5b6,Ge3c5,Gb3c5] Black weakened his queenside by ...[a6], and he is still lagging behind with the development of the bishop on [f8]. The opening was a success for White, but it is difficult to pinpoint where exactly Black went wrong. It is likely an accumulation of minor inaccuracies coupled with the general character of the position – it is simply easier to play with White. What follows is a very good illustration of how to improve your position by playing natural moves. In other words, White's position plays by itself.} e6 {[%cal Gf8c5,Gd7c5] Black defends the [c5]-pawn in order to be able to meet [a5] with ...[b5], without losing the pawn on [c5].} 17. Rhd1 O-O-O 18. Nd2 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Gd2c4,Gc4b6,Gc4d6] The knight is transferred to the ideal [c4]-square.} Be7 19. Nc4 {[%csl Bc4]} Kb7 20. a5 $1 {[%csl Yb6][%cal Ga5b6,Gc4b6] Typical softening of the Black structure as Black cannot play ...[b5].} Rhf8 {A sad necessity to allow the wrecking of the queenside structure.} ({Black cannot play} 20... b5 $2 {as} 21. Nd6+ Bxd6 22. Rxd6 {wins for White as Black is completely tied down: he cannot defend the pawns on [a6], [c5] and the knight on [d7] all at the same time.}) 21. axb6 Nxb6 {[%csl Ba6,Bc5] Black is positionally lost already, with no compensation for the pawn weaknesses.} 22. Na5+ {[%csl Rb7]} Kc7 23. Bf4+ {[%csl Rc7]} Bd6 24. Bh6 {[%cal Gh6f8]} Rfe8 25. Nb3 {[%csl Ya6,Yc5][%cal Ga1a6,Gb3c5,Gh6e3,Ge3c5] White systematically attacks Black's weaknesses until Black cannot manage to defend everything in time.} Ra8 26. Be3 {[%cal Gb3c5,Ge3c5]} Nd7 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gd7c5]} 27. Ra5 {[%csl Yc5][%cal Ga5c5,Gb3c5,Ge3c5] Piling up the pressure.} Kc6 {[%cal Gc6c5]} 28. Rda1 {[%csl Ya6][%cal Ga1a6] Now the pawn on [a6] is attacked.} Kb6 {[%cal Gb6a6,Gb6c5]} 29. R5a4 {[%csl Bc4][%cal Gb3a5,Ga5c4,Gc4b6,Gc4d6] Freeing the [a5]-square for the knight transfer [Na5]-[c4].} Rec8 {Weakening the defense along the d-file, but it's inevitable for a player to crack under so much pressure.} 30. Na5 $1 {[%cal Ga5c4]} Be7 31. Rb4+ {[%csl Yc5,Rb6] A neat finish. After 31...Kc7 32.Rb7 Kd8 33.Rd1 Rc7 34.Nc6 , White wins the bishop on [e7].} *

