{🏆Linares Round February White: Elo – Black: Elo.} 1. c4 Nc6 2. Nc3 e5 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. e4 Be6 {[%cal Gd8d7,Gd7h3,Re6h3] Black plans a quick ...[Qd7] and ...[Bh3] to exchange the bishop on [g2]. However, this plan neglects development and White manages to expand in the center.} 7. Nge2 Qd7 8. Nd5 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Gd5c7] The knight on [d5] ties Black down to the defense of the pawn on [c7]. This means that if Black is to implement the plan of ...[Bh3], he must first get rid of the knight on [d5].} Nce7 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gc7c6,Yc6d4] Black plans ...[c6], but weakens the control of the central [d4]-square, which White immediately takes advantage of.} 9. d4 $1 {[%csl Bc4,Bd4,Be4]} c6 10. Ne3 {[%csl Ye7,Yg8][%cal Gd4d5] With more space, White keeps more pieces on the board, especially as the knight on [e7] is an awkward piece with no prospects that also blocks the development of the other knight on [g8].} Bh3 {Black finally gets to play this move, but after the simple} 11. O-O Bxg2 12. Kxg2 {The exchange of the bishops didn't bring Black much relief.} exd4 {[%cal Rd4e3]} 13. Nxd4 h5 {[%cal Rh5h4] Black wants to be more active.} 14. a4 {[%cal Ga1a3] Kasparov finds a curious way to include the rook in play via the third rank.} ({The simple} 14. Nf3 {, stopping [h4], would have kept White's positional advantage that consists of more space and the weak pawn on [d6].}) 14... Nh6 ({After} 14... h4 15. Nf3 {, White keeps Black at bay.}) 15. Ra3 O-O-O {Black plays aggressively. Castling short was also possible, though in both cases White keeps all the advantages.} 16. a5 {[%cal Ga5a6] Intending [a6].} h4 {[%cal Rh4g3,Rh8h1] Both players go for each other's kings.} 17. a6 {[%cal Ga6b7]} b6 {Black cannot allow the opening of the a-file and the weakening of his queenside after [axb7].} 18. Nf3 {[%cal Gf3h4] White brings back the knight to the defense.} hxg3 19. fxg3 {[%cal Gf1f8] White keeps the h-file closed and opens the f-file.} ({After} 19. hxg3 $6 f5 $1 {, Black obtains strong initiative.}) 19... f6 $2 {Too passive and out of character compared to Black's previous play.} ({The move} 19... f5 {was called for, with unclear play after} 20. exf5 gxf5 21. Kh1 {.}) 20. c5 {Kasparov immediately uses the moment to advance his own attack.} ({It was possible to prepare this with} 20. b4 {first.}) 20... dxc5 ({Opening of the b-file is fatal after} 20... bxc5 $2 21. Rb3 {.}) 21. Qb3 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gd1d8,Ge3c4,Gc4b6] Introducing ideas like [Rd1] and [Nc4], threatening [Nxb6].} Kb8 22. Rd1 {[%csl Yd7]} Qc8 23. Nc4 {[%csl Gg7,Gh6][%cal Gc4b6] White sacrificed a pawn, but has all the fun on the queenside, while Black's kingside play and the bishop on [g7] and knight on [h6] are out of play.} Rxd1 24. Qxd1 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Gd1d6]} Nf7 {[%csl Bd6][%cal Gf7d6] Covering the [d6]-square.} 25. Rd3 {[%cal Gd3d7] Threatening [Rd7].} g5 {[%csl Bf4][%cal Gg5f4,Gc1f4,Gf4b8]} ({After} 25... Rd8 26. Rxd8 Qxd8 27. Qb3 {, White threatens [Nxb6], which is also an attack on the knight on [f7].}) 26. Qb3 {[%csl Yf7][%cal Gc4b6,Gb3f7] The move 26.Rd7 was also possible, but White keeps more tension in the position. The immediate threat is [Nxb6].} Qe6 27. Be3 {[%cal Ge3c5] Attacking the pawn on [c5].} Nc8 28. Nxb6 $5 {[%cal Gb3e6] White sacrifices a piece and transposes to an endgame where he continues the attack!} Qxb3 29. Nd7+ {[%csl Rb8][%cal Gd7b8]} Kc7 30. Rxb3 Kxd7 31. Rb7+ Ke6 32. Bxc5 {[%cal Gf3d4] Threatening [Nd4]. White is a piece down, but all his pieces are active while Black's are lacking in coordination.} Bf8 33. Nd4+ {[%csl Re6]} Ke5 34. Nxc6+ {[%csl Re5]} Kxe4 35. Bxa7 {[%csl Ba6][%cal Ga6a8] Now White has a very dangerous passed pawn on [a6].} Nfd6 36. Rc7 Nxa7 37. Rxa7 Nc4 38. Ra8 {[%cal Ga8h8]} Bg7 39. Ra7 {[%csl Yg7]} Ne3+ {[%csl Rg2]} ({Black could have repeated, when White likely would have continued with} 39... Bf8 40. b4 {.}) 40. Kg1 Rg8 $4 {The fatal 40th move.} ({It was better to finally activate the rook with} 40... Rc8 {, when Black shouldn't lose.}) 41. Re7+ $2 {[%csl Re4]} ({Kasparov misses the win, which was within grasp after} 41. Rd7 $1 {, cutting off the black king from the queenside. Black gets a second chance now.}) 41... Kd3 $4 {Which he misses.} ({The saving move was} 41... Kd5 42. Nb4+ Kc4 {and Black should save the game.}) 42. a7 {[%cal Ga7a8] Now it's over.} Rc8 43. Kf2 {[%cal Ge7e3,Gf2e3] The king moves away from the first rank, avoiding mating threats.} Nd1+ {[%csl Rf2]} 44. Kf3 g4+ {[%csl Rf3]} 45. Kxg4 f5+ {[%csl Rg4]} 46. Kf3 Bxb2 47. Rd7+ {[%csl Rd3]} Kc2 48. Rd8 *

