{🏆Paris Immopar rapid, Round 3, November 1990.} 1. c4 f5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Be7 5. O-O O-O 6. Nc3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 {[%csl Ba3,Bb3,Bd3,Be3][%cal Gd2d3,Gb2b3,Ga2a3] White starts to build the wall of pawns on the third rank.} Kh8 9. b3 Nc6 {Usually in the Stonewall Black places a pawn on [c6], but this doesn't affect White's play. In fact, some moves later, a black pawn will appear on [c6].} 10. Bb2 Be6 11. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gf3d4,Ge2d4,Ga2a3,Gb3b4] White's play is simple: use the [d4] and [f4] squares for the knights and advance on the queenside with [a3] and [b4].} Bg8 12. d3 {Of course, White will never put a pawn on [d4]!} Qd7 13. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4] Preparing [b4]. Note how Black developed, but has no targets or constructive plan.} Bd6 14. Qc2 Rae8 ({If} 14... a5 {, White can still prepare [b4] by} 15. Bc3 {and then [Rfb1] or [Qb2].}) 15. b4 {[%cal Ge2d4] White slowly expands while Black can only wait.} Ng4 16. Ned4 {[%cal Gd4c6] Threatening to take on [c6] and double Black's c-pawns.} Nce5 17. Rac1 {[%csl Yc7][%cal Gc1c8] Just improving the position by placing a rook on the semi-open c-file.} c6 {Here comes the 'proper' Stonewall formation.} 18. Bc3 {[%cal Gc2b2,Gb2h8]} Nxf3+ 19. Nxf3 Re7 20. Qb2 {[%csl Bc5,Yd6,Be5][%cal Gb2h8,Gc3d4,Gd4c5,Gc5d6] White has excellent control of the long diagonal and with a black pawn on [c6] eyes the [c5]-square with the [Bd4]-[c5] maneuver. The exchange of the dark-squared bishops is in White's favor, as Black's bishop is a piece that defends the dark squares weakened by the Stonewall formation: [c5] and [e5] in this case.} Qe8 21. Bd4 {[%csl Ya7][%cal Gd4a7]} a6 {Further weakening the dark squares, but there was no choice. Playing ...[b6] would weaken the [c6]-pawn.} 22. Bc5 {[%csl Yd6][%cal Gc5f8] White achieves the desirable exchange of the dark-squared bishops.} Rf6 {[%cal Gf6d6]} 23. Bxd6 Rxd6 24. Qd4 {[%csl Bd4] Now the queen takes over from the bishop. White's plan still remains the same – advance on the queenside.} Bf7 25. a4 {[%cal Gb4b5,Gb5a6,Gb5c6] In a minority attack White plans [b5] to create a weakness in Black's queenside structure by taking on [c6] or [a6].} Bh5 26. Rb1 {[%cal Gb4b5] Preparing [b5], even though the break was possible immediately.} Nh6 27. b5 {[%cal Gb5c6,Gb5a6]} axb5 28. axb5 Bxf3 {Black gets rid of another pair of light pieces, but that doesn't ease his defense.} 29. Bxf3 Nf7 30. Bh5 {[%csl Yc6,Bg1,Bh8][%cal Gh5e8,Gb5c6] Kasparov decides to transpose to a position with only heavy pieces on the board. He banks on his safer king and the weakness on [c6].} Rh6 31. Bxf7 Rxf7 32. bxc6 bxc6 33. Rb6 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb6c6,Gf1c1,Gc1c6] The risk-free and completely safe play continues. White piles down against the [c6]-pawn.} Rf8 34. Qc5 {[%csl Yc6][%cal Gb6c6,Gc5f8] By latching onto the rook on [f8] White prevents the activation of the black queen.} g5 {[%cal Rf5f4] After shuffling for the whole game and ending up outplayed, Short becomes desperate and lunges forward. He sacrifices the pawn on [c6], but gets nothing in return.} 35. Rc1 f4 36. exf4 gxf4 37. Rxc6 Rxc6 38. Qxc6 Qxc6 39. Rxc6 {[%csl Yd5] The rook endgame is winning for White as the [d5]-pawn is another weakness that Black cannot defend long-term.} Ra8 40. Rf6 $6 {[%cal Gf6f3]} ({This stops ...f3, but it was possible to play} 40. g4 f3 41. h3 {and the king will come out via [h2] to [g3].}) 40... fxg3 41. hxg3 Ra3 42. Rf3 {[%csl Yf3] The rook is passive on [f3] and this gives Black saving chances.} Kg7 $6 ({The last chance was} 42... Ra1+ 43. Kg2 Rd1 {, trying to maximize the activity of the rook.}) 43. Kg2 d4 44. Kh3 $2 {Curiously enough, after this Black can draw.} ({The king had to go in the other direction with} 44. Kf1 Ra1+ 45. Ke2 {and White will combine the threat or [Rf4], attacking the pawn on [d4], with the idea to break free with the king via the queenside.}) 44... h5 {[%cal Gh5g4] This stops [Kg4] and will force a further exchange of pawns.} 45. Kh4 Kg6 {[%csl Yh4]} 46. g4 {The only way to make progress, but the game should end in a draw anyway.} hxg4 47. Kxg4 {[%cal Gg4f4,Gf4e4] White wants to get the king to [e4], but Black prevents it with his next two moves.} Ra2 {[%cal Ga2e2,Ge2e8]} 48. Kf4 Re2 {[%csl Yf4][%cal Ye2e8] The rook cuts off the king along the e-file.} 49. Rg3+ {[%csl Rg6]} Kf6 50. Rg2 Ke6 51. Kf3 {[%cal Gf3e2]} Re1 52. Rg4 {[%csl Yd4][%cal Gg4d4]} Kd5 {[%cal Gd5d4] The only, but sufficient way to defend the pawn.} 53. Rg5+ {[%csl Rd5]} Kd6 54. Ra5 Ke6 55. Ra2 Kd5 56. Kf4 Kd6 57. Kf5 Kc5 58. f4 {It appears that White made some progress, but it's only optical.} Kb4 $4 {Just awful, letting his own king to be cut off. Just keeping the king on the d-file was sufficient to draw.} 59. Rc2 {[%csl Yb4][%cal Yc2c8,Yc2c1] The threat is [Rc4xd4] and without a king, Black cannot resist anymore.} *

